More. More. More. I - well I was born in 1894, he must have been thirty-four mustn't he. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you know where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. He - he came as I told you from that area. Where they - they came - my grandfather come from, where - out in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
 there where - Shenfield, that's it. You see - they - my grandparents I've heard 'em say - were - great - grandparents used to change the horses for the mail. There used to be a - when that mail went from - Whitechapel, that's the Eastern
 District Office. When that left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 12}}}twelve o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 at night, on the back of that motor, I can see it now - they used to run to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ipswich{\*\xmlclose}. That was the final run, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ipswich{\*\xmlclose} I think. When they ran on. And they used to change them at Romford, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - and - I forget the other places now. They'd leave from here. Four in hand. The man drove four in hand and there was postmen working inside that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 mail van}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 . It was like a stagecoach see inside. Sorting out as they went along. And that went from there {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 12}}}twelve o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 every night and that - and I remember going there - when I was a boy, watched that go off, they used to say, you come and see the mail go off. Before we - we wasn't interested in the mail van, we was interested in horses, four horses see. See,
 because we were all more or less animal lovers, horses. Dad was a horseman, my grandfathers - and as we grew up we all got - that way inclined like you - today you know everybody's got motor and aren't they? You see, the kids follow their dad, they learn
 all about their cars playing with their dad's car. And of course when they grow up they want a car. It's - it's instinct. It was horses, there was no cars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was your father's occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He was a carman of - of - a driver. Used to drive thre
e horses, yes. See, and we all - were all brought up - more or less with animals we were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your father ever have any other jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that his job all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. That was only job. My mum was a - when she was young was a cigar maker.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes. Then when - of course when the children come along they stopped don't they, they - automatically stop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That was a good job, that was an apprenticed job wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh she was apprenticed, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was your father ever out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, never. Never. Always worked. Yes. But he was very poorly paid. That work. See they worked in the - he was a City carman and a licensed City carman at that. My grandfather was a City carman and I went to work with 'em and I was a City carman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What does that mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
You drive your horse in the City - you've got a special licence by the police. The - they used to - we used to have to go - every Bank Holiday - I don't know, Easter I think, I thin
k it was Easter, just before Easter we used to go to - Guild Hall and a man came out with a - a little furnace on - like a blacksmith's, they'd pump it up; and he'd put an iron in this little furnace - and they stick on the side of the van, they brand the
 
van - with a different - monogram each year. All round the van. And - then you got a - size and - say the number of your van is one, the licence is a brass one, and that's put underneath - on another part of the van. That brass number is a police license.
 And the police - that allows you to stand in the City. See, you was licensed by the police.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you carry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
All goods, all sorts of goods. You worked for all different firms, printers and - anybody you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 This was a private enterprise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, in the City - in the City they wanted to hire a van for - do a little job for a big firm - paper merchant }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  you to take a load of paper or pick up a load of paper for 'em you went over to - where the paper depot was, it was over Ol
d Kent Road on the - you pick the paper up from that paper place, all the paper came up from Kent, Snodland I think the name of the place was, where they printed the paper, or made the paper, and you went there and got their loads and took 'em to the - di
fferent firms that had - bought 'em see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much do you think he'd earn for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, the average - the average when I went to work with him, the top price for a single horse van was about - twenty-seven shillings. That was after the 1912 strike.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Who went on strike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The carmen did. Yes. All the carmen - of course that was the beginning of the transport workers you see, the carmen. They become the - the starting of the trade unionism, and - and after - they used to work for about a p
ound a week some places you see, and time was no - you never got paid overtime. Very seldom, you went in at six in the morning, finished {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 12}}}twelve o'clock{\*\xmlclose} at night, that was a day's work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your father sometimes would work as late as that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, 
yes, yes. Yes. I have, I've been - I - went to - say we had a - lad - in the City there was a big firm in Gresham Street, Staling Lane, they used to do all - asylums. And you took the goods to the asylum for 'em, with your van, well you was out best part 
'til {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 12}}}twelve o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 always when you had that job. Because if you went to Epsom - you had three deliveries at Epsom, at the different asylums, time you got home it was - was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 12}}}twelve o'clock{\*\xmlclose} at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So it was a hard life at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. YES? YES. You had to start - get up at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 17}}}five o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 in the morning to go to work. And before you go to work you cleaned your horse. And then you went out to work - hungry perhaps, but you went to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would your father stable these horses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh he
re - local - they used to have - big stables here in the - here, what they call Cable Street, the bottom of Cable Street, the Highway, was all - everybody had stables Two or three hundred horses some had you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You paid weekly for the stabling did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well no, the - firm paid that didn't they, it was the firm he worked for had that stable. You only drove the horses for 'em. See? They had their horse - they had their own - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 furriers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 , they had their own - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 harness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  maker, they had their own - everybody, these big firms, they had to have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So did your father work for a special firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 All the time, the same firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, he worked for - he worked for a firm for a great number of years in Stepney Green and they sold out to a
 bigger firm. And this big firm - took that City office where they were - and all the orders there, you understand. See, they had two offices in the City, so this firm - took their city offices and all the - all the work went in there name after that, the
y bought the business of that little man up, I don't suppose they paid a lot of money that time for it. You see?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you know where your mother came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, she came - my - my mum was born here in Stepney as well. Her dad was a publican. He ha
d a - a pub which they closed. Up there - near Whitechapel church, and they closed the pub, in later years - it was a Jewish synagogue - like - what do you call it - Talmudtora where they learned the children to speak Yiddish, and Hebrew. And any time I w
ent through that Greenfield Street - it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 court way}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 run from Greenfield Street to Plumbers Row, and I - and of course specially when I was Air Raid Warden I was always round - about, see I - I was a cyclist and I used to have to go to the top of Greenfi
eld Street we had a depot, a stores, the wardens. And I used to go to - that had been a pub as well. But my - grandfather's pub was - like a Jewish Talmudtora but it all got burnt out during the war, with the fire bombs and - and years it lay derelict. No
w it's different altogether round, it's all built on you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you know how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, well - my mum and dad were about the same age. See - I go by my age - I was born in 1894 and my dad and mum were about - 18 - 1860, that's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They were in their thirties when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did she ever work after marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, I don't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose with a big family she couldn't really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 As I say, that - when - when I be
come a - a - what I call a - helpmate to come in with the money I used to go out and - right from a kid bring her in money, in the City, go selling papers and things. Used to do that. And when I was fifteen I was a lord because I - I - told you I found a 
-
 little - goldmine in that old - factory up where we - I was apprenticed. We took the - I saw in the dustbin old bits of brass, see. And we was always learnt to - be what you call jackdaws, find things you see. And soon as I saw that brass - I knew we cou
l
d sell it. That old brass. So I says to this boy - he asked me one day what I was doing down there. And - I told him, I said, do you want to come partners with me, we tipped the dustbin right over, we'll sort it out and we'll put all the dirt back and we'
ll keep the metal ourselves and we'll sell it. And of course he was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 boy and he knew the tricks as well. So we did that, and then we did that every day. We had a little brush and a shovel there what we hid away from the dustmen, they wouldn't see it. Down this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 court way}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 - from - we used to take the - brass, it was brass or copper - pieces, they made all fittings for electrical fittings. And they used to pick these pieces out, screws and - bolts or whatever they were, little pieces, and - at the end o
f the week the man used to - pay us. He - we used to take them in as much as - say fourteen, fifteen pound of a night see as we went home, walked by, we walked - all the way from Clerkenwell here to Stepney.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You carried fourteen or fifteen pounds of this brass?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh that was nothing when you were - kids. And - we used to put it in that rag shop there in Shoreditch, there was a place in Shoreditch there - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Church Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And we used to - put it - he used to put it on the wall for us. Then the Friday night when we went in - he paid us, that man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much would you get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - I've had nearly a hundredweight in there, hundred pound odd - you know, in weight. Well we used to get threepence a pound that time. Well if you had a - say - fourpenc
e a pound, hundred pound fourpence a pound you see - you had four hundred pence didn't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 It was a lot of money at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, it was a week's work. See, and we was - quite happy, and it cost us nothing. All we had to do was to carry it. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you give any of that money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, definitely. Yes. Then I had stopped money for myself. 'Cos when - I didn't go into work Saturday, Friday - Friday night we finish five days that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That's when you were at the shoemaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, and then I - went straight from - never came home, I went straight to Houndsditch and bought - different things like matches or - postcards, whatever were - we wanted. I could buy little electric - tem little - sparklers for the - for
 the - everybody bought those that time, it was a novelty you see, ha'penny sparkler. Used to buy about - there was twelve in a box, we used to sell 'em for sixpence. Those -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you buy them for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They used to cost us about - two three a 
box. Two and ninepence a dozen I think they were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd take them up to the City?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Take 'em up the City, yes, and we'd - we'd - specially at Christmas time or - fire - work time, what do you call it, November and Christmas. Christmas time they u
sed to - show - go in the - in the gents part - amongst the gent - gentry, like the working class, say, any sparklers, see. And we used to have to hide them from the police 'cos the police didn't want you to have them. In the City you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Over the fire. See? It was fire prevention. And they - we used to - we'd have newspapers under our arm and - and the sparklers in our pockets see. Well - and matches as well see, a box of matches sir, if they didn't want sparklers or they want a 
newspaper. And you used to get a customer now and then. Of course matches that time was very very cheap. We used to buy - I used to buy - well it's - about - from - you could get good matches sevenpence a gross. A gross boxes, yes. You sold 'em - penny a 
dozen, you couldn't earn a profit. They was only - you - every shop I went to when I was a child we used to say - farthings worth of matches please, and you'd get three boxes. Three boxes for a farthing, now you've got to pay threepence a box for them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you sell quite a lot of these matches then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, yes, different where - we used to go round the Stock Exchange, with all the gentry there. Yes, the - with no clothes on hardly, we never had no boots nor socks on, and - matches sir, a
nd they wouldn't touch - they didn't want six for a penny, we used - they'd sell them six for a penny, and we was - look at the money we was earning, that time, we'd sell them six a penny, instead of - see tuppence a dozen that was wasn't it. But - knew t
hat they wouldn't take six, they'd only want one they would, well that was - the other was all profit wasn't it. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 On top of that you'd be selling your papers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, we'd have - we done all sorts of - scheming. Carry - carry a person's luggage. Say we saw a person coming out of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Fenchurch Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 with a parcel going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. They never all had cabs and never went - cabs, used to say, carry your parcel sir? And - carry the parcel over to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}
 station for 'em or - or - wherever they wanted to go see, to transfer from - from the Tilbury railway to the - South Eastern Railway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would they give you for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
They'd give you sixpence or perhaps they'd give you more, and you used to - and when they give you sixpence you was - cor you thought you'd done a - a windfall hadn't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So you really could make as much as your father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 More. Yes, yes, more, more. More. Many a time I've done that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So your mother in a way relied on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, we was - we 
all - and I - and me being a - what I call a - a little run about, I - I done all those tricks. And a friend of mine learnt me that in his - taking me with him in the City. Used to get a barrow out - this is honest truth, used to go and hire a barrow in t
he {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose} here in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Redmonds Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 here at the back, tuppence a day. He'd keep it out all day that barrow you could. And we used to go to Billingsgate market, Leadenhall Market, we'd fill it up with boxes and - and load it up and fetch it home, you know what
 I mean, load the - tuppence a day. He - he was like a lord 'cos I pulled the barrow all the time, he didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was in these boxes though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Empty boxes, like - fruit boxes, any boxes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you do with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Fire wood for mum. 
See it was all - it was all timber wasn't it, they - any - any wood see that was all timber that time. See, if you wanted to buy a - a orange box here in - off your local fruiterer he'd want threepence for that. And we could get it for nothing we ain't go
i
ng to give him threepence were - were we. And we used to get a lot of it. And we used to get some lovely boxes in Billingsgate, only they were damp, and they smelt, but they was - it was good wood, you'd get as much as you like in Billingsgate, wood you c
ould.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was everybody doing this or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well there wasn't - wasn't everybody doing it but there - there was lots doing it. Yes. That next brother to me, Sid, he - he worked for a man in - Leadenhall Market - in - he used to fetch home all the empt
ies. He worked for a butcher, helped a butcher, and they had a cellar underneath the shop - with all the - they were shipping butchers and all the greengrocery boxes and that - and then he worked for a fruiterer there, and all the green - all the boxes wh
a
t he - he had - took his barrow up there, he loaded up his barrow from the - and they was glad to get rid of it see. Like they are today in the City, they've got - in the City they put - you see up cases, well that wasn't on when I was a kid. They kept th
em theirself. They paid a lot of money for 'em and they didn't give 'em away so easy. Here and there they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So you'd be out all day doing all this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What time would you get back at night?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh - twelve, one o'clock 
in the morning, we didn't worry about time those days. You understand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Didn't your mother worry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no. You see, I'll tell you something, when - when I was young - all the pubs was open 'til half past twelve at night. You come along the - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Road
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Whitechapel Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - every other - house as I call it was a pub wasn't it. Two or three yards there's pubs all the way along. And they were all lit up and people were about. But today it's dead now after -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You mean it was really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 livelier}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, it was lit up, yes, and - and then - a lot of pubs you know - outside the pub instead of you seeing electric light now, it was all - fancy arches of gas lights. Ordinary gas - little gas flame. Gaskets as you call it. They was lit up in diff
erent signs. In lots of places. There was no electric. It was gas, gas mantles came first, then the - the jets came first, that school I remember was all lit with gas jets, not even mantles, when I went to it. There was no electric light, now it's all ele
ctric and all them long glass lights they've got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So were you allowed to go into pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, yes, they didn't stop you. You was - I was a little boy, used to run in and out the pubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could you buy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, you could - not ha
ve a drink you could buy anything in the pub. You could buy beer for your mum or whatever you wanted, cigarettes, whatever you wanted. Yes. Some publicans wouldn't let you in but - others did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How many rooms would you have in your house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Gold Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Four. There was four rooms. And then - there was the kitchen and the - yard at the back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What were those rooms, how did you divide the house up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
There was a - a room like this upstairs, that was the biggest room in the house, the upstairs room, 'cos it went over the passage. And then there was downstairs front room and a back room and that's how it went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you use the rooms upstairs as bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, the upstairs - downstairs was the living rooms.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any relatives or any lodgers living with you in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Once we - I had a - we had a lodger. And then when the war came along - my missus - we had the house, the war came along and - we - we let a room there but - there was, you know, just to help so
mebody. And they paid - didn't pay a lot then, about five bob a week I don't suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did your mother ever pay anyone to help her in the house or did she manage all the work herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 She couldn't pay anybody could she, never had the money. She u
sed to - even when - when I was married, she used to come round to me and - say, Alf - lend us the rent. Well I'd give her the rent. See what I mean. That's - confidential, that was - the things wasn't so bright you see. Of course the - when this war came
 along - it cooked everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your mother do your washing at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Or was it sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, my mother or sisters done the washing. And then me, I - I - we didn't have a lot of washing see, a shirt, well how long does it
 take to wash a shirt. We didn't worry about clothing, underclothing. As long as you had a shirt on. I never wore a undervest. Only a top shirt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you warm enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes. Well we was tough weren't we, we were brought up rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about clothes, would your mother mend or make any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, she could mend when I was very young of course as you grew up - clothes was very cheap. You could get a - a suit for - you could get it in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Stepney Way{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} here a blue Melton overcoat for thirty-shillings. You could get a suit for thirty shillings shillings. Get a pair of trousers for about - seven and six, eight bob, good trousers you know. A shirt was half a crown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. I - I've got a - if I can find it I've got a 
- a very old book in there and it shows you in the City - shirts five and six, white - lovely white shirts and made - not rough made, good made. I don't think they were more than five and six each. In an advertisement. Like you saw that advertisement for 
that - steak, ninepence a pound. Best part of the beef, cooked - boiled beef at that. Now you've got to pay seventeen - seventeen pence a pound - quarter. Seventeen pence a quarter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you ever have any second hand clothes when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well was - then I belonged to a - a - a - a Sunday school and they used to send me away with a suit every year. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could your mother make clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - she could and then of course the - the - three sisters were - my younger sisters, when they came along they was all apprenticed in the tailoring. See, they was all expert tailors, them three sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your father ever repair shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He could - he didn't do any repairs, I - I - from my early age I was the shoemaker. From -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 For your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, fifteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And you could do it properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. Properly. I - I took on a contract when I was - no age, up - and I mended all the firemen's boots at Whitechapel. And then I - they - told me that they're going t
o get someone to do it cheaper, so I said well, it's up to you, you know, I - didn't take any notice. Only - he said, he was going to get a man to do it for sixpence a pair cheaper. I used to - at that time - I'll tell you what - used to get twenty-eight 
shillings for eight pair. Three - three and six a pair I think it was. Something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A complete repair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, I used to repair the firemen's boots with their leather. See, their - they used to give me the stuff, nails, heel bore, everything, and I done 'em. But - they were so pleased with it, the way I - brought 'em back you know, all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 polished}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 up, these stock boots, they're all - top boots. And this man I suppose he wanted to cut the price down. But anyhow, I - worked on it a long while and 
I was doing all right you see, I used to do three lots a week, say twenty-four pair a week. And - and I was - doing all right you see. Where my dad was earning say twenty-five bob a week, I was getting - three lot of - I had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much would a pair of shoes or boots cost when you were a boy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
You could buy a pair of shoes - about six shillings for men's heavy working shoes, six and six. Eight - eight - eight and odd you could get a good pair, about eight shillings, round about eight shillings, se
ven and six, eight shillings. Get good strong boots that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would you have new boots or would you have second hand shoes when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I'd have - well they used to buy me new shoes there and - used to be lots of little boot makers
 making - what they call working men's boots, you see. 'Course now I've got to have surgical boots you see now that they're - of course they were different makers altogether, and some had - see, and some maker - was - a different work to a man that knocke
d
 nails in. Them men that knocked nails in, they was mostly riveted the boots were, brass riveted, or iron riveted, the brass riveted mostly they did because it didn't rot the - the uppers. They were - they used to turn out their boots very - cheap you see
. It was a - a real cut away prices.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your mother would have to spend quite a lot on boots wouldn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. YES? But - yes. Yes. Well - that was how they went wasn't it. My mother-in-law had twenty-two children. Yes. He was a - see, he was a fur
rier by trade, he - she was - my wife was Jewish, a Jewish woman. And - her father was a - an assistant - secretary to Disraeli. Yes. See, he used to - there was a big - frame in my brother-in-law's room - flat here in Stepney, that belonged to a society,
 
Disraeli, they were called the Primrose League. Have you heard of that? Yes, well that's what he was and he had this big vast - frame, half the size of that - wall, all gilt with - the Primrose - I've forgotten now - it was a man in - Whitechapel name of 
H
awkins, wholesale grocers they were, he was one of the heads of that as well. I don't know what society - that was the Primrose League, 'course when - when my - father-in-law died they sent a whole brougham of primroses to the - funeral. That society. The
 Primrose League they called it, don't hear much of that now. Yes, the Primrose League, I remember when I was young. And of course when I first got married you heared - heard more about that and - that brother-in-law of mine went to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I don't know 
who had the picture, unless - his son - his son is a taxi driver now. He - over the water, he may have the picture. It was a - like a testimonial. Yes, that was my missus - father. Well they lived in a place in - Stepney called 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Welkland Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, it's down b
y the docks there. And next door lived Alec Earley and his wife, Alec Earley and Marie Lloyd. Yes, Marie Lloyd married Alec Earley, and they lived next door to my mother-in-law and - father-in-law. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Welkland Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} that was, that - that was in the '80's you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They were quite big houses were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes. Big - big posh place that was, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Welkland Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} that time. There's an old music hall there now what they - they - what they call the Albany Bar and another one, a tea merchant's got it.
 They're renovating it up to - where they used to be. Yes, Marie Lloyd and Alec Earley - when they first got married lived next door. Or Alec Earley always lived next door they said. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your father ever help in the house, do you remember your
 father helping your mother do any jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Now washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, no, no. We was - look from - I suppose - if I was eight years of age I was a little run about boy. I remember working as a milkboy eight years of age or just after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You would help your mother in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, I used to work in a - I used to work in a dairy, a little shop - help take out the milk, wash the cans of a morning, they used to have cans you know, no bottles Wash the cans and 
- then he'd fill up the milk and you'd take it to the different customers and then - of a night you come back and you wash the cans up in the afternoon, they used to deliver milk twice a day that time you know, morning and afternoon. And then - then I'd -
 Friday night they had - in that shop - 'til two o'clock in the morning weighing up soda and sugar for Saturday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
About nine. Yes, I used to fill up and make the bags, used to - used to have blue - thick blue paper a
nd they learnt us how to - spin that in little shapes, it was all cut in size and you twist the bag and make a little - little funnel and you twist it at the bottom, then you put the soda and sugar or any - whatever was wanted in them bags. Yes. Have a bi
g sack of soda or sack of sugar and say, do the sugar tonight and - we'd fill up all them bags see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That was when you were about eleven years old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Nine, ten. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much would you get for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh, couple of shillings of course. Not much more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would you have to do any jobs in the house if your father didn't help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well we - as I say like my - my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 mum done}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 the cleaning or anything like that, and then we had little chores to do. My job I remember from a little boy w
as to do - clean always the knives and forks. We had a - a little - machine you put the knives in and turn that handle and it - they had - brick dust in it, that was it, like Oakeys - powder, put it on there and the knife come out all lovely - clean, that
 was our job regular every - my job regular every week. Keep the yard clean, that was another one keep the - what do you call it - the rabbits clean. Clean the rabbits out, that was that all had to be done regular see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And your other brothers and sisters had to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, yes, well they had other little jobs, but the elder brothers went away, they didn't worry about that did they. As they got older they went out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have to help with the younger children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Mind them, yes. Mind them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your father do anything for the younger children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I don't think - I don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He didn't dress them or undress them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no, mum done that, yes. Dad went out in the morning, five o'clock 
didn't he. He didn't come back 'til say - late at night, from his work. He didn't have nothing to do with the children, they were in bed when he went out and in bed when he come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So he wouldn't even have time to read to them or tell them stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, very seldom, very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So would you say you didn't have much contact with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no. No, no, no, not a lot of contact with me dad. And on Sunday - you see - three o'clock was dinner time. You had your dinner before them and then when they come in to have their dinner mum and dad you all went out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your father ever light the fires or do any decorating in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no, no, we - we from kids lit the fires always for mum. We done all that ourselves. We was - - it comes natural to you. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you ever remember going out with your father at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. Yes, well - never - never took me - I don't remember him ever taking me to - anywhere, to a music hall or anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go out for walks with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no. Don't - don't ever remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You didn't have much to do with him at all then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no, he was - when they came - they went out - when they went out for a - they went in the local pub didn't they. Tha
t was all - you knew where they were. They was in the pub. You - they went in the pub so they - they didn't leave the pub 'til it was closing time. But - during the week when - when the most of them came home from work, like him for instance, now I realiz
e
 it, they never had any money to spend. Their money - he - he had a few coppers a day, he - he - what - if he made a tip while he was at work - it was used for food while he was out. Buying cups of tea or - or - you see, that time for sixpence - sixpence 
you could get a good dinner. You could go in a shop and get a dinner for sixpence, cut from the joint and two veg. Sixpence. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Lemon Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was a coffee shop, had on the - on the window, I can see it now, two fried eggs threeha'pence. And it's - two slices of bread would be tuppence ha'penny wouldn't it. Penny cup of tea. Would be threepence ha'penny you could have a - a - a meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Quite a lot of people used to eat out quite a lot then didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, everybody didn't they, if you went out to
 work. It was a natural thing, there was coffee shops everywhere you went. There was a cut away place, Lockhart's for instance, you - everything was ha'penny. You went in ha'penny mug of tea, ha'penny mug of coffee or ha'penny mug of cocoa. Ha'penny slice
 of bread and jam. Everything was a ha'penny in there, Lockhart's. Pearce and Plenty's was another one. You - beef steak pudding, tuppence. And - and two vegetables, that'd be fourpence your dinner wouldn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So you didn't go to bed at any certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no, no, we were - no, never worried. They knew we'd come home. We knew where we lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. And then - then she'd come up in the morning and want to know how much stock money I'd got, see, to give h
er a - a start for the day. Well now that's how - as I say - for - for sixpence she could buy - a loaf of bread. To feed all the family couldn't she. And a - and half a pound of marg for couple of coppers that time, it was only about fourpence - fourpence
 a pound marg was. Tuppence half a pound. Now it's about - three bob something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you share a bedroom with your brothers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, I - I slept with my brother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you share a bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, share a bed with 'em, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Some had left home by then had they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, well as they left home you had more room didn't you in the house. My - my next brother to me - and then when that one got - I had one brother in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. He played truant from school. One day - and h
e went in the City. You know. And - when he played truant, and - he was picked up by the police. And he told 'em he had no parents. They put him in a - industrial school for that. Yes. My mum tried to get him out there, he wouldn't. He wasn't a rogue, he 
w
as just a honest boy. He just - he just - played truant from school and he used to go to the school - right next to Arthur Square - like Thames Police Court. That was the school, St Thomas' church school. And - any how he - he went away, and he went into 
t
hat industrial school, and then from there - he - went into - when he left there, he went into the engine sheds of the London North Western Railway. At Manchester. London Road. And he - worked on the railway right up 'til he passed away. And - he become o
n
e of the - great high hands on the railway - every time I went to Euston with him, like say, I - he came up here for a - which he did regular, the union place was in the Euston Road, and he used to go there, but what I noticed, on the railway station ever
ybody knew him. Because he was so in the - union, he was a - I'll tell you what he was - a supervisor I know - and everybody knew him, the engine drivers, the guards, the porters, they all - you know - saluted him more or less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about your sisters, most of them were at home when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well those three young sisters were - were - they were at home, yes. Then they become dressmakers here, learnt the trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And they'd have a room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, they had their own bedroom see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about bathing, what would you do for baths in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they had - when I was a kid we used - washing day - bathing was in the copper. Up in the corner, mother used to hot the water up in the bath - and - you - the boys had their bath, th
e girls had their - but of course from a - a youngster we went to always the public baths. Yes. They were cheap then, see. The dearest bath was fourpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How often would you have a bath at home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - when I was young we used to have it once 
a - once a week. But - when - we - I grew up, soon as you went out to work you used to go into the - you could go into the public baths for about tuppence you see, but the private baths was fourpence. There was a little barbers shop opposite here - and it
 had a bill in the window, you listen to this. Haircut and a shave and a ticket for Macey's baths, well Macey's baths was up the top of here, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Epsom Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, a private bath, and a ticket - the ticket for Lacey's bath, the hair cut and shave - sixpence. Haircu
t and a shave in the barber and he sold the ticket - he got commission out of - off of Lacey's for the - putting that up see. But that was all it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 These were private baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, private baths. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They weren't run by the council?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, they weren't run by the council. They were private baths. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there any council baths round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well there was a couple, one over Shadwell there was and there was one - Bethnal Green. Roman Road Baths there was, and - and then the Je
wish people opened some private houses up here, the back turnings, opened private baths, they used to charge fourpence. And sixpence. Fourpence see. But in the - in the council baths you went in for a couple of coppers or a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So these public and private baths were used quite a lot were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes, yes. Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When would you have clean clothes to put on and how often in a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I don't know, I - I always had - my Sunday suit was my Monday suit as well. We never had
 no - special changes. And if you had any spare clothes at home when you - went to look for 'em they was in the pawn shop. Used to pawn everything. I'll tell you the truth. I went - into the services in the '14 war. And I was a master shoemaker in service
s. But what I was coming to, this, when I went away I left a brand new suit - indoors. And I went down to - where did I go first - Aldershot, from Aldershot they sent me to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southampton{\*\xmlclose}
. From Southampton I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I was away about six month
s and I came home on leave. When I came home on leave, all I've got is my soldiers clothes, and - I looked for me suit and it's not there. Me shoes, I had a lovely pair of - Scotch brogue shoes. I - I'll tell you about them brogue shoes in a minute. And -
 Scotch brogue shoes they - was a firm in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, name of Richard Dick, they - made their name - with a - a special - kind of - of best footwear, like the soles, it was called Dick the Later. But this - they were the original Stick-a-Sole people, they stu
ck the - boot - no nails, it was stuck on, the soles. And it was a real good firm. Anyhow, I got these lovely brogue shoes in the - in there with a new suit. That new suit I think cost me - a lot of money, three pound, hand made. Brand new. And that suit 
w
ould last you ten years. And you used to get two pair of trousers of that. Used - this old man over in Aldgate there, he used to make you a suit, and a special - and a extra pair of trousers, you had two pair of trousers - to the suit, for about three pou
n
d odd, and you give him say a few shillings, five bob. He was happy as a sandboy. Well anyhow, when I missed the clothes I said to mum, give me the ticket. So she gave me the ticket, the pawn ticket. Then I went round to the pawn shop. And - I took the su
i
t out. And when I took the suit it - he put it out on the - on these like counter, this pawnbroker, and I put my hand in the pocket, it was a - American type suit what was made that time, they called the trousers peg top. They come wide here and they went
 
down to a - a - a shrapish angle. And they were called peg tops, it was American idea. And - I put me hand in and I pulled out a little purse what was in the pocket. And I saw the - pawnbroker looking. So he - he said, well we never touch anything in the 
pockets of the clothes, we put 'em in. And I took 'em out, there - the whole lot was only in for say about seven and six. See, the shoes and the -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there anything in the purse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Eight gold sovereigns. You see, it was good job - good job m
y mother never knew, if she'd have put her hand in the pocket I wouldn't have got nothing would I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 She'd have used them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, she'd have definitely had that. Yes, I had eight gold sovereigns in there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So pawnbrokers were very honest weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, that's what I'm saying. That - that - that was true that. See because - I was always - had a - a few pound in me pocket, and she took that - pair of trousers and it had a little bob pocket up there what she folded up the t
rousers and - and took 'em to the pawn shop, and she - I think the whole lot was in for something - roughly about seven and six. Two and six the shoes and five bob the suit. That time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you have your meals when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Indoors. Oh, when we were at home. Oh yes, we all - all - had at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What room would you use?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 In the kitchen, or the back room. There was a little - back room.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever use any other room for eating at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, only the kitchen o
r that - mostly the kitchen, in the winter we'd go in the bedroom there was a big fire, but in that little kitchen - was lovely and warm 'cos it had a - a little {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitchener
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} there, it was - marvellous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would your mother cook on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 On the - on t
his - all on there. All on the fire. A kitchen - an American kitchen - they call them kitchens, little {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitcheners{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. A closed in stove it is. And - they used to cook on that. Cook in the oven or on the top, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 This was coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, coal or - whatever fuel, yes, coke or coal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When would you eat breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When it was given you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you all have breakfast at the same time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, not necessary, no. Father wouldn't be there or we wouldn't be there - when we grew up. We'd be gone. The girls would have - their little breakfast there - like I would if I was there. Sunday morning, that was the only time you was at home, Sundays.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you have for breakfast normally in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - if you had quaker oats or bread - 
bread and jam or whatever they give you. You never grumbled. Egg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Anything special on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no. Same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you do for a midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they - she used to provide it. I remember my mum sending me to a butchers here in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - four cold faggots, that was threepence. Now them four cold faggots you got from the butchers, they were threefarthings each. She put a potful of vegetables on - like potatoes, onion or swede, all boiling, and then when that was boiling 
they used to put the faggots on top of that, and - and half a dozen of you'd have a meal for that. And that whole lot didn't come to about sixpence. For the whole family. See, that's four faggots was - threepence, and say three - penn'orth of - wasn't thr
eepenn'orth of vegetables 'cos vegetables used to be, when I was a boy, four pound tuppence. Four pound of best potatoes was tuppence. And the very best was tuppence ha'penny.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your father wouldn't come home for a midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, he wouldn't be there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
So at that time there were just a few of you, when you were at school you came home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, well - yes, we had - come home for dinner, yes. But that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What other sort of meals would your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh fish. We used to h
ave fish, salt fish, anything. 'Cos fish was cheap then. For - for a big - big herring she paid a farthing - four a penny. You - man come round shouting out, fresh herrings, sixteen for fourpence. And if you bought a couple of penn'orth of herrings you ha
d
 eight, big herrings. And you - and you don't want no more than one herring. Not a big herring. And mum used to fry 'em, she used to souse 'em, put 'em in vinegar in the oven with - bay leaves. I say, food was cheap. A - a loaf was tuppence ha'penny. A fu
ll two pound loaf. Now you've got to pay two and odd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you have anything special on Sunday for the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, she - she - well she - if she made a bread pudding or something like that that as special. See? That was a treat then that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd all be home on Sunday wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes. Together - in different times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you have another meal at teatime when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What, Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Ordinary days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well you - no, only - when you come home of
 a night you had your tea and that was your finish for the night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you have to eat when you came in for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well she fried fish or that, she'd give you - as I say, fried fish or - or - give you a herring, a fried herring or sprats, se
e they was - that time sprats was about threepence a pound if you - or so, tuppence a pound. You buy a pound of sprats and you all had - some each from that. And give 'em to you hot while they was - on - on that was the way they ate see. They used to say,
 have the sprats hot and you'll enjoy 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would Sunday tea be anything special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well you'd have the remains of the - dinner wouldn't you. Meat pie they had mostly made. Meat pie. I used to go to Leadenhall market for my mum - and buy a rump bon
e for her, threepence. Now that rump bone had enough meat on that - to make a beef steak pudding for a family, or a pie for the family. The meat alone what they left on it after cut - see, they used to cut the steaks off and in - in the crevices was all t
he pieces of meat and they used to chop it up for you, and you come home, well after you cut the meat and - fat off, she could make a pie and - and make a basin of - pot of soup with the - with the remains.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your mother was obviously quite good at budgeting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, well that was only threepence, see, but you had to go to get it in the market. That was the nearest - meat market then, Leadenhall Market, well it wasn't the nearest but it - that was the best place, in them big shops. - 'Course they 
used to supply the restaurants and that with the steaks you see. And they wanted the bone - they didn't want to throw the bone in the - in the - what they called the bone bag and they used to let you have it for threepence, that was their perks, those but
chers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Is there anything else you could get quite cheap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Giblets as well, the same. You - you could get a bag of giblets for threepence, feed the whole family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Chicken?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, chicken or turkey or geese, whatever they - give you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Quite a lot of people would do that would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, and - and for a few coppers you could get pieces of fish - from the fish shop there in - there was a couple of fish shops in - Leadenhall Market, you could go and get the pieces of fish of a - see, a
fter they'd done with the trade of the day. All the cuttings and that you - they'd more or less give you a bagful of fish to take home. The pieces, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So people knew here to go and what to do with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Presumably a lot of people didn't?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, a lot of people didn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your mother ever bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, never baked the bread but she baked plenty of - them bread puddings what I told you, any stale bread she - that was floating around, she made a bread pudding with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would she ever make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well she would with - fruit, if we had fruit. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 She'd buy the fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, if we went in the fruit - picking fruit like in the season, or down hopping, we got - we brought plenty of fruit in to - make the jam with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you bring the fruit back with you when you went hopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Some - some we would, yes. On the day - when we come home - but while we were down there we didn't want fruit because we had all what we wanted. It was - and lib. You had to walk through the orchard perhaps to your hop pick - hop fields and all like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you tell me about when you went hopping? Where did you used to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 We used - I've been in numerous places but we went for years
 in a place called - Barming. That's near - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Maidstone{\*\xmlclose}. When I first went to Barming - there was no buses. From {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Maidstone{\*\xmlclose}
. Now there's buses run - there was no - well there was no trams that time. They put electric trams on from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Maidstone{\*\xmlclose} to Barming. Well there was none of that when I was kid, you walked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How many miles would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Four or five miles see. You walked to the - town. From Barming you went to the town. There was a little shop in the village - where you could buy little things, like a post office, buy little odds and ends in there. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How did you get down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
From London to - yes. Two - two shillings it - it was. Two shillings the fare. From {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Maidstone{\*\xmlclose}. And - six out of - ten never paid. They was - they were in sacks tied up and the man'd come - when you left London Bridge they'd stop a couple of stations up, Spa Road Bermondsey I think it was. Stop the train at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Spa Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - tickets. Of course they'd be all under the seats and Lord knows where and they w
ere dirty old carriages what they sent them away in that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were they special hop pickers trains?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, they was - the rough old - carriage, all the seats - padding taken out, you were sitting on boards, but they was all hid underne
ath who - who evaded the - like after a certain age you didn't want - see, under age they didn't take no notice. But over a certain age, say about twelve, they wanted your two bob. Well then - when we get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Maidstone{\*\xmlclose} - the - the barrier'd be there the tic
ket collector. They were only - poor men theirselves. And then - would be a hue and cry, oh where's my mum, it's got my ticket. Oh my mum's got my ticket, she's gone up there, and - we'd go through. He couldn't stop us, 'cos while he was - trying to stop 
one he'd lose about fifty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you stay when you went hop picking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
In huts, they used to have old - stable, what they - what they call - cattle - houses they were, they called them hopping huts. They were - they were - straw put in, bales
 of straw and faggots, we used to - wood faggots and put the straw on top, we used to lay on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you cook on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Out - outside in the field - they used to put - a bar of wood across and - like - that - and - and - and they used to have pots with handles on that time, cook everything in the saucepans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would London people know how to do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes. They all knew. And then we had a cookhouse there at Barming. It was a - a row of - iron bars with hooks on 'em, and you hung your pots on there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would people cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Whatever they bought, rabbits or - rabbit was favourite wasn't it down there because you could buy a rabbit for about sixpence you see, a wild rabbit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever do any poaching when you were down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, you know if you - you got a chance to catch a rabbit, they used to run out the woods, and - we used to - our favourite - things was - catapults. See, the catapult. I remember catching a duck.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A wild duck?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. It flew onto a post - and - I just - aimed at it and let go and it hit it on the side of the wing and it - and I went and picked the duck up. Well of course that was dinner wasn't it for somebody. That duck.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Tell me the story about the pheasants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh the pheasants, we - well I learnt that, you see, at the backs of where - that was at a place at Faversham. There was a - a - a rich man and lord of the manor had grounds at the back of that there cemetery and I spotted - some men - they used to 
throw the - maize on top of the grave - flat gravestones, you know. And had all - threadled with horsehairs. And - this friend of mine said, watch what goes on. When these pheasants flew down to these gravestones, they picked up the horsehairs. And of cou
rse then they had to bend forward their head to the ground to try and release that hair. And they went and picked them up and put them in the knapsacks and we learnt the same trick didn't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you take them home and eat them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Oh they w
as lovely pheasants. Lovely. I've always remember that. But that was the simple way of picking them up. You never hurt the animal at all, because - until they killed it. But - that was all they caught them with was with the maize and the horsehairs.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 S
o on the whole the people who were down for the hop picking could find ways of getting food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, you find all sorts you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would they do about vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh you - well you didn't buy vegetables did you, you went - you see the p
otatoes growing, you went and - in between 'em and you - dug up a lot and put the stalk back again, in the ground and - and same - you covered up the - went out in the middle and took a - a big cabbage or you took a - a swede, a swede'd last you two or - 
two - a great big swede, some of them swedes was - seven or eight pound, them great big swedes. Don't see the swedes here now in the shops like what we - I saw 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did the farmers know the hoppers were doing this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well he might miss one now - bu
t we - we was artful as well as them, she didn't take it right in sight of the - roadway so if he rode along in his - or on his horse he could see it. We took it out in the middle of the field, we - I looked over with a stick like a little bit of stick wi
t
h a bit of paper on it, or a twig, and we knew that. We'd stick that in and of a night time we'd go along - when everything was asleep and we'd fetch that. And we went to the town, we went to Faversham walking down that mile road, there's all different st
uff growing. You go, oh here's - here's our piece of paper. We had it - or stone on it or bit of paper would mark it see, put a stone on a bit of paper and we knew that was the one we wanted and we'd fetch that home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Fruit, we 
had - we took that - in the daytime. 'Course if we wanted to go in the night but we - mostly in the daytime we took fruit, nobody about watching the stuff, they couldn't watch everything. Used to climb in - I remember there was a - a five bar gate, big ga
t
e, used to open into a - up against the wall of a - what I call the edge of a - an orchard, and we used to push this gate, right up to the edge and climb up on top of the gate - had - had the gate held and picked off all the plums or fruit what was growin
g
 up on - near that gate you see. Be a couple of - couple of trees perhaps, see. Yes, but we - we had plenty of fruit there. They planted our - a hop field full of young fruit trees for - and all you had to do like, go like that, shake it and down come the
 plums and that. See you shock the trees and they fell down, the young trees with the - with the fruit on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would all the children be helping picking the hops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, all - all - all picked the hops, we was all workers. We loved picking, used 
to race one another. 'Course it was all the better for mum wasn't it - the more hops you picked - when it come to measuring out and of course that time - I - now I recall - you had to pick about seven bushels for a shilling. Six bushels, seven bushels bef
o
re you got a shilling. See, they used to sing a song, they - what was it, they pay me seven a shilling so how can a poor girl get a living. That was the song they used to sing. That - and it's true though, six a shilling, seven a shilling was the - six a 
shilling, it was - then didn't get tuppence a - a bushel did they you know. You realized how they - they got money that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your father go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Never. Never. Never, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Mother took you all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, mother always took - our father never went hopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So how much do you think you'd earn a day in your whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - if we earnt a couple of bob for mum a day or - three bob or half a crown, sometimes we earnt - might have earnt more you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you go for the money or did you go because it was a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
We never - we never had no money you see that - mother took all the money. She give us a penny now and then, we had other ways of making money down there like I told you with fruit. You pinched the fruit and sell it to somebody, and have a good share.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd sell it to someone else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. You couldn't eat it all what you took. If I went and took - took a - a - a pot full of apples, a big saucepan with a - handle on, fill it up with apples or t
hat - then I'd take it - then I used to do mushrooming in the morning early. Get a bag - tin of mushrooms and that used to - people wanted them. Now I pay one and six for a quarter of mushrooms. One and six for a quarter of mushrooms, a - a - a little bit
 like that, look, and I used to get a basketful - I used - I am not telling you a lie, when I was twelve years of age I can - I can see it now, I used to get a basketful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And you'd sell some of those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, well if they'd want 'em to be - give us 
a penn'orth well then you'd give 'em a penn'orth, a penny was a penny wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So your mother enjoyed it as a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, it was good for her. She - it was rest, and she had no - if she was - getting money coming in which she never had before did she. See.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was the farmer like who owned these hop fields?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh them bailiffs were - some of 'em, you never very often - if you have - might have had the bailiff in charge of you - I went to a farm - at - Faversham, the year the '14 b
roke out, I remember that well. That was in the August the war came - and - that bailiff there used to breed chickens. Big white Winalots, they have - got a little blackish mark on their neck - white - some of 'em weighed eight pound those hens. One and t
h
reepence he charged her for 'em. One and threepence. One and threepence a chicken. To - take back a few bob, they filled 'em up, the potato baskets, they had baskets potato baskets with a lid on that time, used to hold about a hundredweight of potatoes, a
nd he'd fill them up, put - and tied the lids down and sent us back to - Holborn Viaduct, at the cheap rate, these basketful of chicken, passenger grains.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were they alive or dead?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Dead, we killed - had 'em killed and put in there. And packed 'em 
in and we sold 'em here half a crown, three bob each. Three bob, half a crown, and got rid of 'em in no time. Of course that - that was a con - you could get 'em, you could buy a - play 'em like that. But one and threepence was the price what we paid him.
 He wanted to get rid of 'em for the winter you see, 'cos they don't lay.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He didn't want to feed them right through?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. So we got the great big white Winedops for - one and threepence each.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How long would you be away hopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A month
s, sometimes five weeks - that time. I've had six weeks down there. Yes, we used to go from one place to another. When one place had finished they'd say - here do you want to go and help so and so out, they've got a - a few more - couple of fields to do. 
And we'd go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were the people all very friendly together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, mostly - mostly, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They didn't stay in families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, the - the - you knew one another from years you see down there. You knew the faces. At that place at - Faversham where my mum went - the most of the people there came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Covent Garden{\*\xmlclose}
, that area. The - they were flower sellers and that all up the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West End{\*\xmlclose}. Groups of families you know. They - got their living with the flowers. From {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Covent Garden
{\*\xmlclose}. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bloomsbury{\*\xmlclose} and all that way they lived and of course we come from Stepney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there quite a lot of families went hopping from this part of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, all the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 went. Every district had its - hop pickers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And you were able to be away from schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 We never were worried about that, we went didn't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So you'd regard that really as a holiday wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, it - it - that was our holiday, we never - our mother and father never took us for a holiday, that was our holiday, kids holiday. See the green fields and a ride in a train. It was a wonderful holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your mother ever make any wine or any beer herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no. No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about medicines, did she have any special medicines she'd make?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well she would make - she would make - I - I remember what she made. She made a - a stuff for your chest for - sweet - nitre, oil of juniper, then she used to have - black treacle, they used to have this black, like - Flowers treacle, it was li
ke - not Golden Syrup, it's black and they used to mix that up with - for your chest, it was very good that time what they did. She'd make it up and you - if you had a cold on the chest she'd give you a spoonful of that, you have that. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could you grow anything out in your yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no. It was crazy paving yard where we were there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your mother would buy vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about tinned fruits or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Tinned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you ever remember having that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, you could get it - at that time things was cheap you see, you could get - tin of this, see a tin of - a tin of - fruit for about threepence you see or fourpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of fruit would you be able to buy in tins?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Plums and all like that you see, yes. Gooseberries or anything like that. But you mostly had fresh fruit. You didn't worry about tinned stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about dried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Dried fruits you could get - apricots and prunes or figs, anything like that,
 and they were all cheap. Yes. Everything was cheap. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And you said you kept rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you eat those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, yes, oh that was a - treat wasn't it, but we - my - you did - when you grow up with an animal you can't bear to keep thinking of him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you feed them on then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they used to feed 'em on chaff, oats and that, you could get plenty of food for 'em, carrots and that. See.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they cost much to feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no, it cos
t - we - we used to go and get 'em dandelion, collect anything for 'em. Grass, anything that - you fed your rabbits on - as I say, hay, bought a penn'orth of hay, a lot - oh you had a big bundle for a penny. You give 'em hay and - you know, they ate that 
and - cabbage leaves you got and carrots from the - oil - the - the - what do you call it, the greengrocer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you keep any hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 For eggs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, you know - kept - I had - my brother, he bought - a - lot of hens. He sent away for 
'em. I suppose he was about seventeen, and - he bought these chickens, and - none of 'em laid. So he bought - so he - he started to sell 'em. He sold 'em to a man next door, and as soon as the man next door had them they laid. See, 'cos he was pinching th
e eggs while he was - he was out at work. Yes, and he never told him they laid, we kept the eggs and ate 'em. And of course he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He didn't know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, he thought they didn't lay, see. So he sold them to the man next door and the man next door had eggs every day. I tell you - it's fun - that was really funny you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How many times a week did you eat meat in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh lots of times they had meat, yes. It was cheap that time meat. I told you about faggots for instance. Faggots - four faggots for threepence, for sixpence your family have - half a dozen of you. Give you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What is a faggot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
A - a - a - like a - a little meat pasty, you get 'em in these - in the butcher shops, they sell - it's a made up - they used to l
ike grind up all the pieces of - all the odd pieces the butchers did and with - lungs and lord knows what they mixed up, they call 'em faggots. See it's like mincemeat. You call it mincemeat today. See, you grind up the mincemeat - my wife used to grind h
e
r own mincemeat and make them herself, what they call meatballs, well anyhow in them butcher shops they used to make 'em and sell 'em for a penny. But when they were cold in the morning you bought 'em for threefarthings. At a night time when they sold - a
 
penny - penny faggot and a ha'porth of pease pudding, that's threeha'pence. You had a dinner, a pease pudding and a faggot, that was a good meal for you. You didn't want any more. They was good that time. 'Course today the mixes and food is different food
 altogether.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about tinned meat, do you ever remember your mother buying tinned meat?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, corned beef, but very seldom. Very seldom. You see, you could get tinned meat off of the docker boys that worked in the docks, when they first - not m
any people liked corned beef. You could get a penn'orth of corned beef, go in a - a grocer's shop and buy a penn'orth of corned beef, you got about a quarter of a pound. See.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But it wasn't that popular at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, it wasn't - wasn't popular. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bethnal Green Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was stalls sold meat. There was cats meat stall stood there, fourpence, sixpence a pound, the cats meat. Meat for human consumption, lamb, tuppence ha'penny. The cats meat stall was fourpence and sixpence a pound their meat,
 but the other - strips of mutton as they called it - that time - tuppence ha'penny, threepence a pound. Cheaper than the cats meat, and that was right up to the war. And - and - to - the fruit for instance. I remember every where you went, cox's apples, 
a
ll them pippins, ribsons, all them. If you pay more than threepence a pound you - you wouldn't buy 'em. Tuppence a pound russ - lovely russet apples, you don't see many of them today, like you did then. Tuppence a pound they were, lovely big russet apples
.
 Everywhere they was - in Farringdon Road there, I don't know if you've ever been down near Smithfield Market, in Farringdon Road, from Clerkenwell Road right up to - to Smithfield was all stalls, and you'd see the fruit there, that was tuppence and three
pence a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 People could afford to buy fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. Yes, you could buy - if you had a penny you cold buy half a pound couldn't you. You realize it. See, a penny - you could go - and buy half a pound of apples with a - that'd satisfy your c
raving for fruit all day. Four a penny oranges. A - three a penny - of course if you paid ha'penny for a orange it was a - a - I've got oranges indoors I paid about - over sixpence for 'em, without - we didn't pay a ha'penny for 'em. Bananas four a penny.
. In the City you go in the - in the - up there, where {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Pudding Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - where the Great Fire of London started was sale rooms and them men used to sell - Canary bananas. They take 'em out the saleroom, stand there with a - with the crate w
hat they come in, four a penny. Now - you - them four bananas what we paid a penny for - I've got to pay about two bob for today. Eggs is sixpence each, and we paid a farthing, best. Things is - awfully funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And looking back when you were at home, d
o you remember ever seeing your mother eating less food so that the rest of her family could have more, would she ever go without?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I don't know about that, I don't think - well of course what they did I - that I wouldn't have noticed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was your father given more food because he was the man of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Not necessary. He was given a meal and there - and that was the end of it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He didn't have anything special because he was earning or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. I used to fetch him in a tr
eat every - now and then. He liked - we used - I had a friend in Leadenhall market, used to give me halibut heads, all the heads. Big - large plaice heads, halibut heads, turbot heads - of course they charge for today but he - mum used to boil 'em, and he
 - he used to like 'em cold. All jelly it was, 'cos they - once you let that sort of fish head - it goes to a thick }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 jelly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 . And he used to enjoy that. That was - and I used to get them - and lib. There was food for anybody that wanted to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That knew where to go and find it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were at home did your mother let you talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - when we had meals we had it just ourselves, yes, they wasn't so fussy that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could you
 choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh no, no, I - I - well might have been a - one of my sister's might not like certain food, but us boys, we ate everything that - was put on the floor wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You were hungry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. We - we didn't worry. You give everything a trial.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
And what would your mother say if you didn't eat things, if you left anything uneaten on the plate?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd been off somewhere and having food. But it was very se
ldom that happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
And if there was something on the table you wanted like the salt would you ask someone to pass it to you or would you have to wait until it was passed to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What, the salt? You get it yourself didn't you. Yes. Get anything like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to ask for second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - if there was any going they gave it to you I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 If there was something you could have it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I know on Sundays when - after the dinner - there was any - vegetables left
 they used to - fry it up, what did you call it, bubble and squeak.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd have that next day would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Well - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
What about holding your knife and fork, were you told to hold them in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, you - you had to use -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And table manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, you wasn't allowed to put your hands on anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have to sit at the table in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Not - well, no, no we were just brought up rough and ready you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They weren't too fussy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, not in my - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to bring books or toys to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Never had any. Never had any. The only toy - I - I only remember having a toy and I must have kept it - ten years - or more. A little train set, cost about - sixpence that do
ne, a little engine with two little carriages. And that I kept in a tin box, that was my favourite toy and I kept it in and out, that was the only played with a marble or something like that, but, we never - had any toys bought us like - like you see the 
c
hildren today, every day, books, comics, we never had nothing like that. No, they - it wasn't none. No toys bought. I see a little boy here, he - they spend on him about - five shillings a day buying everything - he gets a toy every week he goes in the sh
o
p, we never had a toy. The only toy I had was a soapbox and a couple of old pram wheels and made a little motor with, you know what I mean. Yes, to push about in the street, and then that come as a - a tool to carry our goods home with what we found in th
e
 market or - make a little motor, that was our pleasure. Four wheels on a board - a - soap box, tuppenny soapbox, cake sugar box or something like that, and make yourself a little motor. Well you - you could - you could run along as fast as the traffic wh
e
n I was a boy. See? No, there was no motors. There was nothing on the road. We used - we used to hop across the road on one leg, hopping races, in the main road and - race one another at hopping, hopping, what they call hopping races. You couldn't do that
 
today could you. We used to jump on the back of a bus or a tram, then the old horse tram, and - and ride from Whitechapel, when the conductor went inside we got on the back and then when he come out we got off again. In the middle of the road, fancy tryin
g to get off a tram now in the middle of the road with all this traffic. Well we used to do it didn't we, we was kids.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were at the table when could you leave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were finished, when you were finished, yes, there was no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Just get up and go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. She was only glad you got out so she could clear the place up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you all sit together at the table, would you all eat at the same time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Not necessary. Mother'd call out Tom, Dick or Harry and - come and have your - dinner, and you had it and you went. You didn't - make no meals of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you all have to sit in the same place at your table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well you mostly - laid - say there was a little table like that for instance, there'd be one there and one there and two here, that's four of you, you have your meal, out, the next set in - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Because you have to organise when you've got a big family don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, well that's how it was done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And who served the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Mum would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would she served them in any special order?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, not particularly, put your meal down and there you are, now get on with it, and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He - he - well he - he had his meal on his own didn't he, we went out when he come in, yes. \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 He - he was head of the caravan. Jack Dooley, everybody knew him. He was the old prize fighter, see before the boxing gloves came in, they - they called the Marquis of Queensbury Rules they calls it see. Well they used to fight with
out gloves, with no gloves at all. And they used to fight - go - and it was done illegally you know, they used to - make a fight on a field somewhere, and tell all their friends who - who - where the fights was going to take place, when it was made illega
l. Yes, and - old Jack, he was the heavyweight champion of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And I used to be - running about for him and his daughter and his wife. They had a - took a pub just where - right opposite where I lived here, the pub was just across there, the Alfa's Hea
d. And from there he went down to a pub, I never - forget the name of that pub now in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Crisp Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I know the pub but I didn't - but the - he went - of course as I grew up you see he was away. But when I was young, up to I was say about fourteen - he was - here, with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How old were you when you started with him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh might be about ten I suppose. Something like that. Me and a friend of mine, she - she - she used to run errands for the mother - mother and I used to run about for them. Doing 
any little odd jobs what they wanted. Pick up glasses, anything you could that time, go in pubs you see. You - you can't do that today. See, children can't go in, we used to go in and pick the glasses up and give 'em to 'em over the counter but - in the c
ountry places where they have - got the busy trade - like hop picking season, you pick up the pot - used to have pint pots, or quart pots - take 'em to the - man behind the bar and he'd put his hand down there and you have a - a bowl of - \{BLANK\}
 see to giv
e you a couple. See, that was the inducement. We used to go and say, pick up your empties guv'nor? They said, yes, yes, fetch 'em in, see they - they'd only lose 'em very likely. And we used to take 'em in, take peoples beer with 'em and all, so long as w
e got apple. Didn't worry about their beer. 'Cos the beer that time wasn't dear, it was only a - fourpence a pot. That's - penny half a pint. See well now beer is about two shillings and odd a - a pint. A lot of difference. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did he teach you anything about fighting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, not very well, but he was always - we was always skylarking about, and his second - his - trainer was - another - he - he was crippled up more or less coming on with arthritis, I remember him, old Mr Baldock. He was his second.
 They went about for years them two. See they was like trainer, one was the - the others trainer. Yes, he was a - a very good man. He - a funny thing, and when the war came along - they published his life story in the News of the World, Jack Dillon. And -
 
you know - it was on my mind that time to save all them up each week from the News of the World, and I didn't, I saved a few - and of course - what with the bombing, I got bombed out one house. And my - sisters moved out and went over to Morden, so I took
 their house, like where I was born more or less, as a - well I wasn't born there but I was living there from a boy. And they lived there as well. See they'd never - moved out the house. Them two - two of 'em. One moved out when she was married.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would
 there be a lot of spectators at these fights, did you ever go to watch one of these fights out in a field?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no. No. No, I - no. That stopped before I could grow up you know, the boxing in the fields. The fighting in fields, yes. I think it - the 
Marquis of Queensbury's rules - come out in the 18 - 80's, something like that. And that's what happened there. I used to go on an ordinary little horse, and boxing, matches here. But - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was boxing popular round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Had a - we had 
the Premiland here in Whitechapel. We had the Wonderland, the place at Wonderland, everybody used that. The Wonderland, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Whitechapel Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. All little clubs was boxing clubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 For ordinary boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, men and - men and all. There was little clubs, i
n Bethnal Green there was a few clubs. You know, some of these pubs - was - a - clubs, boxing taking place Sunday mornings. There was a club over - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cable Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, a famous club, the Dudele, used to go there. Used to pay forpence to go in there we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Is this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 amateurs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  boxing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Amateurs - no, this is professional. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13517743\charrsid66970 Professional}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 boxing. See, amateur boxing's different. See? But the amateur boxing used to take place - mostly the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Peoples{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Palace
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in Mile End. You know, where - where they call it - the College is now. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}East{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. When I was a boy in that {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Peoples{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Palace{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} I used to go there - there was a swimming bath there, it was very dear, a penny to go in. Used to go swimming there. And - they used to hold amateur contests there. That was a well k
nown hall see, and then I saw some famous singers there as well. I remember - Sara Butt, Dame Sara Butt, she used to sing Home Sweet Home. And when she sang Home Sweet Home everybody was - had tears in their eyes. - Yes, it's true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was she the one who used to sing Rule Britannia?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. Sara Butt - I remember here, and I was only a lad. Little boy. 'Cos we used - I used to belong to a Sunday school and we - we used to always go there when there was any shows on. But - the great assembly hall 
was Mile End. What Charringtons run. One of the - brothers of - the brothers. He - he did - he give up the brewery trade and he went and opened a - like a - a church hall, you see what I mean, like a - a mission, he - he would have nothing to do with pubs
. That's what he said, that time. He went along like years and years, 'course the war came along and burnt it out. But, the - the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Peoples{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Palace{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, it used to hold all - all the - famous singers, they used to come there. And it was called the Queens Hall, like up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Langham Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was the Queens Hall, what the B.B.C. had. But I remember as a boy singing there in a choir in the - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Langham Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And we had massed choirs, we went - I must have been about - fourteen or fifteen, we went there for a - one of the B
and of Hope's I suppose it was - it was at the time, I can't just remember that, we sung in the Queens Hall, all the children, then we used to go to the Peoples Palace, The Queens Hall as well and sing regular - in there. Concerts. See if you went to Sund
a
y school you went to those places. From like - especially the Assembly Hall. The Assembly Hall had - oh tons of entertainment that did. Charrington did. And some wonderful speakers used to come there every week. Gipsy Danieals, and a man name of Wilkey wa
s always speaking there. And I'm going back over fifty -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did they talk about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Religions. About - General Booth - was in my chapel see. General Booth used to be up Whitechapel, the Salvation Army there, and he used to stand at the bottom of this street, just opposite Jubilee Street, in between Jubilee Street and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sidney Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, there's a statue there - that was put there where he used to speak and I remember him speaking there. I remember General Booth speaking there. And I remember his place up in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Hanley Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, they turned it into the Brady Girls Club. But it was originally there for men. And then - Brady - Brady come along and took it. You see there was the Brady boys come in - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Berwood Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brady Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and very like - that was th
e girls clubs. That Brady club is started by - it was Jewish, all Jewish for that. The Brady Clubs are Jewish - the head of - Shell-Mex, I forget his name now, he - he - he - they - they - give a lot of money to those places you see, the Jewish children y
es.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 To go in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A recreational sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I - Know the name, I can't think of it. I believe because I - I - happened to - meet him during the air raid when he was picking up all the silver cups and - things in the B
rady - when the Brady club got bombed that night the first bomb what come in Derwood Street - and I was only a few yards from it - \{BLANK\}
 He was. He was quite a - you couldn't harm him, he was a - he had - oval shaped fingernails, he was like - his lips w
as blue, heart trouble. Poor chap. And he - they told me he was the head of the Shell Mex. I - it may have been Hayman, I - I can't think see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you remember the Salvation Army working round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes. Yes, yes, yes, they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you think they were very good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did they do, what sort of work would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The - the Salvation Army used to come round - collecting and they had insurance business didn't they, a bit - oh - wherever they go they have insurance bu
siness and that. And then they - they used to sell their paper, the War Cry, every - they used to go in and our the pubs selling it. And then they used to - try to do away with drink, see, there by their preaching. See, they - they were drink reform - for
mers. See. Then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did it have any effect on people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well I - it did I suppose on a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there many down and outs, vagrant sort of people who they took in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - they - they - was all - it's always been down and outs, see. And 'co
urse today they get helped see, years ago they didn't. See, the same like I told you when I was a boy in the City selling things, every penny we had we was kings you see what I mean. It was helpful. If I - if I could take - a few whillings in a day and ea
r
n a - a - couple of shillings out of that, half a crown or something like that it - that was profit. That time. Specially when you knew your father was only getting say about a pound a week wages - from working six in the morning, and - and that time you 
k
now - I remember - going to work with my dad. Used to start six in the morning - 'til six at night, that was your - day's work, twelve hours. Then after that, if you done another six hours you never got nothing for it, they didn't give you no overtime, bu
t
 he - they - they - 'til about - about 1912 the union brought in a - bit of a - they used to give 'em a lot of money that time overtime, sixpence an hour. See? But they're - the average - day's work - you see - I - I remember when a - a boy working when I
 was first in my trade, working with a lot of foreign men used to be in the East End that time, like you've got coloured people here now, you had these - Jewish - refugees from - from Russia, see. They used to - run away from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} so they shouldn't join the Army a lot of 'em. See, that was the idea. So they used to get into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}, and cross over from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}, get - and get a - a ship you see to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then these people used to take 'em off the boat, go and get 'em work and lodging and that, they giv
e 'em about five bob a week that time they used to, that was the average wage - for a greener. They call 'em greeners. 'Cos they were green you see, they didn't know nothing. And then - them Russian - Jews was - brought over here - by the boat load you se
e. And they had a - place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Lemon Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 where - used - the society was, used to - take them off the boat and hand them out to the different tradesman. A bootmaker wanted a - or shoemaker, they used to go and find that out. He's a bootmaker, he'll come and
 work for you, see. Well 'til they got - settled on their feet - they worked for 'em see. But - some was good mechanics you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were they paid a practical wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I was telling you - four - about five bob a week they used to give 'em and their food, used to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They used to give them their food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, they used to have 'em - bread and - and - and dutch herrings, that was mostly the food - the staple diet. Dutch herrings and food. Sometimes they might have a bit of chicken, 'cos ch
icken was very dear years ago, you could buy chickens for a shilling. See now - chicken is - a pound or more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you think they were all being exploited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they knew that didn't they when they - they get - they got friends. I spoke to an old - Jewish man once and he worked for a - a bootmaker - he was - lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Watling Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. His name they called him in the trade he was Ginger. So they called him Ginger Marr. So this man went to work for Ginger Marr, and he used to sleep in the shop, the ba
ck of the shop, so he used to work in here and sleeping on a - a bench there, like a kind of a sofa that was made, and Jewish people called them soft bunks. Sloth means sleep. Sleeping bunks. And they used to shut 'em up - like a box during the day, them 
s
loth bunks. Well anyhow that man slept in that, and - the '14 war came along, and friend of his told him - used to work from six in the morning - 'til ten o'clock, twelve o'clock at night. Five bob a week. That time. Friday night they didn't work late bec
a
use it was religion - their religious night. So - one - Thursday night his friend - told him, he's coming round for him - there's a job going in - in Whitechapel was a - a - harness contractors there, and they were paying lovely wages for a - anybody can 
s
ew by hand. See, 'cos and all them bootmakers were all hand - good sewing men. So he said, I'll come round for you Thursday and I'll take you up to Great Haley Street is the name of the place, right up - I know the big firm there - right next to the Tilbu
r
y depot, he says to that - Salig, I'll come round Thursday night, and I'll - take you up and introduce you to a man in a pub, he'll tell you what to do. Start work. Well - he - cut a long story short - the guv'nor saw him taking his apron off on this Thur
s
day night - he says to him, his name was Salig, this man, he lived in Jubilee Street 'til he died, he says to him, what you dong Salig, you making half a day today? He'd been at work since six in the morning - and it was ten o'clock at night. And he says 
t
o him, what are you - making a half a day today? Six in the morning 'til ten o'clock at night. And anyhow - that was the words that - that Gigner Myers said to him. Well he - he went and he got the job, and I always re - remember him telling me, you know 
Alf, he says, I heard a lot about gold in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose} from when I was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He said, and the first time I held golden sovereigns in my hand, they gave him two the first week - he worked there. 'Cos that time there was so many - I'll tell you the
 truth, threepence and fourpence it was, you - you paid - fourpence stamp and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 governor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  paid threepence, it was sevenpenny stamp on a man's insurance stamp. Well - when they gave him these two golden sovereigns besides the silver and that, 'course he - 
he had always been picking up five bob a week you see, so he could afford to live without that other - man, you understand. And that's how they lost their - their customer. But - that man, I must say, happily, he worked very hard during that war, that Sal
i
g, he got that job there, then he done - a couple of repairing contracts for the Army, and he finished up a rich man. He had his own business in here - just round the corner here in Jubilee Street, and - then they - then he retired and he became - I think
 
he was - he had some internal trouble and he died - a couple of year back. You know, say four year ago. But he really worked hard that man, and - not a rough - ruffian. He started from nothing, he never had a penny. When the - give him that - he told me, 
w
hen I see them golden sovereigns, he said, I - I kept touching 'em and shining 'em you know, he'd heard a lot about 'em. Of course there was not note money that time you know, beginning of the '14 war here. It only come along afterwards see, the latter pa
r
t of the war. Yes. Poor old Salig. But he - he was a - a sensible man. But, apart from that - what you going to make half a day today? Ten o'clock at night. Yes. A few of the Jewish men, the foreign greeners as I called 'em, used to say to 'em, what time 
a
re you done tonight? So they used to give you one answer. When I'm done I say good morning to the policeman. Know what I mean. When he's done work he says good morning to the policeman when he's going home. He's in a - in there early in the night. That wa
s
 when he - when he was done work. The pressing - the - the tailoring trade they went into consumption over it. Year - hour in and hour out, working, day working you see. Terrible job that was. They went in to T.B. of courses that's how that was, now it's 
different altogether.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When you were a boy how many of your family were at home, how many of your brothers and sisters did you have around when you were about nine or ten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I - I had - when I was say ten, I had three - three or four sisters, four 
sisters that time, and five brothers. Well - was the youngest brother out the five of us. Let's - Sid, Ted, Fred and Joe. Yes. They - they was all in the Army together in the '14 war, all the lot of us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were the sisters still at home at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they was - they was younger see, the sisters are younger, they were the youngest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you know them so well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Or were you closer to your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, we was always with the sisters. The brothers, when th
ey - got up and they went out they - we didn't know what they were doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So when you went hop picking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 There was us together, all of us together, the sisters you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You and your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. My brother - the elder brother - of cou
rse they - they went - they - same as - some of 'em was working when the hop picking season was on, they wouldn't come hop picking. See? They was working you see. Up to the age say - of fourteen or fifteen, then they'd be - at work, most of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So r
eally in your home there was never more than about nine of you, living at home and eating at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
There'd be mum and dad - mum and dad and my three or four sisters say and me and another brother, or say - about eight or something like that on average.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you all eat together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well you take - you - you - never had enough room round them little tables in them kitchens did you. See you - you had your meal and went out and let the next batch in. Specially on a Sunday. Sunday you had - you h
ad your dinner and out, you went out playing, you didn't want to stop indoors. You had other ideas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you if it was wet, would you all stay at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well you - you'd be popping about wouldn't you. Weather didn't worry us I don't think when we was kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 It didn't keep you in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, water, no, we - yes, there was collective times. You see, every poor person had its problems, but some had - was worse that others. Some people knew how to fiddle a shilling or a - a meal - a meal for their table.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you always sit down for meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, but you - but you - you was no - there was no - you had your dinner and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How about your youngest sisters, did they sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, they - you know, they'd have a place there..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How did you used to spend Saturday when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No different to any other day, we went in the City and we stopped there 'til last thing at night, I did. When I was a boy. Saturday was our - harvest day 
wasn't it, the - pay day mostly it was then - years ago. Saturday was. You got - people had a penny to spend - or tuppence, the working classes or - whoever you met you see, the - average Saturday was no difference to other days. Like I told you - if you 
worked on the road, a - a carman, most shops you had to work - 'til six o'clock at night fore you was done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
How about when you were at school and you spent the five days at school, was Saturday any different then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh well, Saturday when you left 
school - you had the weekend to play about in the City didn't you. Or of a night time as well, especially summer time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So when you were a boy about eight to nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. A boy, eight to nine, yes, I was running up the City when I was eight or nine. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You didn't have anything special you'd have to do for your mother on a Saturday?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well if she wanted a thing we'd do it or - or if she gave you orders to bring in the firewood or something like that you went and got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But the rest of the time was yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Oh, not tied down. You were never tied down to do any house - anything unless you volunteered for it to - but you - you had - always had work to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever visit any historic buildings in the City?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes
. Yes? City, I was always round the Tower. I knew - I knew all the church - oh I'll tell you, my first job in the City - I was selling newspapers, and a gentleman came and asked }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  if I'd like to work for him. So I said, what's the work? He said - I'll sho
w you, and took me in the - he was a organ tuner - in the churches, and I went in a few churches with him, and I used to pump the organ, like the little bellows inside the - little box there was. And they had a brass - weight hanging - coming down to a ce
rtain mark. When it gets to that mark you stop. So you keep it - a certain amount of air in the bellows. Them church organs. I remember - I done all Hallows, Barking in - round the back of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Fenchurch Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and two or three churches round there - with him. And then - I don't know what happened, perhaps he got someone else, he went in some other district see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much were you paid for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A couple of shillings a day, that time. Two shillings a day give me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And how many hours would you be required?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh I didn't - didn't reckon up, I suppose - I'd get - I'd see him in the morning, nine o'clock or - be in the afternoon, four or five, six, he'd say - well you can go home now. Give you your money and away you went. Meet me at so and so tomo
rrow, he'd say, cert - another church see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that when you were working full time, was that when you'd left school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, when I'd left school yes. This was my first job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you regard that as a regular enough job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - to st
art with. And then - from there I graduated back to my old work, until I become apprenticed. You see, it must have been - I can reckon up my age - from - see I - I was born beginning of the year, January. So - I had - six years to 1900. I was six years ol
d in 1900. And about 19 - say - 1908 I left school. Well round about 1909 or '10 you see I was doing - all sorts of little jobs for myself 'til I learnt that trade about 1910 or '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 11}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 , went into the boot trade. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You went in as an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I went in as an apprentice, but I didn't stay, I didn't - didn't stay, I only done a twelve month. I thought to myself, I'll never - you know, I was a - I suppose bigheaded that time to myself, you - you can earn more money than this. And when people I
 showed 'em my work, they was - struck with it you see. And I got - oh hundreds of friends here in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose} among the foreign element. They was all bootmakers. There was more bootmakers in - in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose} here, to my knowledge and what was any other 
shop you know. Pubs was the greatest - every street corner was pubs when I was a boy. Pubs and pawnshops as we used to call it. But pubs was the great - but bootmakers, everybody was bootmakers. You see, how it happened was this. Them foreign element - wh
en they come over from - from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, the bootmakers, they got jobs in these factories, you see. Manufacturing - boots. See, bootmakers and manufacturing bootmakers are different bootmaker. See, one is a - well a - I can't explain it, the - they're - they h
aven't got the idea. I knew bootmakers and they - they tell you they're bootmakers, they've been in the trade all their life, they couldn't knock a nail in a boot. They couldn't. Because - they - they've had some other branch of the trade. They've been wo
r
king with a machine all the time. I used to - repair boots for dozens of different shoemakers, in my - life you see. I had a, a - I had - specialized in shoe repairing and - hand sewing work or wooden pegs, you done it, you see, but these men that's worki
ng in the trade, these here factory workers couldn't do that. And - not a lot of 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you apprenticed to a small man yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, a small bootmaker, he learnt me the trade. He -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was he good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, he was a hand sewing man. Yo
u see, he got a - he learnt me the trade, and I decided to leave it you see. I thought to myself, I can get a job. I got a job in Ilford. That didn't last long. I suppose - three or four months, and then I found a - a lovely job in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bow Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, opposite the p
olice station. I was king of the castle there. You see - I - we used to get a lot of money for repairing the shoes. I used to get tuppence for a pair of ladies heels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 This is when you had your own business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, when I was a - worker. Tuppence, t
hat was your price, a third of sixpence you got. It's sixpence was the heels, you got tuppence out of it. If if was one and six the soles and heels you got - a shilling. No, you got sixpence - sixpence, from one and six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And the owner of the shop would keep the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, you got a third, it was always on a third basis, yes. If it was half a crown you got tenpence, and that was how it went on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And how long would - it take you to repair a pair of shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - when - when I was a - I'm 
not - telling lies, when I was young I could - do a pair of shoes, don't matter, mens or womens, in forty minutes. That was our clock we used to say twenty minutes to knock on the soles and heels, and twenty minutes to finish. See, the finishing was - you
 
had to wait for the ink dry and all that that you - used to - I could reckon it up. Five minutes to black a shoe in, that was to file it up, that blacked it in, and five minutes to finish it. That's to put the heel bore on and make it look nice and clean 
a
nd polished off fancy work afterwards. It took five minutes to set the edges and heels, and put the ink on, and another five minutes to use the warm irons to - burnish it. Where the machines today don't do no burnishing, they just polish. See, when we get
 
edge years ago by hand it - it stopped there. Stopped that shape you pressed it in. See, the - the iron what you used is the shape what you wanted and - went round that - very good, but then it was - everybody had ideas of their own about work, and that w
as how it was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
So after a year as an apprentice you decided you didn't want to do it, what did you do after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I - I become a journeyman, and - also a businessman in the City, like I told you, selling little odds and ends. Newspapers, anythin
g what come - we could find. Postcards around the Tower, we had seasons for everything. And markets for everything. The Tower was one - that time - oh, was a different place altogether, the Tower.. See, one side of Tower Hill - is Metropolitan police, the
 other side is the City police. You see. The other side of the road. See, there's - City Police over there and there's Metropolitan police here, round that railing of the Tower comes under the Metropolitan police, from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Leman Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And a few yards away is 
- Custom House, the next - first what there - or - brewers quay as they call it - and that's the City. That's the City police standing in the middle of the road there directing traffic, and there's a - a Metropolitan policeman standing on the pavement.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have much dealing with either of these police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, they all knew - they knew me. Oh I found - found that little - half a - I found a little badge to go on me arm, it was number 995, got on it City Corporation with the Coat of Arms, little red badge went round on your arm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That's when you were a newspaper boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Anything you sold in the City. You had to have a licence - that time. And - that was the first year they come out, it must have been - either 1910 or '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 11}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 , something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How long did you go on doing this selling before you opened your own business?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - I went to work - in two or three places - you see - and you pick up experience going from shop to shop, this one's got one idea, he's got another, y
ou learn off of one you learn off another, you see, and - time I collected a set of what I call a kit of good tools for myself - I picked up a lot of information. 'Course then - to top it, the war came along. The 1914 war. I was eighteen when that war bro
ke out. You see, well then - then I - done a bit of war service. And then I come back, and I - worked for a boot - Army bootmaker up in - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Leman Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. I managed his place there for him, giving the workmen out all their work. Cutting the leather and one 
thing and another, I was like a bit of a manager there. And then after that I - I was working in a place, they had a strike. The bootmakers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What date was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 About 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 End of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd come out the services?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I come out the service, yes. And I went to work in a place in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Leman Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I had - a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 Boot repairers}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Union{\*\xmlclose}
 somewhere up there that - the foreign element, not the - Englishmen. These Jewish men and - they decided something they were going on strike, used to get - half a crown a pair - that time - for mending these Army boots, blocking 'em up in a tree, like - 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 bracing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 'em up, and - jobs - and they got up, they - they went on strike anyhow, and the guv'nor said to me, I remember him, he was called Little Joe. This Little Joe, he - he had his shop right to recent years and - I suppose he's go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 ne now, passed away, but Little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Joe said to me, set down there - when the others went - oh they put their coats and hats on and they walked out. So I didn't know really
, they're speaking in - Yiddish that time, I didn't - have the strength like I've got now with the language, and - but I understood they - they had a union somewhere on the back of the Tilbury depot in Commercial Road. And they - the union - they was goin
g
 to - they - run away from Little Joe, not to work for him. But he said to me, sit down Alf. You do - your work, I'll give you another sixpence a pair more than what they get, because your worth ten sixpences more. You see, I was a bit of a - although I w
as only a youngster, twenty, in me twenties, I was a mechanic according to him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever belong to the boot repairers union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well there wasn't one, that was the one they'd started. There were some boot trade union - up the side of the childre
ns hospital in Hackney, but that was for the manufacturing side, but - there was never any powerful union in the shoe re - trade - not then. Not when I was a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did this strike work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. No. I sat down, I got that sixpence a pair extra and th
ey come back and - and sat down to work for the same. He said to me, sit down, you get sixpence a pair, every pair you do, you're not to say nothing about it. And I sat down and - I had - done it. 'Cos it was a standing joke up that - neighbourhood, I was
 the only shoemaker there could drive a horse and van.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where did you get the experience doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 With my dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What age were you when you did that, how old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh I was - always with the horses, if I could only get a - on a hor
se and van, I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 happy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 as a sandboy, go with me brothers or me - father, or dad, see, he - you gain an experience of that. You get used to horses and you get used to the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you actually drive them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, I was a - I was a carman as well as you call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that after you left school again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When I was growing up, say about - when I was - seventeen to twentyish see, and up to the war - when the war come along - 'course I was - a expert carman, besides being a shoemaker, see. I could drive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you quite enjoy that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, I like it, I liked the horses, you see, at that time you see, I never had a reference for that. But a friend of mine gave me a reference - he was in Billingsgate and he - I told him, I said, I can ge
t a good job with my dad but I must have a outside reference, I don't want my dad for a reference or anything like that. So - I got the job there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you be earning then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 The - the - on the vans - roughly - round about twenty-five bob a 
week, that's all they got. Twenty-four to - twenty-seven was a - in 1912 strike - the 1912 strike - worked out for every single horse van, that's - heavy van - you got twenty-seven shillings a week, some still got less. Twenty-seven shillings a week. They
 give you a bob - about a bob for a pair. You know. Another sixpence a day for having two horses you know what I mean, or three. It was around - six bob more or less, you - you was a driver and you - you drove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But you could get more as a shoemaker?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes. Definite, yes. Yes, yes, I could - you see, yes, you see well then - all the time I was working as a driver I was practicing with my shoemaking as well. Oh yes, Saturday, weekends you know, I - I never - other boys went out, I - I used to - do
 two or three jobs for people. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever make shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes, yes, I made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much would you charge for a pair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - that was - that - they - I never took on the new - like the big new work but I worked in the sho
ps making them, you know what I mean. I never took on jobs, but it's - you see - I have friends - you - you get friends you see when you work in the trade, you meet one another in a load of shops. And I used to have an old man lived up beside me - and I'l
l
 tell you about wages in a minute. He - I can remember now, he used to make three pair of boots a week. Yes. And he got a lot of money for that. He got twenty-four shillings. Eight shillings a pair. Now that man - you ask about these boots one day - what 
w
e call last them up you know, pin 'em up, then he sewed the welts in. Then he sewed the soles on, put the heels on and next day finish them. Two days - two days work - on a pair of boots and he got eight shillings. And hard work. Because if you work good 
y
ou work hard. In - in the boot repairing if you make a good edge, it's - you're using pressure and when you're using pressure it's work. Well - that's all that man got, about eight shillings and eight and six a pair. Old Mr Robinson. It was - wicked, the 
t
rade was. 'Course now it's different altogether. You see - I met a man - a couple of year back, he was - well he'd be a - a lot over ninety now if he was alive, he used to say - Alf - they wouldn't do work like you now. Because if a boot wanted sewing I s
e
wed it, I didn't knock nail into 'em then. We used to sew - have it sewn. Much better. I - I made eight - pair of - soles in a day. Sewn. That was my record. I used to - I tell you what I used to do. Used to have a ball of hemp - in a box. And - the wax a
n
d the bristles what you put on it - and I used to - when I get home of a night make them at home. I'd always have - a pair - a dozen pair of waxed threads in my box. So if a pair of hand sewn - job come in - see, the guv'nor never had to - buy thread. He 
o
nly had the workmen to do it, and they used to say, how much do you want, we charge a shilling extra, I said, but - whatever you charge extra I want. Suit you? Well I used to get off of some of 'em one and six see, two bob. But 'course today - it's all do
ne by machine you see. The stitching machine come along, for fourpence - you could take 'em and have 'em stitched round for fourpence, pair of - and it's done in two ticks, but that never lasted like hand sewn job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever get very poor people coming in with rather ragged ......?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes. The poor - poor devils - had boots hanging off their feet, and no - no heels on - on them - on 'em. You had to build them up from the bottom.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you take on jobs like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, what for a poor
 person, yes. Built 'em up, the heels and that. I've had 'em come in - help 'em out. I - I done a lot of work for the police, I - had a lot - hundreds and hundreds of policeman customers. You see, they - they like a good job done those - boys did. And the
y
 mostly had biggish feet you know, big chaps. 'Course that time they didn't take little men in the police. Very seldom, it was all - hefty men, all had tens, elevens boots. Very seldom you see a policeman rather - tens and elevens boots and - see, but now
 it's different, they've got a different type of man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
What were the police like before the first world war, what was their attitude towards people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh all right, they weren't - they - they never said a lot, they never spoke a lot. They just - don
e their job. They weren't ruffians, those men. They were - what I call - a different type of man - person. They were brought up to - in their job they were conservative ideas you see, their ideas of life. Not - and then they had a bit of a union come in t
h
e police and - and they had a strike in 1919. I knew a - a City policeman in - in the strike, he was right through the four - the '14 war, he come home out the '14 war, they had that strike after the war, and he finished up as a care - a bootmaker in - in
 
Billingsgate, mending boots he was. Mending the - fishmongers hats and boots, and he was a - one of the heads of the police that man, he was a union man see. He joined the union and he come out on strike and - he was put off from the City Corporation. He'
s a lovely chap. I knew him quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
What was the attitude of the police towards children who were doing things wrong in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, any - they - give you a clump pound the ear and set you home and - they didn't - do anything, always some children have suffered in the past for - paltry things you know, sent away to prison. I know a boy picked a cabbage up in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he - he was sent to prison. Yes. It fell off a market van coming up from Dagenham, and he picked it up. And he got 
- taken to the court. For stealing, see, he was charged with stealing. Well there was lots of things done under the hand, and lots of things what no one knew about you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were boys taken from their homes and sent to remand homes in those days like t
hey are now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes. Yes, taken to - sent to industrial schools a lot of boys if you - if you played the truant you could be sent to an industrial school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was the industrial school, they taught you and trained you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well some o
f them, most of them, yes. But those industrial schools - was - they're not like the other schools you see, you had a - a stigma on your name. You was in a prison school as they called it. See, industrial school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You said your brother once .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, he went to - he played the truant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That means that he was away from school and someone found him did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He - he left - he - he'd - he'd - instead of going to school he'd played truant, never went to school. And he was - in the City, somebody had give him something, I don't know what it was - but - he told my - that he had no parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why did he say that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He was afraid that his mother and father would hit him for being away - not at school. See, so they put him in industrial school. And he went to Manchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How did your parents get him out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He - they didn't get him out at all, he stopped there and - from there when he left school fourteen he went into the railway - depot there. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}London Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So he was right away from home several years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He got a job, yes. He was sent away, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were your parents upset about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I - I - I'll say that, I suppose they were. He was older brother to me, two brothers older than me. Ted. And he become a - he - h
e worked in the engine sheds at London - at London Road there - Victoria Station whatever it is there, Manchester, and - in later years you see, everybody on the railway know him. 'Course on the few occasions I went to - see him off - from Euston station 
o
f a night, you'd generally here - ten o'clock at night when he went, or something like that - all the drivers and - and - and people on the trains all knew him. He was some - supervisor in the union or something. See, he - he was a known man, 'cos he were
 always traveling backwards and forwards to - the union Headquarters what I think is up there, somewhere in Euston Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there much criminal activity going on in this part of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes - everywhere weren't it. In the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
East End{\*\xmlclose} 
it was a recognised thing. You see, everybody - tried to help theirself years ago. You see, that's how it was - they - they see you growing a apple so they - so - so somebody in the village want to take - pinch it from you. That's how life went that time.
 You see. They had no other alternative ways of having it, only stealing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You mentioned pawn shops, were there a lot of pawn shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, there was hundreds of pawn shops everywhere you went was pawn shops. In this - this district alone - I 
- during the - during the was I - found some - empty tickets of a pawn shop what was bombed out here in Stepney, and I picked up a few of 'em - bundles of 'em, these - bare tickets, and we used to write on them things, so I've write on one - I've write on
 one once - one copper, fourpence. See? And I'd ask a policeman if he want to buy a pawn ticket. That was a joke, friendly - policeman. One - one copper - fourpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What percentage of people would use a pawn shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Everybody what wanted a shillin
g. Instead of going to a moneylender. See - when you went to a moneylender he could refuse you wouldn't he, or he could. And once you got in the hands of a moneylender - they hold you by the neck more or less. They give you something that - that they char
g
e you so much in the pound - in a shilling each week. If they lent you a shilling - see, they want a penny a week for that shilling. They lent you a pound they want one and eightpence a week. That was - that was how it went on and that still goes on like 
that, even these big - advertising the - paper. Would you like a sweet? Yes, they - that - that - still goes on, that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So who would use moneylenders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
People wanted to borrow money. Anybody whats desperate didn't want to know anyone - or if anybod
y say never had any clothes to pawn, or hadn't got anything pawnable - see if I wanted like - a - a few pound, all you've got to say is take your ring in there and you'll get it. Your money off a pawnbroker. He stopped you straight away the - interest on 
i
t, what he gave you. If he lent you a pound he stopped so much interest straight away, you didn't get the pound. See, say the interest was - so much on the pound interest, that stop straight away for the ticket, so much for the ticket and so much for the 
i
nterest. Then when you've got to give it out - there it was, see the longer it's in the - the more you - interest you have to pay on the article, 'cos people pawned things and never got 'em out again. So they never - give 'em the - the right value you see
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The pawnbrokers then would sell this stuff, what was the time you were allowed to get it back again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well twelve months wasn't it, that was the - allowed you twelve months before it become redundant more or less. Unless you could go to a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 magistrate}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  and - and get affidavit, they used to do that. If you lost a ticket you went to a magistrate and - asked for a - affidavit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What type of person would be a pawnbroker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They was like shops, in - like jewellers and that, jewellers shops and -
 all sorts. Some of 'em had lovely }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 jewellery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you say they were honest men on the whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - their business made them greedy for gold didn't it. You see, they were money grabbers just the same. I remember pawn broker here who let 
people have their parcel out on a Sunday morning. They couldn't get it Saturday night, they never had the money. They could - they worked 'til late and the pubs - shops were shut. Oh pawn brokers were the - you see, they don't - sign of a pawnbroker - is 
a
 betting sing. There's three brass balls. And the - all the sensible people used to always say, you know what it stands for? Say no. It's two to one you don't get 'em out. That's a betting - it's two to one that you don't get 'em out, that's why they've g
ot three brass balls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
How much would you get, what would you get for a suit or something, what would you get from a pawnshop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A suit - I'll tell you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Before the first world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Up to say ten bob. Or perhaps - they'd give you a little
 more. The less they give you - if you left it there, they'd more profit they got didn't they. I'll tell you a true thing about that. In the - I went away in the Army. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portsmouth
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I went away - and I was away say - just over six months. Before I come back 
on leave. When I came back on leave, the first leave - I looked for my clothes, they had gone. I says to mum, where's me boots and suit? I want to put - civilian clothes on see. I've got Army clothes. She give me the tickets, there you are. So - I went ro
und to the pawnbroker, he used to have a little shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Stepney Way{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, where that park is now, and he - give me the suit and the boots, I think the lot come to seven and six. See, the boots and - I think she - she got - two and six for the boots and five bob 
for the suit, or something like that. Not much more. Anyhow, I put my hand in the pocket of the trousers, and I found a wallet. What I was looking for. In it was eight golden sovereigns. This is true. So - I says to Mr Jones, that was his name, I says to 
Mr Jones, well - I'm not broke today. He said, well we never touch pockets, he says. He says, we put 'em straight in the - your mum's bought 'em in all these years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 It's supposed to be true that if you had your suits hung up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well they - they used to hang 'em up, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they always hang them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Or would you pay more for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, you'd pay - a certain - little extra used to charge for that, but this is the - the truth. If I would have had that - my mother found that 
purse before she pawned that suit - I would - the suit would have been and the money have gone and all. But it seems luck she never searched the pockets you see. But I think after that she went through always the pockets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You told her about this did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, I told her what he'd pawned, I showed her it. Showed her a little leather wallet, it used to have little slots in it, put your pounds and ten shillings in they were made that time. Yes. That was real funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 It was very fortunate though wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you think it might have gone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, that was definitely of course - first thing I - before - before - I never said nothing to the - pawnbroker, but as soon as he gave me the suit on the counter - it - I done it an
d - put me fingers in the pocket and there it was. That was a sigh of relief. You see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Eight of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 sovereigns}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  was a lot of money in those days wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Mm. I had a friend, the - he was a boxer, he's in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now. He - me and him used to go to an old man in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Great Haley Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, we used to have a suit made to order, with two pair of trousers. All made by - well more or less hand you know, bar the - necessary machining. But - the - you had two pair of trousers to every suit and he never charged us m
ore than about three pound ten, never. Three pound five, three pound ten, that old boy. That - that was dear times, but the suit would last you - ten, fifteen years, with care. You had two pair of trousers to it. Don't matter what colour, that was the ord
e
r, and he made - he was a real tailor, you know, a mechanic, that old boy. I think he give the waistcoats, he made the - trousers and the - they made one section of 'em - do - say the coat, and they give the trousers - they cut the stuff, they give it to 
their different machinists, to make the trousers up and the waistcoat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would you say there's a difference between the skilled man and the unskilled worker in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. A skilled man in - was a skilled man and unskilled, well it's the s
ame now. You see, the same now. A skilled worker can always command a job and get a job see, where an unskilled man couldn't you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about the differences in pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh well there, there - the pay would be it - in it wouldn't it, but the - wa
ges years ago was - not fair at all. There was sweated labour as you call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But it was worth doing an apprenticeship to be a skilled man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you respected more as well by the community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes, even now when I - I - \{BLANK\}
 See when - when they was - when I was a boy and - the police knew you - the railway police at Fenchurch Street I used to run errands for, run down to Whitechapel, they opened a fried fish shop, John Isaacs that time. Oh - that w
as the name of it, fried fish shop, you could get a bit of fish and chips, well that time - fish and chips in the back streets you could get ha'penny bit and ha'porth. And that was my favourite supper, a ha'penny bit and ha'porth. And of course in that sh
o
p down Whitechapel when they opened they were a bit more expensive. Isaacs. They - they opened a fried fish shop. And - I used to run down and get 'em some chips and fish for their supper you see. 'Cos them men had to work 'til past twelve at night them p
olicemen at - on the railway. 'Cos the - the last train didn't go 'til about twelve from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Fenchurch Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to - Southend. Very often they say - go and get us a couple of pen'orth of fish and chips you know. The City police as well - fancied them see, 'cos th
is was a new thing, a fried fish shop coming here. There was two or three shops in the City sold pork pies and things like that. Harris'. There was Harris' sausage place, you could go and have hot sausages in - in the City and chips and all things like th
at, but when the fried fish shops started - then - in - just this side of Petticoat Lane it was, in High Street Aldgate, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Is this when they were off duty or were they on duty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 On duty see, well they'd say, go and get me that, well we'd - we'
d willingly run down there, 'cos they sometimes give you a penny see, a penny was a lot of money to us. It was all profit you see. See, for - for a ha'penny you could get a mug of tea in Lockhart's 'til twelve o'clock at night. You can't get that now. Ha'
penny - ha'penny slice of bread and jam and ha'penny mug of cocoa - tea, coffee or cocoa was only a ha'penny, a small mug what the call it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So was it quite lively around midnight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, everywhere -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Everybody wasn't in bed by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, everything was alive. You used to see - see there was no electric lights - it was all gas. And darkness, and when anywhere where they lit up with all these little gas jets they used to have - rows and rows of little gas jets burning, with no mantle. 
J
ust the jets. And that used to light the place up. Oh everything was lit up - any shops opened you see, then when the - when I was - getting on, say round about fourteen, they started - letting you in picture palaces, you could go in some for a penny, som
e for a ha'penny. There was one round here you could go - Silverland they call it - ha'penny - go and see the pictures for a ha'penny. Bioscope they called - or whatever they called it. See it was no - talkie pictures, nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 These were just the silent ones with the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
But there you could - they show the show and then that - you all went out you see. There was - they started one up at Aldgate next to Houndsditch there. I think it's a photo shop called - or barbers shop, something n
ow there. And - that was a penny pictures, oh it was a - great treat to see a penn'orth of pictures see. See trains on the pictures you know, I've seen it - I've seen 'em - one occasion - we're sitting down, the train come along on the bioscope and the pe
o
ple all got up and ran out because they thought the train was coming in the room to 'em see, 'course it's coming on the picture. But it put - and there's not noise and it - of course they used to play in all those pictures that time - pianos or organ. The
y
 had all music for the pictures see, and play - always play music to the pictures they did. And that's - what used to go on. That was early entertainment. There was all - you'd see a woman there, tattooed lady, go in for a penny you could. Or you could go
 
and see a man swallowing a sword for a penny. It's - you know, but the tattooed lady and a - I remember one tattooed lady, she must have weighed about eighteen stone - from her hair - right down to her ankles she was tattooed all over her body. 'Cos she o
nly showed you that time but it - to see things like that on a woman, it was a novelty, all tattooed she was, all the way over, from her wrists right up to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 
Herneck}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 . And some - a couple of little birds on her face and - oh - she was a - real - and the - ther
e was another big woman, used to be - have a - a little four in hand, four little Shetland ponies - and one of the old fashioned stage coaches on a small scale see, she used to travel about in that. She was a show lady. I forget now what she was doing, bu
t there used to be all them amusement shows up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Whitechapel Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in them - shops and that. It's all pulled down now, it's all new buildings up there, where the Salvation Army is. Where that Salvation Army's new home is there now - in Whitechapel Road - it's 
- like it used to be a - a rail - a railway station there, St Marys, Whitechapel, well it's all gone now, that side, that's a garage there, big garage. And this side of the road is the Salvation Army, they were all shops so they built a new - home there f
o
r these - people that want to - you know, got no homes and they - can afford to pay the rent there. See - in - when I was young, in Whitechapel was a - a lodging house called Rowton House. And - the - price to stop there was sevenpence a night. See? Seven
 
seven's is forty-nine, that's four and a penny a week, isn't it. But if you was a regular customer there - they only charged you for six nights. Six - three and fourpence a week, just only the lodging, you could lodge - you had a lodging in there and you 
c
ould wash, and then they had like a - refreshment rooms in there, you could buy things, it was like a little poor man's hotel, Lord Rowton, he had a big place at Kings Cross as well. But now, what I was - talking - see now they have to pay about ten or el
even shillings a night, for - that - that time was only - sevenpence a night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Who would go to Rowton House in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Men away from their wives, men got no homes. See, a man saying - many - many a man's had a good job work - liked in there. 
They had special rooms there I think for a couple of shillings extra a week private, - places, they had lockers to keep their things in, private lockers, they paid so much for the key for that, little locker they give. But that was the fee that was charge
d
, that time. Of course the people that really lived there as I say was people perhaps parted from their wife or - all like that you see. But they still wanted to work. So if a man had a job you see - or like now - now this time - a lot of men are out of w
ork, but they get their old age pension. They're still living in those places, and they can afford out of their pension or social help what they get and their social security act to carry on. See well years ago when I was a boy there was none of that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Rowton House was quite a respectable place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, it was respect - if you was dirty you went in there - and dirtied any sheets or anything - and it was reported, they wouldn't let you sleep there no more. They'd say, not tonight. I remember a case,
 a man, he was a newspaper man, he got killed in the 1914 war this chap. And he stood outside Stepney Green station selling newspapers for years. The war come along, he joined the Army and away he went and he was - he never come back. Well he was living i
n
 Rowton House, he was away from his wife. And he had a wart on his neck, and - and - a - a wart was hanging on his neck, like a - disfigurement and the man behind the counter like, the clerk, they had him taking the money for the lodgings of a night, he s
a
id, not tonight. So this chap, I remember him telling me, he said, I asked him what - why he want me to go - stay there. He says, you've got something - crawling on your neck. And he looked at the chap, he says - I'm very sorry to tell you that's not - th
a
t - that's nothing crawling, it's a wart whats come there, and they let him back there. But they thought it was a - a - a - he had a louse on him. Yes. He was a little fat red faced chap, he stood outside Stepney Green station - see now, the years has pas
s
ed on, his name slipped me, and I know it well. Yes. That name and he - but he got - I ; definitely - he got killed in the '14 was, 'cos I was - a young man about his age you see, or he might be a bit older than me. Yes, he was older than me but - he'd be
 
over - about eighty-five I reckon if he was alive. Yes, he never came back, I remember 'em saying - he's gone. He used to have a - see - if you had a stand - that was your stand, selling newspapers, and he stood right outside Stepney Green station. Inside
 
Stepney Green station was Smiths the big people. But they didn't stand outside, he - he - his - his - he stood outside on the public - on the pavement. Yes, most - they call 'em pitches. You took up these pitches and if it paid of course some of 'em was g
old mines. See, those pitches. In the City especially.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you remember you mentioned Aldgate, there were a lot of slaughterhouses?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, the - Aldgate meat market.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you tell us about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, well - when I was - young and tha
t that was a - all the butchers shops was - had their own slaughterhouses at the back, you used to go in and watch 'em - kill 'em you see. The Jewish people - we - of course you see the Jewish people - they - they kill what they call kosher killing. They 
d
on't - pole axe any animal. Any - anything what's been pole axed - it's all got to be cut - the - the neck, see, so - what they used to do - the calves for instance, we used to go and watch 'em kill the calves and when - then they - they tie - tie up thei
r
 back legs, the two legs, and they're pulled up - hanging, and this - rabbi comes along - with a - a - very - sharp razor knife, and - and - and they bleed to death. They cut 'em and bleed, and the blood runs down and it's taken away to somewhere else for
 
black puddings and all like that, see, but the Jewish people - that was their market, where they killed all their - Jewish food. See, well, now it was - of course they killed English food as well as their, but of course - the Jewish people only eat what t
h
ey call the forequarters of the animal, they don't eat the hind quarters like we have rump steak, they don't have that part of a beef, they only have the - front shoulders as I call 'em. And - half his - the - eat - eaten by the Jews and half is eaten by 
us - Christians. The back part is eaten with us, yes. Yes. But the shoulders and - front legs of a - a bullock or any animal is eaten by the Jews, it's koshered, see, and by killing it kosher with a reverend it's kosher meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And these animals were driven up, where did they come from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, Romford - Romford, mostly Romford market they come. Used to see 'em driving along. Herds of animals come up that - sheep and all. Some come - of course the - you - they never had the big containers - vans that
 they've got today. They could fetch one bullock up at a time in a - with a - a - a single horse van. A tip up cart it used to be more or less. A big high cart, they put one in it, but - the - the driver that drove - see, from Romford cattle market, from 
E
ssex where most of the animals that time come, English meat see, the Jews don't eat foreign meat, they only have English meat. And that was their market. And of course and - in recent - after - well a few years - about the war time or just after the war, 
it was transferred to Islington cattle market. They made a branch there of it, so Aldgate market more or less disappeared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there any horsemeat butchers around at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, there was plenty of horsemeat butchers here, but they were over Bethn
al Green. The one opposite that - back of Whitechapel station was one, a big 'un. In that little turning right the back of the station, it's called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Winthrop Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that was Harrison and Barbers, they were a big people. They used to kill all the horses, and then there was two or three others, but they were the chief slaughterers of pig - horsemeat in the East End.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Who would buy horse meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Everybody for their cat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Not for eating themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh no. That - that came along after. Some peo
ple - when the war came along - took a fancy to it 'cos it's sweeter meat than - you see - I've heard in my time, why people eat horse meat - it's like - they've got no gall bladder, like a - other animal, so the meat is naturally sweet. A pigeon is the s
ame. A pigeon and a horse - have got no gall bladder I've been always told. And the Belgian people always used to use the - horsemeat on the Continent. When I was a boy, down the side of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Tower{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} there is a wharf there - it's called - Brewer's Quay. And
 there - all the horses used to be driven down there of a night time, you see 'em - going along four - tied together with a stamp on their - stuck on 'em - where these - Belgian people have bought 'em, and they used to go away on them boats, well most of 
t
hose old horses was - dilapidated poor - worn out, they wasn't - young and virile, well some of 'em looked nice but - they was mostly old - old horses. Yes, used to see them there, going across the bottom of - Cable Street or - that was the name - startin
g
 of it, you see, around Tower Hill, right down Tower Hill, just by the entrance to the Tower - was where they used to take 'em, on that wharf, and they used to - put 'em on these ships and take them across to the Continent. 'Course they run regular those 
b
oats did you know. And you'd see the men sitting on the horses go driving along of a night. Don't suppose they got more than about five bob a day if they got that them men. That's how - twelve hours a day. Lord knows where they drove the horses from you k
n
ow what I mean. Well that's what went on, well people wouldn't eat that here, only for cats meat. See, cats meat - was - everybody had cats. It was all houses - and some had two cats or three cats see. They wasn't fussy that time, it was all cats - over t
h
e mice. And pets. Mostly it was for mice. And rats. And then - everybody bought cats meat see, and cats meat was dearer to buy than what - lamb was. In Bethnal Green Road - was a stall, I can see it now, and that's a long while ago. Cats meat was fourpenc
e and sixpence a pound. The cheapest cats meat was fourpence. A pound. And on the stall for human consumption was strips of mutton tuppence and tuppence ha'penny a pound. This is true that is.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there many rats about the houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Rats,
 yes. I caught one as a kid, I - used to - a hobby of catching 'em. Yes, this was our hobby that - catch rats and mice. Well you couldn't - every house had 'em that time didn't they. I - I - I caught a rat - my brother made me a trap from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He ma
de it out of - all - steel as you call it, iron. And it was a bait back trap with a strong spring and I got the - used to that, and I used to - bait most of the rat traps what we used, we was always taught brown herring. Well a brown herring - I don't kno
w
 if you ever seen a brown herring have you? Well, it's a ordinary herring, smoked, only it's - goes a chocolate brown, dark brown. Well that used to be the great attraction for - used to - burn it, put it on the fire and we - really put it and burnt - say
 
the head or a piece of this browned herring, it was - got a very pungent odour. See it was smoked - herring. And - you could buy them for a ha'penny each, threefarthing, a penny. You could always buy a ha'penny brown herring. Now they want about a shillin
g
 or more for that now, or two bob, anyhow - that's what we used to bait 'em with. The tail piece, especially that tail, 'cos it's more or less solid. Put it on your trap, fasten it, and then - we used to - melt it as I call it on the - on a light or on th
e
 gas, make that pungent smell, and that catch - caught any rat. Well once the rat got in that cage it couldn't get out. Of course we used to tie the cage with a long lump of string see, so we set the - set the trap over there and have this bit of string h
e
re so - if the rat pulled it down the hole if there was a hole there like they have done, you could pull the string and pull him out and see if he's alive or not, then we used to finish him off ourselves, we was very gentle children you know, that time, w
i
th those sort of things. Cruel. We didn't know the word of cruelty. And yet we was kind to any animals. We wouldn't hurt a dog or a cat or anything like that. Pigeons or anything. Or a sparrow or anything we found. But rats we was - that was our enemy. Be
c
ause they came in our house and stole the food didn't they. Well - cor luv a duck, rats was a - up - I - I caught a rat, this is true, with that trap my brother made me - by the tail. And that rat bit its tail off. He escaped. About - I should say - a mon
th }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 a little over after I caught that rat. That - minus his tail. He'd bit it off. See, the first time I caught only the tail. He - to get away he bit his tail off, and about six weeks or so, something like that, I caught that rat again, and that tail had
n't even healed up properly. You see, that's wild life you see. Yes, but we - we was that we - we was used to it as children, see. That's why lots of people wouldn't - go in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 or wherever they were. You see, everywhere you went was stables years
 ago, everybody had a horse and van, wherever horse and van was - there was always in - those sort of animals looking - for food. Then they come up in the drains most rats do, they come - up broken lavatories see, where a broken drain is, that's where the
 
rats escape from the main drain. See, where if there's a broken drain they come through that. Oh I've - well - I've - endless places you could see 'em - rats, wherever you went. Of a night - even now you go about you see rats running around. Over Wapping 
there for instance, there's some - running alive with 'em. Near those old wharves and that you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So a lot of the houses were very unsanitary were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, all of 'em. Yes, well look - look - look where I came from for here. I lived in that house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Golden Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 from a little boy. We moved - come out of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Silver Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and went into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Gold Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I - got married from that house, and then when I got bombed out in my shop, I had a little shop, and I got bombed out, and then - I - my sisters w
ent over to Morden and I took their house off of 'em. I said, to the landlord, can I have that house? Yes, certainly. See, I had a - I had a - they used to call me Mr Gotts that time, see, easy now, I've got - had a rise, Mr Gotts, I was a respected perso
n, but - when you're not respected they call you by some nickname, a - Alf - old Alf, you - something like that, that's how life is today, yes, but - that's true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When you were a boy if men were called mister would that mean that they were respected?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, if you - if you give a man a prefix, see - I worked in the Post Office - after a - after the war - I sold my shop. I heard that was going to be all pulled down, all the - places and that, they give me compensation no doubt, but I didn't stay f
or that. I sold a chap - a young chap come out the Army, and he'd learnt a bit of boot repairing in the Army like that - he was - what you call a - a sick soldier, and they learnt them some trade, after care, and he sold - he told me about it, I said, wel
l I - I'll let him have my shop if he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 it. Have all the trade and I guarantee I won't take one customer from him, if they come to me I'll send 'em to him. He - couldn't be no fairer than that could I? And I did, I sold him the shop and I had a - three
 months holiday, I never - worried no more. And then - I thought to myself, well I must do a job 'til I'm sixty-five. And - and then I - I went and got a job in the Post Office, see, when they - you got a - if you've got a clean character and - and got a 
- you've got good references you see you can get these jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did you do in the Post Office?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I was a - boilerman - cleaner. The boilerman was the chief - thing you see - I knew how to look after boilers. I want - they train you how to send y
ou in different offices, you know, say a man's gone sick - and - it's very hard to get them on I could see now, boilermen. It's hard work for the - some of 'em, and anybody ain't got no physical - what I call energy in 'em - they - they're - they're usele
s
s because they neglect things. Well anyhow - I went to Vic docks, what they call - over the docks there near the Albert docks, and the man had gone sick. He'd been there about twenty years. And - next door is a - the other Post Office where they sell the 
s
tamps and that see, this was the sorting office where I had to go. And this man had gone sick, this here boilerman, the cleaner. That's the term. So - they asked me if I would take the job on. I said, yes. So this guv'nor said to me - do you think you cou
l
d do anything to the boiler make the water - it was wintertime you see. See I hadn't been in the house - shop five minutes as I call it, like the - Post Office, so he said - he said, you could hot the pipes up for us? I said, I'll have a look. Went down i
n
 the boilerroom, right down underground it is. And I opened the doors of the boiler, and - low and be hold I could see what the trouble was. They hadn't cleaned the clinker out. On the bottom door, say about a foot high, right the way through the length o
f the boiler was a long boiler like a Lancashire boiler, was about a foot of solid concrete - clinker, there was knives and forks and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 spoons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  and tin cans sticking in the clinker, see, wasn't hot enough for - some of it melted, some of it didn't. Old - old l
umps of metal, what the man in the next Post Office instead of him taking his rubbish from his kitchen to the dustbin, he was a tipping it in this man's boiler. And that man - yes, and that man was drinking heavily at the time, he wouldn't take no notice 
o
f it. But they weren't getting the heat in the boiler, because - the main part of the boiler was blocked up with solid metal clinker. So what I did, I broke away this, I must have had about - thirty hundredweight to two ton of clinker, in lumps. Hundred -
 
weight pieces, well I broke it right out, right through the boiler. Well, I cleaned it out, and I lit the boiler - I got the boiler going and within a half an hour I got hot water - all over the building. And that man came down to me, he - see - he said t
o
 me - and he used a funny expression, he says, it's the first time I've had a warm since I've been in this so and so office. He swore. And I told him what was the cause of it, I said, look there's the cause. I said, it's - I may not be here - in future bu
t if you see that in the bottom of a boiler - I said, when you open the bottom door you can see it. It - it's solid right through on the - 'course I told him that and they wrote - they - of course they gave me a good character didn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that the last job you ever had before you retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, the Post Office, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So you've had quite a mixture of jobs through your life haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, I was a shoemaker -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 The shoemaker was your main trade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh when I was younger I worked in the - you know, in the City and all like that. Yes, 'til I settled down, you know, when you settle down you - see but - after the 1914 war - things was - a bit - dodgy, and there was no money about and in }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 every back}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 street was a hundred shoemakers, as they call it. Everywhere you went was a bootmakers shop in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
, 'cos there was the foreign element in here. Like you've got the coloured people - now, we had that time the Russian Jews. They were the poor devils that come from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
, that catch - to evade the Army out there, they came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I was first in my trade - in the East End here, they never knew how to speak English, they - they - everything they asked you for, if they wanted a light, they
 asked for it in Yiddish, they didn't ask for it in English. They wanted a fork or they wanted anything they spoke Yiddish to you so you had to pick up the language, and - so - you could understand 'em. Book in Whitechapel for a shilling. It - that's one 
s
ide in - writ in English and on the other side writ in Yiddish the word, so if you wanted knife, that's massa, laffa, spoon, fork, gigpel, all like that, right - and - and the other side it showed you in - Yiddish what it was. One side was English, and I 
b
ought that for a shilling, a translation book, and I learnt more or less to learn their language. Bread, butter, anything you see. Well - in - I showed the children across the street - for a few years when I first retired - and this was - this school here
, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dempsey Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and the other school up the other end is - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Ashmiddle Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school, and they used to go from this school of a dinnertime the children to that school to have dinner. So two little Jewish boys passing by every day - spoke to me like and nodd
ed to me as I helped them across the road - and - one day one of these little Jewish boys said to me, excuse me guv'nor are you a - a Jew? I - looked for a minute, and I spoke to him like this. Was wilsta of my laten? That means, what do you want of my li
f
e? So one little Jewish boy said to the other, I told you so didn't I. He is a Jewish man. So I called them back, I said, here I want you. I said, how do you know I'm a Jewish man? He said, well I told my friend you're a Jewish man because he said, I hear
d
 you speaking Yiddish with an old woman. So I said, what old woman? He said, she lives over there - in them - houses. I said, what did I say Yiddish to her? He said, she asked you what they're building on that bombed site, it was a - an old pub, it got bu
r
nt down during the war and it's still there, this site is. And you said - they're going to make a gefilter fish pond. See, the Jews call the fish - they call it - they chop it up and they call it gefilter fish, and you told that old lady they were going t
o make a gefilter fish pond there. So I said, that's how you know I'm a Jew, ay? He said, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose so few people spoke Jewish who weren't Jewish?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, well then of course - you see then - I - over the years you see I mixed with a lot of Je
wish people, my wife was Jewish, but she didn't speak that language. She didn't speak Yiddish. She - she might have understood a little bit but not like I did. I - I had - got the experience from work and during the war there was air raid warden was a gre
at experience because - ninety percent of the foreign element in Whitechapel never spoke English.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The other day you referred to the gentry, who would be the gentry at that time, before 1918, you used the expression, who would you refer to as gentry, what sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Gentry, well - your gentiles is - gentry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
You were talking about when you were selling things or something and you used that expression?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh, oh, that is - oh that is people you know with - what do you call it - intellect
ual people. Intellectual people you see. There's always what you call the - the labourer and - and the - - Conservatives see, the gentry is - people - they're - first of all they're dressed tidy aren't they, and - the collar and tie brigade, like you woul
d
 have around the Stock Exchange for instance. If you went round the Stock Exchange, the people at work there always dressed up posh. They got bowler hats and - and umbrellas, you know, and you go - you go round the docks and see the working class there - 
they've got an old hook hanging in their back you know, the - the different class of person. Different type of person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So there were definite different social groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, always, always that. There's always been that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about 
a middle class, would there have been a middle class around this area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, there's - middle class people are the business people weren't they, you know, like - they were class - generally classified as the middle class, people what was - and of cou
rse in this area where we are now, this was one of the select parts of Stepney here. This was the Nurses Company Estate, all this side of Jubilee Street, Dempsey Street here, Jubilee Street - right down there, and back of the police station where Barber S
t
reet, Harbour Square, Jamaica Street, Clark Street, all these was - you know - what I call - a different type of - cleaner person, you know what I mean - not the riff-raff. It's only since the - war come along that it - filled up with odds and ends from d
ifferent places that got burnt and bombed out. They took these places from - lower down in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
. See, the further down as they went in the rougher areas as they called it, like Wapping for instance. Although Wapping was rough there's still gentleman
 - gentlemanly people live there. But as I say, in the little - little clumsy houses as I call 'em, the two bob a week houses as I call 'em - you see - people what lived in that house say that - they have got to pay fourteen, fifteen shillings a week rent
 - were a different class - person to the people that paid five bob a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What class would you say you belonged to at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh we always - ever since I can remember - we had a - a - a big house in - Gold Street, when I first went to live 
at - in Gold street as a boy, there was all nice people there, you know, like schoolmasters and people like that had the houses. But they wouldn't live in them houses today, schoolmasters, 'cos they had a tap out in the back yard, you know what I mean, al
l that business. Or had a - see. All of them had outside toilets, don't matter where they were here in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 more or less, it was all outside toilets, none inside. I don't suppose there was - one house in - in - in a hundred had a - inside toilet. An
d - the one house in - two hundred had a bathroom. No one had a bathroom in the house. As I say, we used to - when I was a little boy used to get up in the copper in the corner of the kitchen. And those kitchens weren't very big. And - and I could - diffe
r
ent life altogether, and yet people loved 'em. Loved to be in their home you see, that was their home. You see, I can see now little things - many years ago - like you always remember. You remember animals what you've had, and you remember all sorts of th
ings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
