Well if they went - we went to the hospital or they went to a doctor, there was little doctors used to charge 'em sixpence, up in Bethnal Green there was a doctor called - Doctor Jelly, he used to be the Putney doctor. H
e - he was the tuppenny doctor and - he - he opened a - a provisions shops, after he finished with the doctors business, he had some argument with them - tuppenny doctors he was called, Doctor Jelly, top of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bethnal Green Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Tup - the tuppenny doctor. We
ll there was many of the doctors, you know - here - round about here, they - - they'd give you - give a poor person sixpence, instead of taking one from them. Of course there was other task masters I suppose as well. You see, like that area up in the West
 
End - where all the doctors are, you know, Harley Street you see, on every other door there's five or six doctors you see, I - I was up there when I was a boy for some reason. Yes. Yes, that - that - of course that - doctor's business up there you see. So
me of 'em are making fortunes at it now with this drug tricks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
What about who these more important people would associate with, who would shop-keepers associate with mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well they - they'd have their own class wouldn't they, they'd be - they'
d have their - if they belonged to the Conservative party, they'd have a local club wouldn't they. See, they'd have their own party that time - before all the Labour party business started. The old - these here - clubs - would be about in the East End, us
e
d to be one in Mile End, Beaumont Hall, round there, for the Conservative party. And they've got it now in Stepney Green, what they call the Scouts - have got it all. The Boy Scouts. That's where they are, where the - Conservative party - used to be a - b
i
g place here in Stepney - Beaumont Hall. That was where they started you see. It was - Conservative club and all the - wealthy people as I called it - belonged to that. 'Course there was plenty of working class belonged to it, but - the wealthy people - b
elonged to their own club.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would there be a Liberal club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, they - they have all them little - places, they started. I remember they started the Labour party here in Stepney Green in an old pub. It was a - the Mulberry Treet, that's the na
me of it, and it was a pub. See, the pubs that time had club rooms. That was where they used to hold them, that was the club room there. It was the Mulberry Tree was an old - music hall. When them pictures first started, they opened it as a picture place.
 Go up there for a penny. It went on for a long time, and they used to - they called it the bioscope that time. And you could go up there for a penny. See the night's performance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And most of the people like clergymen and teachers and doctors, would th
ey entertain amongst each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose they would you see them people, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They wouldn't have much to do with working class people?
