h man, but poor people generally met poor people didn't they. They didn't get introduced to - only - rare occasions like wars, the war throws two people together that - you see, you don't - you don't know who one and other are. I remember going - in a tra
in up to - Manchester during the war, and a - when I got in at - Euston station the air raid started, at ten o'clock one night, and in the carriage was a lot of American soldiers, and they more or less were terrified. And me - I'm an 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose} - air raid war
den, I'd seen a lot of - ruffian in my time. And I got case hardened to it you see, and there was a lady there, she was - the only lady in the carriage, and I said to her - sit down here, they haven't got a bomb for everybody lady. And I could see these c
haps all - muttering and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 shrivelling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 about. And of course I had my air - air raid warden gas mask with me in my pack. On my hip. So - sat down and I offered her a piece of chocolate and a orange. 'Cos in the war you couldn't get things like that. Well it 
turned out to be - that lady was one of the - Cadbury's - Lady Cadbury, and she gave me a card and I lost it. Oh - where I done with it I don't - I lost it, she told me any time I wanted a job to call on her - she lived - I know - I can - a big main turni
ng before you get - main - place on the coast it is, on the - West coast, up there - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 way. And they used to all change, you had to change when you went up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, you got out that station, and went on. Anyhow that was where it was, I think it - and she told me any time I wanted a job during my lifetime to call on her, she would fix me up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That's what you mean by people meeting people of different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. I met her, yes. Yes. Of course I - my wife was in hospital up there, y
ou see in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Birmingham{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And I used to go when I was on night duty - the turn over you see - so if I - I come off of - night - day duty seven o'clock at night, get home and washed and changed and went to - - Euston, it was ten o'clock and I used to go up ther
e, travel all night, see the wife in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 Birmingham}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 and come back to start work the next night - in - when it was me day off as they call it. Twenty-four hours off. See, we used to work - twenty-four hour shifts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you say that a different sort of per
son went to church than went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A different class of person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - some people were chapel were - more or less humble weren't they. The - the - the church people - were - well - it - it - everybody, they mixed us up about t
hat but - certain people liked to be big pots in the church, always they were the comfortable people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They went to the Church of England you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did many people round here go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, oh yes
. Thousands of people went to church and chapel. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You say there were a lot of little missions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, there was missions, everywhere you went was missions. Round here for instance - dozens as I say, little churches and missions. It's all gone. There's only a couple of churches left now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would you say your mother or father saw themselves as belonging to any particular social group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, they only were the working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they look at themselves as working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They didn't look down on theirselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But would they regard themselves as working class people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. Yes, yes, they - they were workers. See, my mother was a barmaid by trade. And then - when the children come on she only had thirteen children. And - there it was. My mother-in-law had twenty-two children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Was it easy to move from one class to another at that time? I mean today it's easy isn't it, it's very mobile?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. But the - you see - it wasn't easy to move but - today people - 
you can't tell today people - people today might not have any money, and they look better dressed than what the people with money do. You'll see that here today. See - when I was a boy - if you was poor you were poorly dressed and every - everything. You 
w
as poor. You could see the children by their clothes. They had old shabby clothes on you know - what were bought secondhand for 'em. Today if you asked a child to put secondhand clothes on - he wouldn't wear 'em. You see, it's a new - new trend in life. W
e didn't know no different, it was a change to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And do you remember anyone being described as a real lady or a real gentleman?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, there was plenty of them about, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh these - people that was runn
ing these missions and that, like clubs and that. See, if you belonged to a Sunday school where the - a mission where they had a Sunday school, there was generally gents - gentile people there you see, not ruffians you see, if you can - they were brought 
up different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Your home was rented was it when you were a boy, did your mother pay rent for her house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever see the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you say he was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, one landlord we had, I remember
 one landlord - we had, he was a publican. He had a little pub, local pub. He had a lease on the house - and of course I - when that lease run out it went back to the ground landlord, you know, the freeholders. And they - automatically have it, you see - 
y
ears ago when people bought houses you could buy a house for a couple of hundred pound that time. And when the lease ran out, it's called the ground lease you know - it - they - you had - they had 'em out on so many years lease, and then they went - they 
went back to the original owners. The ground owners. The freeholders. And that's what went on with 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What were landlords like as a group in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were they responsible people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, some of these big - big companies like there - big companies in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 like the Mercers Company for instance, there was a big concern. Now they've sold everything over to the L.C.C., it's all done away with. I can see now - round this area was - houses - nice houses like - four and five
 and six bedrooms in 'em - fourteen and six a week, fourteen bob a week. These houses was in this street, I've seen 'em build - they used to put - apply to the Mercers Company, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Harbour Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that was fourteen and six a week. Well they used to get tenants
 like policemen in them. And then they would guarantee their wages weren't they, their - their rent, see the - police had to pay their rent. They didn't pay it but it - they had to produce their books that they are paying it. And then they had a lot of - 
Jewish men come here in the neighbourhood, opened their houses as workshops. See, they had two rooms out the house as a - tailors workshop. See? So that's what went on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Were the landlords - was your landlord when you were a boy responsible for the decorating of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes, yes, when they done it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And what about repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well they - well you - they done it - they done it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And did they do it if you asked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, well in a way some of 'em. Oh some of these 
big companies like Mercers and - that, they done it regular, free, see through the - their - these companies when when they had these big vast estates - like they had round here, hundreds and hundreds of houses, they kept carpenters and bricklayers and - 
plumbers, they kept all that - in their workshop, they had a workshop - where their offices were or somewhere. Oh yes, yes, they done them up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about the small individual landlords?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 The small one, no, no, no. No. A small one wouldn't do anything like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Do you ever remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh certainly. Tell you they - if - you see, if - when - when I was young - if a man never had any work, say he - he was sick, say a man never went 
to work Monday, then he'd have a day short wouldn't he, his guv'nor wouldn't pay him, he couldn't go and say, oh well, I wasn't well, like they do today. Have a fortnight off or something like that. If you - you took a day out you - you took Saturday out,
 and they expected you to come in to do - take a - a load somewhere, you - someone else would have - get your wage, they'd take on what they call odd man for a day. See, you wouldn't get that wages. Oh yes, they stopped you for everything that time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was your father ever ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Can't remember. Only time I know him to be ill was when he had that - he fell -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And when your father was ill who supplied the extra money for you all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well that time he was ill, we was like to grow up wasn't we, and
 I was a little housekeeper then. I used to go in the City and - sell things and lord knows what, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And that covered .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, that covered it. I had - my mum used to give me a couple of coppers for - stock money and I'd bring her back on 
the night - when I see her say ten to twelve o'clock at night, and give her; she'd give me that - take the money away and give me the rest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your family ever have to go to the Board of Guardians?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 There wasn't no Board of Guardians that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there anything of this sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well there was a place - there was a Board of Guardians, I think they used to give 'em a - a big loaf of bread or something like that. I don't think they give 'em any money though. Might have done but I don't thi
nk - I never heard of it. Might have give 'em five bob or - I know an old couple - lived opposite me, he was an old slaughterman, worked in the slaughterhouses, name of Geary, he - he - he and his old wife went over to - to the local Guardians that time, 
I
 think they used to - I think the old age pension was about five bob a week then. That's what I've heard - recollect. About five bob a week old age pension, 'til Lloyd George brought up ten bob. They was fortunes then, ten bob a week. You realize it, ten 
shillings a week. A couple.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there any charity at all that you felt people could go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they used to - got to these missions if they could get any - a cheap - thing or a lunch somewhere, that's all. Go to these different missions, and it
 was only them people that - could put you touch with anything like that. But there was no - you see, when a person was - down and out, they used to go - over to what they call the work house. And they used to tell 'em to sell up their things and come ins
ide. See, so they - if a person - he wasn't given any charity, he'd sell up his home and go in the work house as they called it that time. And once you went in there you was finished weren't you, more or less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there a work house in this area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, a big work - oh there was numerous - everywhere the work houses. They had a big 'un there in - Mile End, Bancroft, it's a hospital now. That was called the Mile End work house, and - let's get it right, they used to have a - a wood - place they used 
to go in, the in mates used to chop wood, to sell bundles of firewood to the poor people - like the shopkeepers. And they had - they had all sorts of things for these people - that - stayed of a night, they had like cells for them to be - live in, over 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bancroft Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. They had - rope picking, they used to pick hockum. Picking the hockum for their - cas - go in the casual ward of a night, work house, destitute. Before they let 'em out in the morning they had to do their task. 'Cos I see - a book in there and 
it said, man's name, where he slept last night - take given, and it's un - beside of a lot of it was - absconded. They'd - they used to climb over a wall into a - a Jewish cemetery in Mile End, along the canal bank and get out without doing their task. Us
e
d to do stone breaking and all like that they did, when they was given them tasks in them work houses. 'Cos when I first - I went to work there, as a shoemaker, when I come out the Army. When I came out the Army - I got a job there - and - I got three day
s a week - work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What date was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
About 1918 I suppose. So - I went there - and - they said only a man taking - outdoor relief could get the job. That was the Labour party that time. Well - I - I never - took money even from a Labour Exchange 
I didn't, I always worked. I - got the job anyhow there, and there wasna Doctor {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Wilson{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 here, he was in charge of the Borough - the Borough at that time, and he - he had some argument I think with 'em - and he left this district and he went to Tottenham. Bu
t before he went he asked me if I - would like to go - with him to Tottenham, and I didn't like leaving the district you see. I said, I didn't think - of - of course I - I'd have been out having about five or six pound a week pension now wouldn't I, if I'
d have gone. And - I - didn't - go with him, but that was what he asked me. And I'll tell you why he asked me. A little boy - in the hospital - over at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bancroft Road
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - had to have a pair of surgical boots. And he asked me if I could take the irons off of a 
pair - boots what he's got and put 'em on another pair. And I told him I could. And I did it, and how long did it take, only a couple of hours. Well, that was the commencement that - I knew Doctor Wilson. A man had his foot off, right his toes and ankle y
o
u know, only left his heel on the leg. And he asked me if I could fit the man up a prop - what they call a pot. It slides in - in like a round pot. So I said, yes. So he said, how long will it take to do? So I said, well - I'll cut the piece of leather be
f
ore I go home tonight, and wet it. Then I'll take it home and I'll stitch it. You - tack it round a - a piece of roundwood, see, to make the shape of the leg - the bottom, and I said, tomorrow he can have it. What, he said. Takes these surgical people abo
u
t six months to do a job like that. I cut that piece of leather in the afternoon, made it wet so it goes shape, put it on the - this little hobbing foot, wooden thing, and I took it home and I made the rest at home and I sewed it and I brought it back the
 
next day. I got a pass out the work house for this little parcel to take home, and I brought it back the next day. And - I - put a couple of liths of leather on this and made a little heel, it's all a circular shape like that stick is there, and - about t
hat }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 height}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
, and I'd seen one of these before. But I hadn't seen it made but I knew how to make it. And I made it and I bought a sixpenny ball that time, a sorbo ball, what - the first sorbo was first coming in. Then I cut the - the two ends of the sorbo off
 and I put it down the bottom of this here - cut you see, it's like a - like a point go up - big - eye on a point like, and I put this sorbo ball down there and I went up to this bed in the ward and I said to this man - this is your what's - new shoes. An
d
 he said, oh yes. I said, see if it'll suit you, and I explained to him what - what was inside it. I said, you must never put your foot in it unless that - ball is in there. That sorbo. It was about that thick see. And he put his foot down and he run up t
he ward, he didn't walk. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 That}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  - that - had walked before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And no one had ever thought of that before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they had thought of that but they didn't that think that I had - thought of the sorbo. No. And not only - it was only a little ball, I cut 
a slice off it, I remember I bought it in the shop sixpence, brand new. And it was good sorbo, it - 'cos at that time sorbo was made of rubber, today it's made of synthetic things. Rubber - rubber is a - tremendous strength the sorbo balls then, and that 
m
an put his - his bare heel - he's got the heel - only had the heel he did and the front is sewn up you see, this part. He run up and down the ward. Well over that Doctor Wilson asked me if I would go - he told everybody it. But overnight to make a job - y
o
u see what it was, leather is brown isn't it. I took it home and I dyed it, this - after I'd sewed it, and I made a - a - three or four liths of leather, and then - I explained to the man, I said, now - don't ill treat it, when it wants mending have it do
ne by a good mechanic, don't let it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 wear}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 out, so you keep it solid. And I showed him how to fix over - at that time round rubber heels used to wear men did. You can wear one of them on there, that'll last you for months and months and months without trouble.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
And all the time you were actually making the shoes as well for people in the work house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I - I used to mend 'em in there. Mend them for the - that - the old ladies used to wear boots that time with - what they call felt tops. They had a spec
ial boot they did. Had like a - a - this was made in felt here. You can always tell a workhouse woman as they called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You mean they wore a uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, they - they - some - most of them did, they had a dirndl - the men had {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} tweed sui
ts. If you was in the work house you had a Derby tweed suit, you had to wear it. You was a marked person. The women was the same, they were marked in - like with them blue - blue felt boots. They were marked people, the work house inmates. Yes, it's true.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
What were the people like who ran the work house, did you ever come into contact with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, I spoke to the master and matron, they were nice people. Oh yes, Mr Chap - his name was Chappel, Mr and Mrs Chappel. Of course when they retired fro
m there I suppose they were pensioned off and went to live in private - somewhere, but they were the - master and matron of Bancroft Road hospital then. It's a long while ago, it's 1918. But I've got a memory of all that you see. Used to be a labour - two
 
- labour masters in there, to - to give these here inmates their work, whose - what they call casual ward board, come in a - they come up and they want a - nights lodging and that, they used to either give 'em stone breaking or - hockum picking. And they 
w
as proper cells there - in there, just like in prison, in that work house. For inmates. If they was a bit naughty. Oh it was a - and - and the cold bare walls was always - all - no - no paper or paint they were bricks. The walls was brick walls. Of course
 now it's getting modern like you see, they've got - turned it into hospital and all that, it's all different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever know any person who went into a work house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes, plenty. Oh I think plenty of people went into the work house. I
 saw 'em in there. I - when I was working there - a little while, a man came in there and he was a mat maker. He was an expert making mats. He had an old bedstead he made with a frame and all the little hooks on it, what he used to plait this here yarn, w
h
ere they buy that special string, and he used to make all that sort of lovely mats, and he made 'em for all the work house - what do you call it, the - all the - in charge of the work house, all the - staff, he made 'em all mats. Well - I saw an advertise
ment in the paper, a mat maker wanted for a boys home in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Surrey{\*\xmlclose}
. And - it was for Princes Christian's home. So I took it up to the old man and I said, well I call him old man, he was twice my age that time, say I was twenty odd and he was forty odd. So I sa
id - here you are, there's a chance of a job if you want it. So he says, how am I going to get there, I've got no money. So I lent him ten shillings. And he went to Waterloo station, that - this day and he went to this home that's somewhere at Surry, and 
h
e got the job. And he came back - and - he told them in the work house that he's leaving, they said, oh we thought you were staying here for good. He told me he made numerous lovely big mats all by hand, all different designs. They never give him that. Of
 
course that bought the stuff in there, I suppose the - the parish paid for it, and this one has this mat, this one had that mat. He said and he never - and of course when I got - told him about that job and he got it, he went away and a couple of weeks ti
m
e I had a letter from him with that money, that fare money. And he got the job in Princess Christian's Home, that man, making the mats. And that man I think he had - only vision in one eye. But where he'd learnt that trade I don't know, whether he'd learn
t it in prison or not I couldn't say. But he - he must have had a character or else he couldn't have got that job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
But if you went into a work house was there no way of carrying on your own trade and just going there to sleep at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no. O
h no, no, no, they - they wouldn't like that. If you - you - you - you - you was - working in a trade you had to got a lodging house didn't you. The Salvation Army or Rowton House, and there was plenty of - numerous working lodging houses you could get, e
verywhere you went was lodging houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So work houses really consisted of unemployed people or old people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Work house people once you went in there you gave up everything. You - that was your finish. You sold right out hadn't you. And there 
was plenty youngish people in them places. I saw 'em in there, I saw a lovely local tradesman - in there, through being - having no - see they never had any money so they had to go somewhere didn't they. Away from it all. And - they'd lost hope you see. L
ots of them went when they went over there as a - as I say for assistance, they were told - fetch your things in. Sell up and - sell 'em. That's what they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A lot of trade was done on credit in those days wasn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, credit was a 
great thing, yes. Everybody trusted. - You trusted one another. And that's it, if you wanted to do any work you trusted. See like me, I - I - in my tin pot way, I had to give a lot of credit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you say your mother was an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, she was a - woman of the world wasn't she, she - brought up a family.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was she affectionate towards her children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes. We loved our mum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And if you had any worries could you go to your mother with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He - he - we never mixed a lot with dad. It was always with mum. See dad was at work. When dad come home from work he was - after he'd had his tea he was dead tired, he'd be in bed wouldn't he. Go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So if you had a problem you wouldn't go to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Not very often, unless it was on a Sunday he - you - when you was old enough you had your - you knew how to do your own problems, you didn't want - their - it's only when you're kids, and there wasn't many - problems you couldn't - do without him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
All - all - all must look after one another. That's what we were brought up to. To help one and other and look after one another, and that's what we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And how did they expect you to behave towards them, your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The same. You had to respect them didn't you. Even when - you couldn't do like I see children do today, when mum said, you go and get this e
rrand and you say, no. That would never come off. You had to do it. She said - whatever they said was the written law. You did it. There was no back saucing. None of that. Back answering, you just done it and you got on with it and you're happy - doing it
 you see. And you learnt to love your parents like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And if a child hit you, would your parents tell you to hit them back?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, definitely, yes, yes. Don't come to us, go and - look after yourself. And that's what we did do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Children were brought up very independent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes. Oh no. And when - when - we knew that when I was young - anybody hit me he had to look after himself, because we never get forgiven you see, we go and hit them back straight away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I don't know. We all grew up and - we all grew up to go and work and fend for our own living, all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they consider anything important in life, anything special that they 
thought was important, your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they didn't like you to mix with any - body - wrong, you know what I mean. You know, wrong doers, evil minded people or thieves or anyone like that, they didn't want you to mix with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could it have been easy to come in contact with people like that?
