Oh yes, yes, yes, everywhere you went. It's always been like that. You see, my dad - was a man - I don't think - he ever put sixpence on a horse or - in his life. He never - done anything like that. 
The only vice he had - he had a drink and a smoke, but he didn't do any other - he didn't - throw away money, he waste a lot other ways. 'Course you see - drink - years ago was the only poor persons solace, that was the only place where they could go and 
h
ear a organ of a - night or a gramaphone, or have a nice big fire in a pub, used to be lovely great big fires, and they were warm where their house would be cold, you see, and they'd go and have a half a pint of beer or whatever they had, and spend the ti
me in a pub, nice and warm, talking and sing-song and that's how a lot went on. That was the way of life. Now they've got all different ways of life, they've got television, they've got - gramaphones, they - not gramaphones - wireless.
