 house. And then if it was a shop it wouldn't be more than about a pound.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would a market stall cost?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
For a stall, well - the - the - the council used to - if the council - some of the stalls you paid the council about a shilling a day or two bob a day, no more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Do you think market stall holders would make quite a lot of money before the first world war? Like they do now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, well it all depends what they had. It all depends what - what they were selling. - Yes, I had a brother, he used to sell rabbits, wild rabbits, nothing else. And he sold wild rabbits he did. In and out of season you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would he get them from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They used to come in boxes from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Frozen. Frozen rabbits. And they was - two dozen in 
a box. For - oh a long flat box, see the length of a - a rabbit - they used to put them legs to legs that way, there used to be - I remember the boxes, two dozen in a box and they was frozen stiff, they used to get 'em from - Smithfield or }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 wherever}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  they bo
ught 'em and - they didn't cost much more than about sixpence or ninepence each you understand. And they used to - hang pem oup and thaw 'em, then open 'em and skin 'em, see and there they got the profit on the skins, selling the skins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever help do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, I skinned thousands of rabbits. Oh yes, that was a - mu - help - I was learnt that trade all right. He used to - undo the back leg first see, and push that through and you start the skin. You pull it over from the two back l
egs, pull the skin and then it - it's - you hang it back again and then you pull it right down - to the ears and cut the ears when you pull it through the ears, and it was off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you do with the skins?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They were sold to furriers and tha
t. As long as you didn't tear 'em see, that - was in the art of skinning them you - you was careful you - you didn't tear them, you see, when the - them frozen rabbits or - of course - a English rabbit is - skins easily, but when they're frozen you've got
 to go steady. Yes, we uses to skin the rabbits, that's simple job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 If people wanted second }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 hand clothes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  where would they go for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well there used to be - all these - stalls in the markets. All these - people that come round old clothes, you 
see, like they do today. today - they - people throw 'em into - give them to the dustmen and all like that, these porters in all these flats, they put 'em in bags all the old rags and they sell 'em to the rag boys and the rag boys - take 'em and sell 'em 
i
n the markets see. That's what goes on, it used to be up in - in - in Houndsditch - a - a big old clothes market for years Petticoat lane there. And they used to sell - all the clothes - all - take 'em all over the place - dustmen now get all the - and po
r
ters in the - estates like these porter, I see the porter the other day. Whole motor load of - old clothes went away. A woman - person moves out of a flat see, leaves everything there, they've got their customers, these porters, and they come with a car a
nd take it all away, all the - old home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were they all in quite good condition, these clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, some of 'em are. You see, you'd see good condition clothes thrown away now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about on stalls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, you still see 'em up
 White - Whitechapel, there's two or three stalls up there, old clothes. Old boots. And things. There's one man stands - opposite Jubilee Street, as you go over there - he's - over that crossing there's a stall, that first stall up - facing the pub, there
's a pub there, the Forty Fives it's called, and he stands out there every Saturday, he's got cosmetics on one stall - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 jewellery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 , he deals with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 jewellery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 , old worn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 jewellery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  and watches, and - clothes, old umbrellas what he gets from the railway, lost property office. And then there's a man brings him sacks of - old boots from - one of the public schools.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any musical instruments in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Nobody played anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I can play the mouth organ, that's all. We used to - 
like that's the cheapest one. We had a - a gramaphone. And - one thing and another. But - we never had no musical instruments. It's only this - since what they call wireless has come in that - people got more or less - music minded.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about singing did people sing a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Sing, oh yes, they used to sing, oh yes, everybody was a singer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you ever make music together at home, have a sing-song?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, yes, yes. Oh yes, you always - sang. Especially if they'd had a drop of dri
nk you know - You know, they felt happy you see. People who were drinking then. Yes, well - well then used to go in the local pubs you see, they had a gramophone on or they - used to have a street organ come out - every now and then, go round, stop outsid
e
 the pub and turn it, all the children'd be dancing outside the pub to the street organ see. That was the pleasure they had, that's all, nothing else. 'Course - in later years as I say the penny pictures started coming, you could go to pictures for a penn
y
 or tuppence, in these here little places, threepence was top. I used to go to a - in Cambridge Rod, the Foresters music hall, that was only tuppence for the gallery. Well we wasn't interested in the rich people that went downstairs in the pit for fourpen
c
e. We - there was tuppence threepence and fourpence see. I think a sixpenny seat would be top of the house, one of the boxes. Yes. Tuppence we used to pay at the Foresters. We used to go - and they used to have matinees. I - I think I told you about that 
E
ast Lynne affair there. They were playing East Lynne there at the Foresters, this is honest truth, and in the pathetic part of the play - she's nursing her own son you see this woman - and - he dies, this boy in the play, East Lynne. And she comes in ther
e
 to nurse him, she's got glass - black glasses on, and she says the pathetic words, dead and never called me mother. Well there was tears all over the hall. And all of a sudden a shrill raspberry went through - went through the building, somebody tore it 
o
ut - a raspberry out and had tears and laughter at the same time, you could see 'em. But I'll never forget that. Yes, the shrill - particularly remember when she says those words. Dead and never called me mother. This shrill raspberry went through - and i
t sound - you could hear a pin drop you know, and of course the manager come out and - and - big burly man he was, I think his name was Bore, a great big fellow, weighed over twenty stone. He used to shout out, quiet please.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Audiences were quite lively in those days were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Yes. Oh yes, I used to see - Harry Lauder when he was ordinary - little tich. Gertie Getana, all those - good old - turns used to be. And of course that - they - they were in the - they went to the high - posh music ha
ll, the Paragon - what's Mile End Empire now. The Foresters was a - a - they had a few - theatres over the water that - they used to show all dramas you know. And of course then they - had a music hall licence, had music hall as well, but not like the - v
a
riety - places. They were always a penny dearer to go in, they was threepence in the gallery. But the Foresters was tuppence. Their - variety. Used to be the - company called the Brewsery Burglars. Lou - Lou - oh - I know the - name for a minute. It was a
 - some big company it was, they used to play all those sort of plays you know. Real funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your parents go to the music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I suppose they did, but I don't remember what they went - much about them going out - out but - I know we did as so
on as we had a penny or tuppence to spare, that was our favourite. If we could save up - my favourite used to be - have threepence. Then used to go - tuppence up to the - pictures or like the - Foresters, and when you come out of there was a shop used to 
c
ook boiled pudding, plum pudding, currant pudding, all like that. A cook shop. Used to go in there and buy a penn'orth of currant pudding. That was our tea party, you know, we was lords of the - to me that was - always thinking of it you was 'til you got 
i
t. Then you waited for the next time. But before you went to that there music hall you want to always try and get a penny so you could go and have a - or you went and had a penny basin of soup in the same shop, but they used to cook boiled - boiled curran
t
 pudding, boiled plum pudding, there was - everywhere them sort of shops about. Used to be a - one right opposite - Whitechapel church, Johnson's they called it, it's a jewelry shop now. Right - the shops still there but - Johnson's used to - have - legs 
o
f pork roasted in the window and you know you could go and have a cut from the joint for about sixpence see, roast beef and - pork or whatever they had, that was the - Christmas time they had turkeys there, in there. It was a real - old fashioned cook sho
p
 you know. But of course the favourite for children was the - fruit puddings in the window, currant pudding, boiled plum - a little baked - pancakes with plums in it, you know, like - that was our favourite if we had a penny. But it was very seldom we had
 a penny, we had farthings and ha'pennies. 'Course I mean you got 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When you were at home would your parents play any games with you, with the children in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well I don't remember, they had other odd - things and - in what - you see
 - when my dad came home from work he was generally tired out. If he had his meal, he went to bed and you had to keep quiet. There's no - when he went to sleep you see, he - he was out perhaps - fourteen hours or fifteen hours a day for their - they went 
-
 go out at five in the morning and come back perhaps eight or nine o'clock at night, after he had his - his cup of tea or - or - or bloater, whatever mum give him that time for his tea, ha'penny bloater, they were dear that time bloaters, ha'penny each, b
rown herrings, ha'penny each. A - a fresh herring was only four a penny. You could get - see if you wanted to feed a - a - I mean he wouldn't eat one - more than two. You get -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Then he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 d be tired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, then he'd have his - his tea and a couple of
 slices of bread which was - that, now she made her bread pudding from any old stale bread what was corroded. That was a tea party wouldn't it be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you boys and your sisters ever play any games yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes, we play. Pl
ay - we was - you were brought up to - play. I mean we used to belong to little clubs like if you belonged to the - Band of Hope clubs you went - this hall and that hall. They used to show - pictures, like little - what do you call it - magic lantern that
 time they called it. In the missions, they used - you had - well it was the only entertainment you had.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any books in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Don't remember. Don't remember books. Unless you brought a magazine in yourself you see. We could get 
a - a book from the library if you wanted it, but we could buy a little - of course that time a - a - to buy a book for a child was only a ha'penny a comic. See, you got - only spent a ha'penny on a - and then that would pass round to everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did any of you belong to a library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
My sisters I believe did but I don't remember belonging to any library. We never had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 no time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  for that, we was always out fiddling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about newspapers, would your father read a daily newspaper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. Once a w
eek, he paid a penny for the News of the World, once a week. That was all the News of the World cost, he used to - I - used to go - and - buy half ounce of tobacco for him - and a - pay the paper money, that was threepence. Threepence for half ounce of to
bacco and the News - Sunday paper. You see. And he had tobacco for a couple of days more or less, 'cos he smoked a pipe - he only - smoked one shag tobacco, British Oak.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would your mother ever have time to read, do you remember seeing her sitting and reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, I never remembered seeing her read. Yes, I suppose she did if they had a book - to read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they read to the children, would your parents ever read aloud, stories?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about funerals, did you have a funeral in your family when you were a boy?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could you describe a funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well the - the funerals was just the same as anything else. You - the - they buried 'em - just like any - every - everyone else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did people wear mourning clothes at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, that was the - ah that was it, see they all tried to wear mourning, people did there was - not like today, now they go with a - a - a pink coat on now to funerals now. But - that black mourning - you see - if somebody i
s loved, no matter who it is, it shows respect mourning you see. If you got a - black -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever see one of those funerals with horses with the plumes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What were they like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well the - the - the - they had fe
athers, like plumes of feathers over the horses heads. Yes, saw that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would a funeral be expensive at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no. Today funerals are expensive, then they were - see - see a lot of people - a lot of people where a child died years ago,
 the undertakers used to take away the children and bury 'em without funerals see. They used to put 'em in between the legs of grownup people and bury 'em. Yes, to - babies, yes, that was how they was taken away by the undertakers. So you - when you see a
 funeral going along there might be two people in there. See, a baby and a - see they used to put the children in between the legs of 'em in the - in the - to get - buried without any - problems you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did most families have some sort of insurance for funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, a lot of 'em had insurances didn't they. You see - they paid a - couple of copers a week you see to - it covered expenses you see. But I do know that about the - undertakers taking - children away to be - people couldn't afford a fu
neral and didn't want funeral, couldn't afford it, so the undertakers used to take the babies, or anybody like that. Oh yes. That went - that was a great - they got a - something out of it you see. I suppose they gave 'em a couple of quid see, say, here y
ou are, take it away. Everything would be O.K. Yes - that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did your parents ever take you out visiting, would you ever go out with your mother visiting neighbours or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Got to a aunt, you know, take you to a aunt I had a - an old aunt do
wn at Poplar. We used to go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go out with here shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, I'd go shopping. Carry the bag back for her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you ever go out alone with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, not very - well - very very seldom, my father - we - we we
re - he had his friends and when he grew up like he - we grew up he had his friends and we - and then we found ours. You see. It wasn't no - great - until I got married - then I had a lot of - relations you see. My - mother-in-law, I told you, she had twe
nty-two children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You married into a huge family didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
My mother had thirteen, my mother-in-law had twenty-two, and 'course - all those brothers and sisters - I was friendly with, and they was friendly with me because - now I can see why. Y
ou see, because I was helping them by helping their sister. You see? She'd had a - I think a rough spell, and then I - like I helped this girl. I helped her and I - helped her - and they - respected me for it you see. And - as I say, she was Jewish by bir
th, old English Jews, not - foreign. Her father worked as a - a Secretary to Disraeli, the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I remember you telling me that, about the Primrose League?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, and when - when he passed away - they sent a whole hearse of primroses. You now. Pair of - horses and coach load you know, a whole big - open hearse, it's - they used to - fold up you know at the back, like you see - the Queen have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your father have the day off on a Bank Holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well mostly them - drivers had a day off Bank H
oliday, there was no work in the City see, it was shut. See, he was a City driver all his life, a carman, and - the - they didn't need them for Bank Holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would he do anything that day, would he go out or take you all out somewhere?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no, they - they - he went to the - he went to his local - pub.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you do on a Bank Holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well we - on a Bank Holiday we - I - either used to go to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose} - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, or go to some park you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How would you get down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Walk. Walk through Blackwall Tunnel and walk - I've walked through Blackwall Tunnel to Greenwich and you've got another couple of miles say from the other side of the Tunnel, and when you come home instead of coming back through the tu
nnel, you went along Bermondsey, over Tower Bridge that way, another three or four miles extra see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 It's quite a way isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Oh well we - we knew our way, when we - we was children, we all knew our way. And - I - I've taken - a dozen chi
ldren with me to Greenwich Park, and they used to start sorting out their - little - handkerchiefs where they've got two or three pennies in it perhaps to go off with. Some never had anything at all. Yes, I've took 'em to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose}, and then instead of coming back through the tunnel go right along, let's come home {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Tower{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType
}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} way, I'd say. I'd fetch 'em back that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever go on a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, used to go - used to go a holiday, through them - er - wh
at do you call it, them - Sunday schools, used to have a outings - and we used to - and unless you belonged to in the school you could pay a couple of coppers a - a week on a card, have a holiday. But the - those - our Sunday school outings - was run by t
he Shaftesbury Society, used to - send children away - was it Princess Christian, she had a home for Boys at Windsor, there was a place at Southend, there was quite - numerous home for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go and stay there, how long for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Fortnight. Week 
- week or a fortnight. Yes. That was - they'd give you a - a little suit and a pair of boots as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you ever remember going on one of these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about the school one, would you ever got to one of the school holidays?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no. Never went to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would they go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
All different places - the Company Holiday Fund they used to call it. The children used to pay - so much to the teacher on Monday morning or something like that, there was a - special t
ime paying in on their little cards. Oh that was for - comfortable children you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you have different clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Not necessary. It didn't make no difference to me what day it was, as long as I had something to put on. But they 
didn't worry so much those times with children. You - see when you were poor you were poor. You see, there was no - unless someone gave you clothes - I remember as a boy - I was friendly with a - in this district used to be a - a lot of business people's 
c
hildren went to that school see, that room up there on the right was my - classroom, right along there, and I had - they were always looking out that window over here was the gardens of houses, and - and that. Then there was business people - I went to sc
h
ool with, there was a chemist, he had two sons - and they used to give me all their old clothes, and boots. So they kept me going as a boy. Smith his name was, he's - that - that building up there belongs to the council now is - Ibex House isn't it, Ibex,
 
no - that - that place there - at the corner of Philpott Street, back of the London hospital - was the chemists shop right on that site where that big new building is. Smith, he was there for years. And war came along, I know they went - both went away in
 
the war. Most of the boys that I was a boy with - was done during the war. The '14 war. See, the average boys - half of 'em went for the war, the '14 war. Slaughtered unnecessary. Yes, it was a terrible thing. In the Dardanelles and all that, and no - out
 in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Wicked waste of man power. Yes, that's why I always think of my brother, Fred. He - he had a good job in White - well - when he left the buses he went to - work for a Colonel in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Wales{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, a colliery owner. And he used to drive him about - and his family there in this big house, Lord of the Manor he was. And of course when Fred joined the Army - he was taken to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} the next day. And he become a chauffeur to - Mr - Abe you see, Douglas Abe, then he became Sir then he became a Lord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did he think of Haigh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I suppose he - he - he - he was all right, well they - he met his guv'nor out there, while he was out there, he was a Colonel in the Army, and - he told him when he joined the Army his wife sent his wife a - a - had a cottage 
you see - on the grounds, and he - she - went out of the cottage, like that lady - owned it, like the Colonel's wife, and - he said, well my home is stored in - Cardiff, see. Anyhow, he paid for all that storage for him during that time. But he - I don't 
t
hink he - he - he wouldn't go back to - when he - when he came back from the war he opened a garage for himself see, he's a mechanic, a motor - motor mechanic. And - that's where he stayed, and then they bought - he bought a house in Porthcawl - he bought
 two houses, one for a policeman - he give it to him after he finished because - they wasn't allowed to have - that kind of a house, a policeman, no. See, they're - different rules. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They had to live in a police house did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Well - a
nyhow, Fred bought these two houses. I suppose that time - there was houses would cost about - less than five hundred pound. Now they've gone ten thousand odd for those two houses, each, easy. 'Course they were made solid.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You said you went to a church of England Sunday school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Stepney meeting house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your parents go to church there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they didn't go to church - unless there was a - the only time my parents went to church is like I'm telling you, when there was a - 
a wedding or a - what do you call it, a - christening, something like that you see. That's all what I remember you see. But 'course my sisters was church - as they grew up they were more church goers than what we were. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But your parents wanted all the children to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. But when we - we was young they encourage - my mum always encouraged us to go to missions, and then why we went because the back of our minds, we got something. Christmas time and a - days out in the country you know lik
e to Loughton, well if you attend those places you go, if you don't you don't go. So it was up to us - and I as a boy always went to Sunday school right up 'til - I - more or less - become a man, fourteen, soon as I left school I want - I become a - a man
, you forget about your children - your - any more. That's how we used to - we used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to play on a Sunday, would your parents allow it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
They never - no, they never stopped you. The police wouldn't let you play like you do to
day, and yet you see, when I was a boy if you was - we used to play - with a little ball in the street the police'd summons you. People - complaining and the policeman came round and - and summons you. You get fined. Wasn't allowed to play We used to play
 tippy-cat or marbles or things like that, or if you had money you could play up with ha'pennies and pennies that time, gambling as they called it. But the police was very - very - sharp on children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any other social activities connected w
ith the church that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I used to belong to a mission here in - in - there was a local mission here, John Brown's - he used to be the Mayor of London one time, Lord Mayor of London, he had a - a mission along here, John Brown's mis
sion. It was a ordinary chapel then they - he - he - they turned it into a John Brown's mission and we used to go there and we used to have tea parties and all things like that. Different people - I - I took a boy there once, I heard there was going to ha
v
e a - a party see. So I took this boy and he's a Jewish boy, a Dutch Jew. His father dealt with old rags and metal and bones. And of course I took him to the - our tea, and what we had give us was - hot - baked potatoes in their jacket - and hot dogs, and
 
they were pork sausages. And when I took him home on the night after we'd had this here - below out - he told his father, eeh I had a real treat today. I went with Alf and he took me to the mission, John Brown's mission, I had hot pork sausages and hot do
gs. He's telling his father, he's a Jew. Hot pork sausages he had. Funny wasn't it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was his father upset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, no. He wasn't so religious. No, he wasn't orthodox Jew see. Oh if it had been an orthodox Jew - yes, he was them - what they call D
utch Jews. They're not - they're not so fussy. I can see - I knew - knew 'em quite well, yes. Solly Redbrake, that was his name. He was the eldest son. But he - he - he had such a treat he said. He had these lovely pork sausages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you belong to the choir at the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, I belonged to the - if I was in the chapel I'd belong to the choir, 'cos I used to like singing - hymns, see. That starts you off see when you're singing hymns. We used to sing hymns. I knew all the hymns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go regularly as a choirboy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. 'Course it wasn't done on a - footing it's done today. You were - I was only dressed ordinary, I wasn't dressed any special - way, see, we was only - we belonged to choirs now they've got uniform choirs, all - all one s
ort. 'Cos things - the circumstances didn't come to that see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there any temperance clubs run by your church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, temperance clubs was - mostly in - the Great Assembly Hall, Mr Charington, the brewers brother, he - yes, he was a brewer, hi
s - he was one of the brewers, Charrington. I think his name was Fred - Mr Frederick Charrington. You know, right opposite Jubilee Street there - there's the Great Assembly Hall, it was like a great big music hall. It was a chapel see. And of course the w
ar came along and it got burnt down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did people used to got these temperance meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, used to have all these don't - temp - temperance speakers there that time. Used to be - singers and speakers he had there. Each week you'd see a d
ifferent name up, who'd be there. It'd be a man they used to call Gipsy Daniels, he was a gipsy converted see. He would speak there and someone else - I remember a man - well known man there was a Mr Wilkey. Wookey. He used to be always there with Mr Char
rington. But - he didn't believe in - in drink you see and he - he was one of the - relatives of - one of the brothers of Charringtons. Brewery. Oh yes, that's still there that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970  C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 harrington's place is.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there any other clubs organised by the church, any evening clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, there was everywhere, all these missions that - everywhere you went the - the East End was a - a mission here in Commercial Road, the - the East End mission in - in Mile End Road was other missions, everywhere was missions a
nd - in little side turnings there'd be these missions, had their own - what they call flock you see. Every -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they provide anything for children to do in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, there was plenty of places there for that - made little socials. T
hat place over Charringtons - every night in the week was something - going on there. They had a small hall the children used to all go there, the childrens hall they called it. It was writ up, the childrens hall. And - they used to have all these - choir
s
 singing and one thing and another every - different entertainments what they - these ladies and - be about would - throw and tea parties and that. See well it was the lure of the tea parties that lured the children to the - place you see. Oh if they - wo
u
ldn't have got nothing from it like otherwise. See Christmas time you get invited to a tea party or something like that. You pick up little odds and ends. Oh I saw some very funny things going on with those parties. The old ladies go with a - umbrella ups
i
de down, drop everything in the umbrella, know what I mean? An open umbrella tied and they'd walk out with it under their arm like that, open - half open, with what little - little scraps what they've - cakes and - bread what the - bread sandwiches. Oh th
ey went to tea parties in style.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your family say grace at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Don't ever remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you taught to say prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You didn't have any family readings of the Bible or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about politics, was your father interested?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no. Never. No politics, no. He - he never even - I don't think he ever give a bookmaker sixpence in his life. He - he'd no - no gambling instincts in him. In all their outlook in life was drink yo
u know, if they wanted a - have a entertainment they went and had a half a pint of beer for a penny. If they had sixpence they had six half pints, that's how that - the law of the land was that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think your father would discuss politics in a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think he voted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, they - they went in a pub - if it was bad - played games like darts or bagatelle, the game used to be like a kind of a billiard game, bagatelle, they used to play that game mostly the 
little working mens - what they call - rooms there, at the back of the pub they were, little side rooms see. Yes. They'd be up there playing cards, crib, that was the favourite game. Crib or bagatelle or darts. That was the three games. They all - that wa
s their only entertainment what they knew, and that's all they went to the pub for, a drink and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How many evening a week do you think your father would have time to do that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - it all depends if he had money wouldn't it. If he had money 
he'd be there every evening. But at the weekend they got their wages and they got a lot of wages that time - I can remember - up to the 1912 strike his - his wages wouldn't be thirty shillings a week. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So he didn't have much for himself out of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, and if he made a couple of coppers during the day while he was out driving, like beer money as they called it - they were all right you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did he vote in an election, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I couldn't - I don't never remember him voting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your mother didn't talk about politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no. No, no, there was none of that - done you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Do you think at that time your father was a driver, would employers want him to vote a certain way do you think or would he risk losing his job, was there any political pressure do you think on the drivers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - there - may have been but there it is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He certainly never talked about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did your mother have any interest of her own outside the house, did she do anything besides the housework and looking after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Helping someone else she would. You know - all you heard those times was; so and so else is going to have a baby and they're going to help her, that's all you heard. They go and - do her washing and
 do her - cleaning, like my wife, she used to get up say half past - I may not be - coming back - she said, I'll see you about ten o'clock, and ten o'clock she'd go - and out she'd go. And she'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 come in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  - and ask me to put the kettle on and all that. Well that'd be nothing, the buildings there, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Plessey Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Put the kettle on and somebody - she'd help someone out of trouble. She used to do their washing, do their shopping, do their cleaning, not for any - gain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And your mother did the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes,
 my mum did the same. My missus walked - there's dozens of children round here - they're grandparents now these children - and - she bought 'em into the world, my wife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You mean she'd actually deliver the babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, she would do that. Yes
. They have congratulated her from the hospital - for that. She - I remember one occasion - there was a Jewish woman, she had a - a lot of children, and the - they sent a woman to help here, like a - a kind of a nurse. And - she went up the - wife to see 
t
his young woman and this baby's laying out - that, so my missus said, well what's the baby doing there? This woman said, oh he's a doner. A doner she says, what are you talking about? She said, he's - he's finished, it's not for this world. And my missus 
a
sked me to put the kettle on, and I put the kettle on. And she bathed that child, with warm water, and she - she used to use olive oil for the back passage, and she put the back - olive oil with a feather on that child, and the child's bowels opened, it w
as costive. And that was a - that would have been finished that child but that - that - that boy's a grandparent now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your mother ever have to help to deliver a baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh she did and all as well mother would, yes. Mostly be the - the - them so
rt of people you know, the rough and - as I call 'em the rough and ready people helped one another. Well my missus - must have - to my knowledge helped scores and scores of people. If she knew anybody - or anybody wanted they'd come to her and ask her.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your mother have all her babies at home or would she go into hospital?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, they'd have 'em at home mostly wouldn't they. Mostly that time they had 'em at home didn't they. They - that was how it went on. Like as I say my missus - there was a
 young woman up there, she had - how many children did she have - she had - about - ten children and I think my missus brought nearly all of them in the world. And the - there's - oh I can - there - there - them boys or girls that I knew what she brought 
in the world are grandparents. Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
If your mother wanted to enjoy herself would she be able to go out and do any things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well she was a - see - like - my mum - my mum, as a young girl, she used to sing. See, there was a - a theatre in Leman S
treet called the Garreck Theatre, it's where the police station is, there was a pub there, the Garreck, and there was a theatre there and all the old turns like Marie Lloyd and all them, Kate Carney, all used to go there and my mum used to go - there and 
s
ing like they - call competitions, they'd have a booze up as I call it, and then a sing-song and that was how they - done years ago. And mother was a singer, she sung there. And she could sing all Irish songs. She used to sing all the Irish songs. I never
 
- couple of her songs what she sung, she sung - Danny - Danny Boy and - and - Plough boys was - riding beneath the green pastures. I - I'm forgetting the words, anyhow she used to sing all the Irish songs. Mum, and they used to all say, go on Adelaide, si
ng us - sing to us, and that's where I think we all - fond of the - the singing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did she used to sing at home much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, used to sing there, yes, sing, yes. She learnt us all songs singing. There was no other people - no other music was there. Se
e, we - gramaphones was - was a - was a - a music when I was a boy, well, people - if they had a piano they was - comfortable people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your mother go in a pub with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I believe so, yes, yes, yes, they would - that was only - only 
a - that was only a outlook of - of - of drink that time. They'd go and talk to one another in a pub, meet one another, the people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could she go to those clubs to play cards, did women do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 She wouldn't do that, no, she wouldn't do that, she
 wasn't a - I don't think she was a card player, I don't think she - at the finish they started to learn her to have a bash, sixpence on a horse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But your father never betted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, he never - done anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did he ever take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes he did, boxing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Oh they all - all went - all drivers and carmen were all tough boys you know. They - they loved a bit of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they do that proper Marquis of Queensbury boxing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, the
y - the old fighters they were. You see and they were - that was boxing with the bare hands, but un - when that finished in - I think that finished in the '80's, 1880 odd, the - and it come under the - boxing, they had to wear gloves. Padded gloves you se
e.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think your father was quite good, quite a good boxer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh he was a tough boy, we - well most of us, we was all brought up tough, all the lot of us. You see, you - you was always brought up to look after yourself. Nobody wouldn't take adv
antage of you, you know what I mean. You see, 'cos - like today you see these hooligans - they're bullies, the - years ago there wasn't so many bullies as there is today. Here and there there was a bully, but he - he had to be careful. See the - the - the
y
 do such unfair things today, the - the people don't fight, they - they clobber one another. Well that wasn't allowed, if you clobbered anybody or kicked 'em, up North the boys used to use their feet. They'd kick you in the shins as they called it, tap yo
ur shins with the instep of your - their instep against your shin, that was a favourite - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North country{\*\xmlclose} way of - fighting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They didn't do that in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
But - no, if you - you clobbered anybody like that they - they'd chop you down. See, you didn't fight fair, you - they didn't allow that. Well now there's no sense of - fairness running on, everythings done illegal today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did your mother or father belong to any savings clubs, did they ever put money away each week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well they might have
 belonged a loan club, what they call a loan club in the local pubs that - run - nearly every pub run a loan club. You could belong to a loan club, save yourself a shilling a week see. Couple of shillings a week, what you could afford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When would you get it out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Christmas. Just before Christmas. Christmas clubs. In the - that was the majority of savings. Some of 'em - in the churches had 'em. And chapels you see, these loan clubs. 'Course in the pubs when you - when you - in the pubs you see peo
ple went in and had a few as well, see it was trade for the polican. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they belong to any boot or sick clubs or funeral clubs that you knew of?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well yes, I suppose they would. There was all sorts of clubs what people - different - distric
ts had different ideas you see. But most of these missions run clubs for Christmas and - and publicans nearly all - you'd see a bill in all the pubs door - windows, loan club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Because they got something out of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, they - they give 'em so mu
ch interest every year see. And they - when the people had their money paid out to 'em they spent a few bob in the pub didn't they, so it was a custom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
What did you do as a boy in your leisure time, who would you play with when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 All the local boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
In the street. We had to walk all the way to Victoria Park from here to play in the park. Or - there used to be a park round the back of Stepney - called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Shandy{\*\xmlclose}
 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, they had a couple of swings in there. That was a favourite seaside resort of ours. 'Course now in later years the children have got {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Shadwell{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, on the river there which used to be Shadwell fish market. And then the - and then the - of course you could go on - go to the Tower if you wanted to, go and play round the Tower there. Round the Tower gardens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to play football and things in the street, was this allowed?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, you weren't allowed to play football in the street - you'd - the police would summons you, and if you broke a window, oh that was your lot. Oh yes, you - you'd have to - put up with being summonsed - the police would - summons you and you'd get fined.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of games would you play with other boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well we used to play - football, cricke
t, but - we used to play buttons with buttons. A game we played for - for buttons, or picture cards see. Saving picture cards, tram tickets as you like, but picture cards was everywhere you found 'em all over the place. See, in every packet of cigarettes 
was a picture card. And anybody smoked, you used to - there was millions of 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You used to collect these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, collect 'em, you'd try and get sets some boys would, sets of 'em. Some of those pictures was very - nice. There was a tobacco p
eople called Hobdens, they used to - sell and like flog those - little photo pictures, real photos. They was wonderful little pictures when you realize it. And they used to collect sets of 'em you see, different people. And children - collected 'em you se
e
, and they used to - swap with one another, your cards, and then we used to play - we - you could buy a - a packet of playing cards when I was a boy for ha'penny. A little - little pack about - just I suppose about inch - fifty-two playing cards and we us
ed to gamble with them for our cards see and marbles and one thing and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you play with any of your brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
My next brother. But as you grow up in a - in a family your brothers have disappeared. They've got their - they've got their own friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you get on well with most of your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you quite a close family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any one you were particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well that - that - my next brother
 to me - we were like - we slept together - for years you see. And of course then - when he left home to get married or - whatever it was - he - that's all finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to get your clothes dirty when you played outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They couldn
't stop that could they. Oh we'd have to - be careful, we'd have to clean 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your parents ever discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You were free to play with whoever was about?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any hobbies when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, I loved animals. Like birds say - chickens, rabbits, pigeons, Pigeons I love from a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have pigeons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, like you see you could buy a pigeon - when I was a boy, for fourpence. Threepe
nce and fourpence down Club Row or - or somebody caught a - a - someone else's pigeon they sold it to you, want a pigeon and you - that's how you - got - stocks, and then they breed like - flies you see, what I mean, those sort of things if you're kind to
 
'em and give 'em - and to feed 'em didn't cost you a lot of money, you see, for a penny or tuppence you could feed - them pigeons years ago buy a pint of seed for - penny or tuppence, or threeha'pence or something like that, would feed 'em, and then we us
e
d to go around - getting the food from the - from the horses, what the men threw away to give your rabbits, the chaff, waste chaff. And if they wasn't looking we'd put our hand in the bag and have a bit extra. Oh yes, we had sampling ways with us. Free sa
m
plex as they call it. Then you could go in - in all the market places like Spitalfields market for instance here, or Stratford market - but Spitalfields was the local up there, you could get all the food you wanted for - rabbits or anything like that see.
 
They lived on that. Hay, any hay. Up Whitechapel was a big hay market. It stood - where Aldgate East station is - three, up to Whitechapel church and then down Commercial Road - from - top of Commercial Street there, down nearly as far as - Church Lane ag
a
in see, and all them hay carts used to come up from - Dagenham, anywhere out - you know, High Wycombe, anywhere - and stand there and they were sold you see. Cart loads of hay. And a funny thing - underneath a lot of those hay carts of a morning - you'd s
e
e a pair of rabbits hanging. What - hanging underneath on the axle, somebody to buy see, they bought 'em up for a customer. They'd get a shilling for them I suppose, they'd be - lucky that time. Wild rabbits. Yes, you'd see - very often see a pair of rabb
