Well, when I was - when I was a boy - if we went down hop picking - see we went fishing. And we had - we was learnt of fish with a simple - thing. We used to get an old fish head in the 
summer, and hang it over the stream, on a branch of a tree that was hanging over a branch - a - a stream like a river. That river there we used to go to was the Medway. We used to hang that - fish head like a - plaice head or a cods head - the - fishmonge
r
s give 'em to you - and hang that on a bit of string, and of course the flies turned it, and the mag - maggots dropped off that fish - onto the stream didn't they. Well that caused what they call - a swarm of fish. And most of them, they were gudgeon. Lit
t
le black fish like a spratt. And I'm not telling you no lie, we used to - have a - a button, and a little - and a maggot on a hook, so we used to drop that in and with that same hook and button - and the maggot, we used to pull the fish off, put it in aga
i
n while they were swarming see and they'd pinch that, see, and we used to come home with a - a bagful of gudgeons, well mum - mum used to fry them like sprats for us, and that was like a treat I tell you, because that was fresh fish. We used to catch hund
r
eds like that. See, that cods head that - or plaice head hanging in the branch, keeps dropping on the stream, it caused a swarm of fish, 'cos they only had drop off one or two at a time, and each time they drop you see, and then we'd put our little hook i
n with the bait and pull 'em out all the time while they were there. It wasn't - it - it didn't drop in the water a couple of inches and we got the fish on on it, and then pull the fish off before it could - do any damage to itself.
