 learnt to swim - with the - with the - with the swarming, with a fish head was a - a real sensible idea that. And - we caught - you always used to say - Londoners say like that was end of August and September - you want some fried sprats? You see, you di
dn't say gudgeon, they - that was all they were, 'cos -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
They was - we learnt that trick with the - what do you call it - the maze with the pheasants. See, 'cos we - we was watching - and seeing 'em catching 'em, of course when we found out the trick w
e knew what to do. We used to get a handful of - make a little hole through the maize and threadle the horsehair in and tie it in a knot - like that. A foot, less than a foot and of course when it got down here they - they tried to get it out again. Of co
urse it was the hair and then they used to have their head on the ground, we used to pick 'em up.
