arm, he's - he had a injured shoulder blade. And he had a cycle, and it had solid red tyres, no soft }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 pneumatic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  tyres, and he had a - a - what they call a Dunlop - Dunlop - not a Dunlop, a - oh - forget - the - the pump - the - - the brake just on top of the
 tyre, went down, Bowden brake they called it that time. Bowden brake. Bowden. Bowden brake, you pushed it up and it shut - like - similar to these - carriages have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 foot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  for the invalid carriage. Well anyhow, he used to ride that all over the country. 'Cou
rse he never had no problems with - punctures because it was solid red tyre, it was rubber that time. And - all he had to do was to oil the bike regular. See, keep it clean, and he did that and he used to have only one arm, now that chap rode all over thi
s
 country on that bike, with a fixed wheel bike. No free wheel, he couldn't - he - he went downhill you sent down it. But he only had that as I say - he never had no expenses attached to the bike, only oil it now and then, and that was his bike that he - l
et me - ride along.
