Well very - very like - well you see that brother of mine, that eldest brother, that elder brother, he was apprentice in the - in the motor works for Strayton Esquires, and of course he - he - he was a scholarship boy when he was young, and he was a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 learned chap}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 and then he become a bus driver. 'Course that time a bus driver was a - well I expect they had here good wages didn't they. See, yes, and he - and as I say when he
 joined the Army, he become - Douhlas Aigs chaffeur, he was a - he was - of course he was made a sergeant straight away see, Staff Sergeant. Oh yeh, he was made Staff Sergeant straight away. Because - now I don't suppose there was a dozen - spare drivers 
in the country that time could drive a Rolls, or anything like that, he could drive any motor vehicle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why did he choose to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
That was his ambition. Yes. Well when - when he was young - I remember when he was young, he used to make - he - 
you know what his hobby was? Making little firewood - little trains - steam trains. He used to buy the little bits of the engine he could, here, in - and - there was firms in the city you could go and buy the wheels and the different parts, and he used to
 
make those little steam - that was his hobby, making steam trains. Steam carriages like to go on lines. And then he, as I say, he was - then he - then he finished up, he finished up as - a garage owner and mechanic. He took a partner in with him and - I t
h
ink they - he sold it out to 'em. 'Course all the - all the police in - where they lived - round Porthcawl used to bring the work to 'em see. They wanted a - anybody had a - motorbike or - that was the first starting, that wanted repairing they brought it
 to Fred see and Fred done it all. All motors and that. And he used to come up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - and buy cars for people - different people. See, they wanted to buy a car they'd send him up here because they were the headquarters that time was around Portland Str
eet in - in the West End there where - what do you call it - Madame Tussauds is, all round that area, that was the car area. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Portland Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. A workshop in the gard - in the - gard - in the - yard you know. And - I made a workshop and bench see, and my dad
 came in one - Christmastime and he said to me, Alf - he knew somebody down and out could do with some - giblets for Christmas. He said, could you - show him how to get 'em. I said, yes. So - this man was a giant of a man. He worked - he was a brewer, a d
r
ay - drayman on the brewery. And I took him, we went a - on the bus for a penny up to Leadenhall Market. And - there they were glad if you cleared the shop for 'em, Christmastime, 'cos that' rubbish you see. As - as they strip the - as they were selling t
h
e - ducks and - and geese and the turkeys, they - throw 'em down, big heaps of these giblets, so I went in to this man, I - his brother used to have the - paper shop here, with the newspapers of Sunday. And - I said - do you want some of them giblets clea
r
ed away? So he said, yeh, we'd be glad of that. See, I knew the chap in the fish shop side of this, they had a poulterers shop and a fish shop. So he said, yeh, well you can have it. So this fellow, he got a sack, big sack, holds I suppose like a - a suga
r
 sack, hold about two hundredweight of sugar and he fill it up with all these heads and livers and gizzards and - feet, and back we go and we're back home in no time. And - I left him. Of course my - dad told me after what happened. He was up all night cl
e
aning these - he got a great big bowlful of livers, that's only the livers, he took all the - there's a little green - in - a little green thing I think - in - the gall. He cut the gall out. He got a great big bowlful of liver only. Now what's that worth 
t
oday? You realize it. And he said - there was all these throats there like - oxtails the way he said it, they was thick as ox - some of them geese throats and - and turkeys throats was very thick - thick. And that man was up all night long cleaning 'em ou
t
, he had a - I think about six little children. And he was telling everybody in the pub what - what I done I for him. He got enough food there to last 'em a couple of months. See, and then - then - that time - see, just before Christmas - like - the night
 
before Christmas - these people were glad to get rid of it you see, you can't get the dustmen to come round and take - yes. That just shows you how you could get food. And talking about fish - I had a - a man had a - worked in a shop in Leadenhall market,
 
and we used to go up there for only the fish heads. We used to get - large plaice heads. What's that other fish, halibut. Halibut heads. Halibut heads and plaice heads, we used to take them - of course they only threw them in the - what they call the - wa
s
te - what do they - put on the ground - they used to make a - fertilizer out of the fish, yes, that was it, they used to make fertilizer out of it, you went in them - big firm down at West Ham used to supply all the fish shops with these - big dustbins, r
o
und - and - and I used to go there and - say to my friend - all right tonight? He'd say, yeh, and he'd put all the special ones in a - certain bin for me you see, he'd say, here, take what you like. And I used to take home - a - a - about a quarter hundre
d
weight of - of - of fish - fish head. Good solid food that was. And then my poor dad, he - he loved it. He really loved it, my mother used to boil it for him, she'd put some little spices in it, when it was boiling, and then when it got cold it was like a
 thick - glue jelly. And he loved that. And no wonder he - it done him good. And we were all brought up on that. Didn't cost nothing did it, that food.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 If you knew where to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, yeh, yeh. Yeh, cost nothing. And the same - the same thing when
 we was at - down in the hop country. We used to go and get the mushrooms. And that - to me I think - is direct nature you're eating. See, that's real nature you're eating, mushrooms. See? Didn't cost nothing that time, now they - I buy mushrooms now - th
e
y charge me - six shillings a pound. One and six for a quarter. Cor, when I realize what I've given away as a boy. I - I'll tell you a funny thing I've heard in the country, this is true. Went down - hop picking one day, and walking round and I spot a lot
 
of little potatoes growing. You know - the - they're growing - up - young, new potatoes as we called 'em. And it appeared - where they were growing the farmer had put all these sacks of potatoes and that and bagged them up the - when - dug up the old pota
t
oes, and all the little oddments had turned - seed and - and grew, see, and they was all new potatoes. Of course when I found this here - spot - they were really wild you see, they weren't - you ain't stealing from the farmer, there was all these young - 
seedling potatoes growing, and I dug 'em up, and we had bags and bags and bags of those little marbles - new potatoes, and mother used to boil 'em in their skins see, and give 'em to us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did people take babies hop picking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Yes, yeh, yeh,
 take babies - babies, everything went, they went in the field with 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So really a mother could take all her children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, yeh, took all the family, we used to take - you see. What - you see - how they gave it - some places they used - slept 
in tents, but a lot of people wouldn't - would - don't like tents. We used to - nost hop pickers went - used to live in - sheds belonging to the farmer, what he kept as a - a animal compound during the - winter, see. He kept a - a cow or - or - whatever h
e
 kept in there. And they was always - they always - give you hales of straw to put on the floor, and faggots as they had bundles of wood there, and your beds was made on top of the faggot, the faggots was placed on the ground, and on top of that was the b
a
les of straw, and then you made your bed. There's many a thing been lost in them there beds and never got back. You know, what had dropped, if they lost any money that time - they was very careful. And - all they had that time was candles to light them hu
ts, or little paraffin lamp.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you do if it was wet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well you'd stop in wouldn't you. You'd be in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You couldn't pick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
You - oh - oh - well you - you couldn't pick very - very well if it was raining. I know I've been there - fr
ozen of a morning, early in - September there's sometimes frosty mornings you know. End of August and September, been frosts so they had to light fires in the fields. All the old - pieces of faggot what we found.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you ever remember years where it wa
s raining so badly it wouldn't be worth going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes. They've done that, yeh, many a time, yeh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you do, come home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Mm. The - if it - the rain - the weather was too rough they - they - naturally want to - come hom
e, see, well these farmers wouldn't pay 'em out 'til the last - minute see, 'til it was all finished. See? So they - they didn't give you all the money that was on your book. No, no. Say you earnt day - say the average person earnt say six shillings or se
ven shillings a day. They'd only sub - sub about half of that you see. They'd leave that 'til they come home. They used to come home to have a glorious picnic in London didn't they, a booze up as I called it. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your mother use some of the hop picking money for things in the house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, she - well, every - every woman - more or less - does everything for her - the home don't she. She buys this and that. See? I - I - done my best from a youngster to help her. You see, the last - the 
last time I think I remember going hop picking with her - was just after the '14 war. See? And - she got a - a - a woman had asked her to take a little girl down there, give her a holiday. And this child - had no - what they call - appetite, she was real 
-
 delicate hungry child. And 'course - I gave her my sample of - how to eat, I went and got the fresh clean button mushrooms, and I fried 'em, well - fried 'em, that time bacon was very dear, tuppence ha'penny a pound. And you could buy a pound with tuppen
c
e - what they call streaky bacon, tuppence and tuppence ha'penny a pound that was. And I have a great memory for prices, and my mum'd buy a pound of that - and - and - they'd fry the bacon. Well this little girl, she - the woman that sent her said she had
 
no appetite. Was right, the child didn't want to eat. So I - my mum made me some of those mushrooms on bread see, and fried - what they call dipped in the - and I said to the little girl, here, taste this, see if you like it. Because I loved it you see. A
n
d - this little child - she - ate - ate the slice of this bread and - there was no stopping her after that. When she got the flavour. And she want - only wanted to come with me mushrooming, I said, no, it's too early going out at four o'clock in the morni
n
g. I used to get up four o'clock they used to. Before it was - before the mist - rose - on the grass, see, as - as you see the grass - you could see a - a foot, and then it comes a bit higher - about a yard and then you could look - look under the mist an
d
 you could see where the mushrooms were, and we knew where the - to look for 'em, in one special place, where these - sheep always - stood see. And - as they - as they rose up so these fresh - buttons was there and we used to go and - cut 'em off you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would you be able to buy mushrooms when you were at home from the stalls or would they be too expensive, would that be a luxury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they'd be about fourpence a pound wouldn't they, they'd be dear. Fourpence. Fourpence a pound. You get the best
 English tomatoes threepence and fourpence a pound you could, I remember that. Now you've got to pay about four shillings a pound haven't you. But these - that was the price. And the same with the mushrooms. You people - people that - that used to - getti
ng them like we did for nothing would say, fancy giving him fourpence a pound, that's - you understand? You wouldn't do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would anyone from outside the home ever come in and help your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 She didn't want it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Suppose she was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, would that, yes. They would do that, everybody would do - would do that. But as we grew up we all done our little chores.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were very young neighbours would come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Well - well I know when we was very little - they all ha
d their own groups of friends, the women, and they all helped one another, yes. Yes. My - my missus is the same. When she knew anybody was in trouble - she went and helped 'em out with the - confinement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about relatives, did you have many?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, had plenty of relatives all came, yes. There was all relatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you quite a close family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, well they - you had all your relatives you see - they had - my dad had - my dad was - was from a big family, his - his father - his - wha
t was I going to say - he was the eldest son of four brothers. Matthew, Mark, Luke and John, that was their names. And they - all the cousins from them, all used to come around to us. Most of them was - carmen, or - lot of 'em was mail drivers, all that -
 what drove them red vans or the pair of horse vans or the mails horse or single horse vans. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your parents invite friends home very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, they - used to have - yes, they'd have a - they'd have a party every - now and then on a Sunda
y night - mostly on a Sunday night. I remember my dad say to 'em on a Sunday night, they come round and eat up all the remains of the food of the house you know, what they call bubble and squeak night, and they'd all have a supper, and if they had a glass
 
of beer they'd - they'd - drink up and if it was a cold or wet night I've heard my dad say very often - well boys and girls - you've got to go home, I'm in my house so I've got - I've got - aint got to go out in the cold and wet. He used to give 'em the h
i
nt to go see. 'Cos that time you see - pubs was open 'til twelve o'clock - on a Saturday night. Half past twelve other nights see. Eleven o'clock Sundays. See, eleven o'clock was - early closing, eleven o'clock - in the pubs, seven to eleven. But in the w
e
ek time they was open 'til half past twelve - bar - Saturday night. That was twelve o'clock Saturday night, because Sunday morning see. They were going into Sunday morning. It was long hours the publicans had didn't they? They used to be open five o'clock
 in the morning, standing at the door waiting to see their customers. I - you see 'em standing at the - the pub door - five o'clock in the morning.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Hard life wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - every - every corner was pubs weren't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did - they make a good living, the publicans?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I suppose they did, but you see everybody had - drank didn't they. You see, if was - it was natural hobby of everybody to drink. They never had no other pleasures in life, the working classes didn't, or any other classe
s. You could either - be a - drinker or a teetotaller, and if you was a teetotaller you was - you was lost - in a lost world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about drinking at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, some people drank at home, and the - you could go in the off licences to get it, the
re was - off licences everywhere, the same as pubs. You see, and people - people that was what I call a bit select, didn't want other people to know they drank went in off licences. See - they - they didn't want to be known by their - Tom, Dick and Harry 
that they're drinkers so they went in off licenses and got their
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about the difference between a saloon and a public bar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
A - a - a saloon bar was - you paid a ha'penny extra to go in a saloon bar mostly. If it - beer was a penny in the - public it was in the private bars - another ha'penny or a penny the most.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 The different type of person would go in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, well - they - they didn't want their - the poor - to mix with the rich, you see what I mean, the rich didn't want to mix with t
he poor. Understand? And they wanted to talk - business see, business people went in the saloon bar, spoke business. Like - my - one sister-in-law of mine told me, she said - if you go in the pub, Alf - pay another ha'penny, and you go in the saloon bar o
r
 the private bar and you keep your ears open you'll hear - listen something for your benefit. She said, you might hear - something - good for the four o'clock race or the two o'clock race, but you won't hear it in the public bar, all they're interested in
 - is the beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Didn't they used to talk about racing, the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, not a lot. Not like you do today. But - you see, now - they haven't got pubs now for that, they've got betting shops, all - everywhere - betting shops and boys.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And you said men didn't discuss politics much in pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, not a lot. I don't think so. Not as I - as far as I know. You see, I - I as a young man I was a - a chairman of the union, it would be the Carmens Union I was - when I was driving, I - apart
 from my trade I was still a shoemaker, but I was - I was - that was - what I was doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did either of your parents ever teach you to read before you went to school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well we - we - we used to have the newspaper, that's all. New of the World.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did any of your brothers ever teach you to read or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no, it came automatically along.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 About four. I went to school at four, about four, a young - then - and wh
en I went to the regular school I was about - eight in this school, this {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dempsey Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school. That was what they call junior mixed, there was boys and girls together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was the first one you went to called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 The school, it was a - a - children's school down Stepney here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that just the infants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, infants school, well - it was a mixed school you see, and - that's where it - it went you see, and then from when we moved - up this way, we moved back - from - lower down Stepney, w
e come up here to Gold Street - and the - my mother took me here. Only she took me the once and - and never took me no more, I went myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have brothers and sisters going who would go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I had a - I had two brothers - went to ano
ther school, not this school. And the sisters was younger than me you see. They - they were - younger than me. Like two sisters was younger and one sister was - younger, she - I suppose - time I was about - ten she went to school see, something like that.
 She used to go to school younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you started at about four what time would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
In the morning? About nine. Nine to half past four, something like that, nine to four.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Never had - oh I had that when you got home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you come home at the end of the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes. When - when I was at this school when I was eight, used to come home twelve - to two see. Used to come home at twelve and have a - a little snack and then go back - for the afternoon, half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would all your other brothers and sisters come home at lunchtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - mostly they - they would do, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they have any school meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. No, no, no. One brother - he used to go - to a 
- a mission in Stepney there, what they call Stepney - a - a mission up in Commercial Road, that used to give you a bun and a mug of tea - of a morning. That was for poor children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that early in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes, yes, before you we
nt to school, about - seven to eight, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why did he go and not the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He belonged to a different school. See, it was in a - different school you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You didn't all go to the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I couldn't say. I went to Dempsey Street, they went to - Church School, St Thomas's here - next to - Thames Police Court. Of course it's all being - built on now, it's all pulled down, that church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that a church school over there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, that's a - council school, that was the School Board for 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} when I was a little boy, and they changed it to the LCC. That was - School Board for London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that a mixed school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh. Yeh. Boys - there was infants, boys and gir
ls - and girls. Yeh, downstairs was the infants, just here, in this street. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dempsey Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Round the back was the junior mixed, upstairs was the - big boys and the girls was at - underneath see, in the middle. There was girls, - infants and junior mixed - all - all like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you there right til you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, right 'til I left - from - from the age of say about eight - the beginning of - just the beginning of the century 'til I was about - let me see - 1908 I left school. As soon as we left - the - the - Christmas come I didn't go to school no more. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I - I - I - I took it all in good part. I could - we - we learnt you see and there was all - that time in this district was - business peoples children and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 policemen\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 children, was all - nice school that was. There was - only a couple of Newish people went to that school when I was a child. And then - then all of a sudden - hundreds got there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did most of the Jewish children go to their own special school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, they had schools for - they had one in Stepney Green, the Jewish school. And then they had - here - this street at the back here, near the London Hospital, Rutland Street they called it, on the parallel with this schoo
l here like straight down the road. There was a lot of Jewish people there. You see - well there was no coloured - problems like there is today. Indians and - coloured people. You saw a - coloured man once in - a blue moon, or a Chinaman. Chinamen were ri
g
ht down Pennyfields - district. East - Limehouse, that was called Pennyfields, that was the Chinese - element. But coloured people, there was just a few knocking around Cable Street way, that - grown up, and - become - you know, inter - woven with white p
eople.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you say there was a lot of prejudice against the Jews in the early years?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, it was terrible when I was a boy. Jews, everybody had it - distate of the Jews you see. Of course now it's different - nobody's got any distaste f
or anybody. You see - there - I never - there was never a coloured boy in that school when I was a boy. There was a half and half family, named of Devonport, they was two brothers, boxers, they - they - interlocked with - with the white people you know I 
mean they were - of Spanish descent, coloured people. But not like you see the Negroes now like you - see 'em now. Very few there was. Coloured people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you think the Jewish people were badly treated by the people in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well they weren't treated badly by the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
East End{\*\xmlclose}, you see, they had a - everybody - they had a - a different outlook in life, they had a business instinct. They - when they become a tailor they wanted to become a tailor master. They weren't satisfied with being a wo
rker. That was the difference you see. They had business instincts you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think that's because people suffered and been in great poverty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, when - when they was out in - when - when they were out in - Russia, the - the Jewish fratern
ity - they - they had to join the Army, see, 'cos there was what they called conscription there at that time. But they - came over here because they had to join the services, so they joined - they went into Germany and all like that, and got - got across 
h
ere somehow or other, and got bled by the people that brought 'em here, they used to give 'em - about a few shillings a week - these tailor masters and - have expert workmen for nothing a week. And all they fed 'em on was bread and - and - what I call - b
r
ead and butter, bread and margarine. Five - five shill - I - I knew a man, a shoemaker, a friend of mine, he finished up - he worked in a shop - six in the morning 'til ten o'clock at night mending boots and making boots. And - one day he - the - 1914 war
 
broke out - and - he took his apron off, old apron, and he - the guv'nor looked at him, he said, where are you going? And his name was Zalec. He said, I'm going to see a friend of mine. He said, what, you making half a day today? That was ten o'clock at n
i
ght, he'd been at work since six in the morning. And he said, what you making, half a day today? And I can remember lots of 'em saying to me, Alf when I - go home of a night I say good morning to the policeman. When - when they go home of a night from wor
k, they say good morning to the policeman, that meant that they were going home in the morning. After twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you see many of the orthodox Jews walking around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they have these special schools for the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, they got the - tomatorahs there, oh yes. I know - I know all about the Jewish religion. You see, my - wife - was a Jewish woman, I married a Jewish woman. But of course she's from the old English Jews. Her father was a - what would you call a ma
n - he was a secretary to Disraeli. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 About him being in the Primrose League, you told me that about when he died.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, when he - when - he - buried. Mm. He got a whole - whole armful of primroses he had, right over. Pair of house. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Looking back at your schooldays would you say you liked it at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. I did. I like - I'm glad I went to school when I was a child because it - it - occupied your mind. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was the attitude of most boys, were they waitin
g to leave in order to earn money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well most of them mostly yes. Yes, and I saw - like even that time - hundreds and hundreds of boys - when they're young were smoking. You see. And - I can remember their - their sicknesses from that. They become sic
k you see. And when I was young I was on the athletic side you see, I - learned to swim always, football, anything - but - swimming and boxing all those sort of things, I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 gymnastic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  in the - gymnasium, and - I exercise my body as I say, right 'til I was
 - twenty-four - before I started to - smoke. That was when I - started to work for myself properly. And I - you know I got a bit - free you see, so I become a smoker. Otherwise I wouldn't have never smoked if I hadn't have been a - a workman or an athlet
ic again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about teachers, what did you think of the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh, they were very good. Oh yes. Our teachers was real good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Is there any special teachers you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well I know - I - I know 'em all, I know their names as wel
l. There was here - in this school was a - a Welsh teacher named Mr Williams, he was very strict. And there's a Mr Chandler, he was in the Boer War. And - he was in the City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
London Volunteers{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the CIV's they used to call them. And - Mr - Mr Lodge - and 
Mr - Mr Lodge was very big man, but the man before him was Mr Caton. But Mr Lodge was the headmaster, and then - there was a Mr Pepper, and there was - Mr Furby and there was two or three young men teachers - junior - what do you call them, Junior - junio
r
 teachers. And then - I remember all the teachers. I remember - Miss Hall, she - she was the headmis - headmistress the junior mixed. There was a Mrs Day, that was in the junior mixed. That - beginning of the century that is, I'm talking about. Mrs Day wa
s about 1901 or two and Mrs - Miss Hall, that's their names.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you remember any of those having a special influence on you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well yeh, they used to tell you - do you little turns, 'cos we - I was poor you see. And then - they helped you in giving you - getting you little things, like a million little things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Like - go to a - a mission or a concert, see, at a mission, anywhere. They had a little - I can even remember the caretaker, and that's - over seven - seventy years ago, his name was Mr Weaver. In - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Dempsey Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school he was an ex-Naval man. A great big robust chap. And I often think of the kids around here today, the - he never stood that nonsense what they do today, cutting and carving wall
s and - mark - what they call vandalism. He wouldn't - never wear that. You see. He they're encouraged by everybody to do these things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Boys in those days had more respect for sort of property?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. And if you hurt an animal when I was a boy - w
ell they see you throw a bottle down or a piece of - a nail or anything sharp - for an animal, a horse or a cat - horse especially. Anyone see you broke a bottle - you'd get a - a real good hiding. And you never forget it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have a very formal sort of teaching, people sitting in desks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 We all had desks, yes, we had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And chanting things, multiplication tables and that sort of stuff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, just the ordinary - give you your - from one class to the other, different - the hard
est job we had when I was a - I remember was shorthand, they brought that in - to light, and - I - I liked shorthand, honest, I did, and we - bought a book for a couple of coppers, a Pitman's book, and it showed you the - starting of it, and I haven't don
e
 that for donkey's years, but - I remember it was - one one was think and one was thick, that was a different letter. A different meaning. A tb - tt, jk, k gay I think I remember it - that was how it went, but - they stopped it, the shorthand. They said i
t was too hard for children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have a special master came in to teach that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, the teachers - mostly the teachers - of course some were proficient more than others. Them teachers was good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have a good sports master who encouraged boys who were good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, there was no sports when I was a boy hardly. Wasn't no sport masters. You - you just went to school, you never had no sports. You - you made your own sports. See, now you can - now the children, they can go swimming, the
y can go every - we - we didn't, unless you belonged to a - you went - yourself to the baths. See, if I wanted to go swimming, I used to go to the baths and challenge who - who - who wanted to race me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Nothing organised?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, was no organisation
 that time. Unless you joined a - a club and then the club started. It was the same when the Scouts started, I remember when I was a boy - they started Scouts. Well they joined the Boys Brigade, first you could go in the Boys Brigade, belonged to a church
. Most big churches held the - branch of the Boys Brigade. And then - after that the Scouts started, and then the sports seemed to start from them. Beginning when the - the Boy Scouts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you a scout?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. I never went as a Scout.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you go to play football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 In the big park like over - Victoria Park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have to belong to a club to be able to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. Just go there, yes. And of course we played football in the streets. 'Til we was turned away by the - neighb
ours or the police. Police would - summons you you see if they saw you kicking the ball. When I was a boy they'd summons you. See, the people used to complain to the police and the police would - not only tump you round the ear they would - summons you as
 well. That was - when things was getting - they said out of hand, and then there was - little games in schools what they used to play up - they'd play up the line, throw coins up onto the pavement on a line. That was a form of gambling, and cards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Wasn't that allowed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. Playing badger in the streets and all like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they come along and stop you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, they'd - they'd raid them. If they - if you was playing up the line, all of a sudden police'd come behind you and pinch your pennies and - and clump you round the ear and run, see, well they had beer money didn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You think they'd keep those pennies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Certainly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose you didn't fuss about it, didn't complain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, you was only glad you got
 off. That's what they used to do. They used to play - they used to put a - a cigarette book, little - book like that - what we had the cigarette papers in, and they put two ha'pennies on there, and they'd toss 'em up, and they'd toss 'em up which comes d
own head or tails see. If you're on the heads, the tails belong to the - thrower. See when he throws up if it comes down two tails their his, if - it comes down two heads - it's yours like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you cheat at that do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, there was tri
cks they had loaded pennies and all like that. Double ha'pennies as they call it, with both heads the same, stuck together. There was lots of way of cheating. But those exploits with sponning the coins, they could - throw 'em over - a lot of it went on on
 
the - canal bank, I mean in the East End there was canals run from - London right up to the North or - Midlands. And on these canal banks on the soft earth where the horses pulled, the barges, they used to have gambling schools, well that was away from th
e
 police see. Well now and then they'd get raided. Oh there was a - was a lot of that went on, all over the place. For - tossing ha'pennies for - heads and tails, went all over the place, in the docks, in the wharves, everywhere - where you went in the Eas
t End.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Any cards, did people play cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, they played cards and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 In the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
In the streets they'd play cards, banker they called it that time. Banker and these - plenty of 'em used to play - that Jewish game they called Tharo
, they - lay it out and - then the man that took the bank you see - you put your money down and he - and he paid out - they paid out on this Tharo game. Oh there was a great amount of gambling went on in - in the - in the - country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about betting, was there much street corner betting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, betting, street betting, the - that went on always. See, well then the police used to raid now and then, and catch you with a bet and you - they - you got fined - for making a bet. And these street book
makers - they had their pitches you know, and they were giving the - tipping the law off - for not touching them. And that's what they went on. Here I know in one little area - was a - about ten bookmakers, in one little area. And they used to give the ma
n
 on duty in the morning a couple of shillings, and the man on duty in the afternoon a couple of shillings. See, that - then - so much money each week for a guv'nor, a collect - they had their collectors you see, they did, the law. And that's what went on,
 they made fortunes in - in a little way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Real protection money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, it was for them. But - now there's still street betting going on. Apart from these shops, see, these shops what's going on now, you go in a shop now - and you can't get locked 
up for betting. But you can if you give it to a man in the street to bed. It's illegal. If you're going in a licensed shop it's different, but if you give it to a - a legal collector - there's a man goes by here with his wife - every day regular, they liv
e in one of these big flats - like one of the flats and - they go round all these workshops collecting the private little bets see. They're not licensed. And they - they pay 'em out every day see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When we're looking at before the first world war, woul
d large sums be involved in this sort of betting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, book - bookmakers had names - one bookmaker, used to be - in - what we call - one, there was plenty, one particular had - you see, from here to that school - a - a row of men all lined 
up giving their bets, men and women, giving their bet, sixpenny bets and shilling bets, two bold or whatever it was. See. They had - had big - big - what do you call, collection. Hundreds of people put their bets on. Especially on the big race day you see
, everybody want to back on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 say for instance. They was all lined up there - with all their nom-de-plumes, they put it on, then they pay them out - every now and then someone absconded - they couldn't pay out, they went broke. And that - that went 
on frequent see. Welshers as they call them, that's the name they give 'em, Welshers, they - couldn't pay out. I think - something - I know the horse - at that time once and it - and it all - all gibbed the lot of 'em. I've forgot the name of that, everyb
o
dy used to - say to one another - what won the - Queen's Prize, that was it, was the - the Queen's Prize, happened the man - a lot of 'em all gibbed it, they took - overtook the money, they couldn't pay out. So the customers got nothing did they. Oh there
 was thousands of bookmakers in the streets. Everywhere you looked was a bookmaker. Tell you, in that little area alone was - about a dozen bookmakers just there - about half a mile from here, in one little area, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Duckett Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} they called it. It was a well
 known notorious neighbourhood. That area was about a dozen - bookmakers. So if that man on duty was down there for a month early turn, he got - that money didn't he. That policeman. That was only one little sideline. Oh - all them - all that went on, Whi
techapel and all the shops and - and - everywhere you looked was bookmakers you see. I - I - I - I'll tell you a true thing about bookmaking. I was passing the police station just here, that's called - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Arbour Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that's the Thames Police Court. And a ma
n standing on the door on duty - says to me, what do you know for today Alf? I says, a certain horse. He says, well give us your money and I'll put it on for you. There you are. He's the bookmaker. Yes, he put it in his pocket. He - he was the bookmaker. 
See what I mean? That was one of the - the boys. Yes. Oh there was some right boys about, these were all - all sorts. Yes, that - that's true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there lots of petty crime going on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, it's always been, always that. Always thieves about. You 
see - there's always been - paltry people. Who will go through life like that. Life will never stop this, always the - paltry people, who will - what do you call - rob one another Get rich quick, people lazy. Pickpockets and all like that, paltry. They're
 
one of the most detestable people I think there is, pickpockets. You see, they've bot no compassion on any poor - woman, or old age woman - or a young girl, innocent girl, getting on a bus, they pinch her purse, and all things like that. To me that's one 
of the most - wicked things there is in the world. And I've always worked hard as a - a lad, me own - and when I see them paltry people I - think no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 There was quite a lot of pickpockets about earlier in the century?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Nm. Oh yes. Always been. I - 
I know a occasion my mother went - shopping in a local market, Watling Street, and she put her hand in her pocket one day - and there's no purse, it's gone. And - another day soon after that, she put her hand in her pocket and she put her hand on someone 
e
lse's hand. Of course she was a tough big woman. She held that hand, and it was a little boy about - fourteen or twelve to fourteen say, and what did she do, she clobbered him - straight in the nose. So a woman standing there said, blooming shame to hit a
 
poor little boy like that. And mother give her one. Now, she said, now we're getting somewhere. And she knocked her down. Well they summonsed that woman, police did. She was - the Fagin for learning the children to pick pockets. That's true. She - when sh
e said it's a shame to hit that boy - mother struck her and knocked her down. 'Cos she wouldn't have none of that nonsense you know, and then we had a tough time. But she didn't believe in that sort of thing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there any prostitutes in this area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Everywhere they were weren't they? Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes. Every area you've got 'em. You've got 'em even now. But now you've got 'em amongst your - you don't know who - who who's who. You see - they - they're always like that. You - you see, in 
the - in the areas where - seamen were, coming home from - sea in the East End, Cable Street - Popular or anywhere, near the docks, they get in these pubs and and a sailor did at sea a - for months and months and months - and in the two ticks they get him
 drunk and - and they used to have - and britch him, take - take all his money. \{BLANK\} Assaulting little babies, they're the people, that - that - that gets me - I think to myself, I'd like to be the one to deliver the cat to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were many children 
molested in the early years of the century, do you remember that happening often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, you heard of cases but - not a lot. There was one thing what I was always brought up to detest. Anybody - interfering with a boy - like a parson for instance - 
or these what they call - sexual men, hey - that was another - never our way of life. And we was brought up rough and ready but not that way of life. Honest workers, and we couldn't stick that. That way of life. See it led to horrible things with children
 and that, and it wasn't our way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there many cases at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh there's always been that. It's always been that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But it was frowned upon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes it was - then - there was groups of fellows you see - they're all - I think they're 
best out of the world those sort of people. That's why I say the cat would prevent it. And you see there's - thousands of people - lead that immoral life. Men and women. Them lesbian girls as they call 'em. Women and then - then there are these - we used 
to call 'em pansies, the men. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Nancy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} boys. But - then the - during the war, and I was air raid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 warden}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 I - befriended a flower seller. He used to sell flowers in Whitechapel, and he used to go all round the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West End{\*\xmlclose} - with lovely flowers. And he - he lived ro
und the back of Whitechapel - and - I was about the only - fellow that he - he - he seemed to have confidence in. You know why? He showed me - bundles of envelopes with wages in. He worked for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Lyons{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s. That was a sideline see. From his flowers. But he was 
one of them queer - queer type, he spoke like a girl, you know that feminine voice, and he showed me - he had a lot of money in the Co-op, he was in the Co-op banking movement, Leman Street, and he showed me money and I says to him - why do you keep all t
h
ose - about fifty, sixty envelopes with money - in, I said - he says - yes, he says, I should - put 'em in the bank. I said, you have that - undo 'em all, put the money in the Co-op bank - for safety. That was during the - blitz you see. And he showed me 
-
 little things like that, because I was not - wasn't interested in it. But if I had been a rogue, could have - knocked that fellow, he - he - he was harmless to my opinion to prevent it. But - there it is, that's how they go on those sort of people. They 
ask to be - what they call murdered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The prostitutes at the beginning of the century, could you tell by the way they were dressed, the type of person they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - most of 'em - most of 'em was the way they - done their faces up. They wouldn'
t be like you, clean faced. They had their faces powdered and painted, all the blue - like you see the blue under their eyes now, and they're not prostitutes. But they make theirselves look like one, the girls today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Most women presumably didn't wear make up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, when a girl made her face up with ro - roses on her cheek, you knew that she was a prostitute, because she made herself up. She put red on her lips, well of course then it become a fashion, everybody had red lips and that, but as I say, 
today they make theirself look like that. See. But that - that way of living has always been throughout the world that, people trying to get rich quick. How long they get rich for I don't know, but there it is. But most of those - distasteful people - don
't know what to think. You go in the country you'll see a girl - without any make up whatever, got a lovely complexion, you see. But you - go in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, they have to put about fifty different colour paints on their face - before it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 satisfies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  them. The one colour mixes up the other - other, you don't know what - what they are. Their eyes is plucked and their - everything's done but - long lashes on their eyes. What for?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose they think they look nice, more attractive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 If a woman got a clean -
 what I call a clean smart dress on, and a clean face and hands, she's attractive. But - to a sensible minded person I think that them coloured faces - distracts them, they don't like it. Because it - it looks - horrible. I think so anyhow. When you see s
o
me of the colours on their face, pink, white and - and all - the green under their eyes, it is not natural. You see when you - when you clean a horse, like when I was a boy - when you brushed a horse and cleaned him, you took all the - dust out of him, he
 was healthy and happy. That's another thing. And if you don't do that to a person they can't be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Looking back at when you were at school, do you remember your teachers emphasising certain things as important? Things like manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Oh yes. Learn you to - learn you manners yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, oh if you - I went once to school with my shoes a bit dirty, they'd tell you of it and send you home to you cleaned 'em and come back, and that was a great insult to you - if yo
u went to school with a dirty - pair of shoes on, teacher send you home, go along and clean your shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about very poor children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They - some of the very poor children never had any feet - boots on did they.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you remember seeing children like that in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Listen - I'll tell you about that. When the '14 war broke out - I was driving a van here in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 by a school playground, on a winter's morning. And all the children stood out there in the playground in the snow,
 with no boots and stockings on. Nine out of ten of 'em had no boots and stockings on. And they stood in the snow, lined up to go into school, with the snow squeezing through their feet. This is true, honest. That's the year - the - beginning of the war.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that in a very poor district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, Stepney here, opposite the gas - gas works in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Ben Johnson Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Haggis Street school they called it, and there - there's the - the playground there, it's just - well, last couple of years been pulled down. 
You can see where they lined up, and I used to go in that playground with this girl as a - like - when she was Guide Captain. They used to use it of a evening as a - Guide centre, and they - I told her all there where the children stood and I've driven by
 
here, of course if you're on a van you can look over the - down on the playground. Yes, they - dozens and dozens of children there - rough cold weather, had no boots and shoes on, all lined up there - that was the beginning of the 1914 war. Yes, and in th
e - in the late - in the - in a - about 19 - 14/16 that time -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Wouldn't the school do anything about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What could they do? The war came along, they couldn't do nothing could they?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 There must have been some sort of charities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, 
there was - Doctor Barnado's and all that place, they had their own inmates didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you remember Doctor Barnado's round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you tell us anything about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, Doctor Barnado's, they had a - a mission h
ere, what they call Edinburgh Castle, in - Ben Johnson Road, just by that school that I just told you about, and they had a place here in Stepney Causeway. They had a boot factory there they used to make boots and mend boots for the inmates I suppose - of
 his institutions. And of course he - in that - they learnt - the boys the trade and they - when they become a certain age they send 'em out to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} and all like that they did. Emigrated 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think they were well treated there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - th
ey had no parents did they? And while they were in there they were fed and clothed. They wouldn't be if they was outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were the adequately clothed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, if they were in there, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did they wear a uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well they wouldn
't have a uniform but they'd have a - a substantial - suit on and they used to use a cloth years ago called Derby tweed. It was a - a - a pattern of cloth was very - sturdy made. Most of the children wore it or cord - cord trousers. Cord suits they'd have
.
 And - it's like in the workhouses, they all had cord suits, and Derby tweed suits. See, they were all in the - in the - mental hospitals they all had the same. Derby tweed, the inmates. You could always tell they was inmate of some institution, by that D
erby tweed they wore.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was it a cheap material?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, it was a good strong material. It was a working man's material, lasted. You bought a pair of Derby tweed trousers - I think the - when I was a young man, if you paid round about - seven and six, 
eight and six for a pair of trousers, they were good - solid trousers, made to made to measure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have any Doctor Barnardo children at your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. They had their own place there, Edinburgh Castel down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They'd go to their own school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, they had their own place in - in Stepney - Stepney Causeway was the headquarters. They're just recently pulling it down. And then they have a lot of - ex-policemen working for 'em, you see, when a policeman - finished up he got a job a
t Doctor Barndardo's, see they - it's was to all contributions coming in and - they're booking it in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would that be the right sort of person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well that was what they had, see, they had that sort of - to stop any villainry. See, they employed the
m, they gave 'em good after jobs you see, after they'd done their twenty-five years. See, years ago the police used to do twenty-five years. Now they do thirty. See - I knew a lot of - ex-policemen went to work at Doctor Barnardos - after they'd done thei
r - see, 'cos they've all got to work 'til they're sixty-five. See. The contributions, health and - insurance and contributions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they go as some sort of wardens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well clerks and all like that. All sorts of jobs they had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was it a big Barnardo's?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How many do you think would go there roughly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh, there was hundreds of people there. Whole lot worked there and a whole lot - and they had that big boot factory there in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bower Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, backed onto Stepney Causeway,
 see. It was a big concern. And they got their homes in different places now. And it's - run on a - on a business - scale you see, then they have these here - people paying regular - these - flag days what they have and all the income comes in, and then a
s people die and leave 'em money, and all like that, charities, peoples got feeling in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How did they manage for money in the early part of the century?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they - they done on voluntary contributions. From the rich you see or the people th
at could afford it. That was all that kept them going, it was the same as - Booth started here in Whitechapel. General Booth, he - they used to have their flag days, you know, that day - I forget the name of it - I know the name - they used to collect - a
n
nually you know, a day, they have a day - flag day like Queen Alexander's flag day. They collect all over the - country, these contributions See. Well all that money counted. And them - them Booths are all millionaires. They didn't start millionaires did 
they? See what I mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Can you remember having celebrations at school for any specific events like Queen Victoria's funeral, can you remember anything like that, if you had a day off, or the Relief of Making or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - yes, yes, yes, I remember that, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you remember anything about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes. Remember - that - there was anything like that you'd have a day off. The greatest - the best event of our - my life was always the - Lord Mayor's show day. 'Cos then it was
 run in the week. See, today it's run on a weekend, Saturday when the school's is closed. So we used to play truant that day. That's how we saw it - by playing truant if we wanted to see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What was the Lord Mayor's show like in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh 
it was wonderful. Yeh, it was all sorts of things we saw didn't you. You'd get in a certain place in the City and you stop there, 'til it's gone by you. And if you knew the City you could work your way back into the - side turnings and meet it coming back
. See the - it went right round the City, Aldersgate, Moorgate, all like that, see, up - Tower - Ludgate Hill and Tower Hill you know, that way, that's how it went. Up the main route. Circle of the City, round all the gates.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were any of the gates still there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well I - don't remember - I know most of the gates, there was Aldgate - Moorgate - Folgate, Cripplegate - Nortonfolgate. That's something dropped. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And the procession would go past all these gates?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes. It went r
ight round the City, finished up at the Guild Hall you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Anything else you think you can remember having a holiday for at the school, any special events? Like Empire day, did you have Empire Day off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. Don't remember anything for that, Empi
re Day, anything like that. We was - looked forward to that - summer holidays when I was a boy, when we went fruit picking or hop picking. Then we - had a holiday. Used to have a - nice few weeks holiday in the course of a year see. That's - that's why a 
l
ot of the poor people were backward in school, the time they had off. Some used to go - fruit picking, then they'd go - hop picking, that time they'd have - five or six weeks at a time hop picking. See, well now that's all done by mass machinery. We never
 had that you see. When - when one farm finished, they'd say - some farm up there got another week's work, do you want to go there, and they used to say yes. Then they'd take 'em down there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Six weeks is quite a lot for a child to have off isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, we had - we had - we had it didn't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you feel your schooling suffered through that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 We didn't - never thought of it. Never thought of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did the teachers ever make a thing about punctuality, was that important at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes. But most of us, we - you had a - a mark against you. You had a - a red mark, see, a late mark - if you was late in school you had a - a mark on the - on the register that you was late, a little stroke like that. They could tell whe
ther you was a - you - come in early or late.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I expect some children probably had things they had to do at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes. But every child had the same problems, those days, when I was a boy. Not like now. Nine out of ten people when I was a 
boy - or more than that. Ninety out of a hundred people never went to work the woman - of the house. I can honestly say when I married my wife, she never went to work in her life. And we were married nearly fifty years. She never went to work. I kept her.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think the man felt that was his role?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, I - I thought that. I thought that that was the - the woman in the house see. She did work for other people for nothing but not to get paid for it. She - she'd go and - help a woman in confinem
ent and do her shopping and her washing and her cleaning, and no pay, no idea of pay. Of course touch wood I was earning a - a - a fair living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Obviously some women had to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. Yes. But - everybody seems to go out to work today. That tim
e they didn't. Soon as a woman - got married, they'd say I'm not - they're not going to work no more. That was the idea of it. Especially if the husband had a good job. Look - look at some of these dockers here in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}East End{\*\xmlclose} there, earning fifty pound a week they are. Now on top of that their wifes earning - thirty pound. You realize the income some of 'em got coming in. It's - world's all haywire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 There weren't many jobs for women to do then were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No - no, you - you - you take - these po
rters in the building. They've got cars, a thousand pounds cars. When I was a young man the - the man in the five - five shilling bicycle, he was that big. He was comfortable. Now they've got thousand pound car. It's - a different trend today. It's all - 
all - all - all different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would teachers ever talk about the way of speaking, would they pick boys up about the way they spoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, they - they would check you - correct you you see if you - didn't do right. Swearing or anything like that th
ey - they didn't hold with it at that time you see. And then they were - more frightening and strict you see, they - say things to you that frightened you, you see if you - you was a - a ruffian as I call it, when I was a boy, you'd get sent to a - indust
rial school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You could be recommended to go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, yeh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 From your ordinary school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, and they wouldn't have you. They'd say, you've got to go to industrial school. And you were treated - harshly and everybody knew it, you was in an industrial school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 If you did something the teachers disapproved of how would they punish children?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Cane. Cane, they used to give us the - cane then. Had a long cane, and you had to hold your hands out, and they struck you on the - inside of the hand, or on the seat of your pants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would this happen for something very serious, would it be a serious offence?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - might not have been so serious but they - they used to give it to you if you done anything wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would any parents come up and complain about that in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No. Not as I knew of. They'd be ashamed to tell their parents. You see, because the type of boy that done something wilfull like to have been caned, wasn't a tender hearted boy. He was a ruffian -
 mostly. And if a boy done anything - ill treated an animal or anything like that - they was dead against anything like that you see when I was a boy. You was a - a animal. Then you'd get - not only treated wrong by the - school people you'd be treated wr
ong by all the boys in the class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there much bullying in your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - that's - that - that would - that's one of the things they'd punish you for. Wouldn't allow that. See? But you had to stand on your own two fee with bullying. See, i
f you was in the - anyone want to bully you - you was tender hearted, other boys wouldn't let 'em bully you. See, they wouldn't let anyone bully a - a - in a - what they call a - a quiet type of boy, but if you was a ruffian - and you wanted to have a fig
ht, well you had it. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did people ever fight in the playground?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes. Not in the playground but they - after school hours, they'd go somewhere in a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 side street}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  and have a fight, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But it wasn't allowed in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, not i
n - oh no, no, no. That's where you'd be punished in the school if you done it. You'd get the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your parents ever show any interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Not much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they ever come up to school to meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no,
 no, never, I don't ever remember that. When I was taken to school that time this school, I must have been about eight - and - that was the only time my mother took me, and after that I had to go backwards and forwards to school - on me own. And now I see
 
little children round here, their parents take them in a car to school, and they're not two ticks away. And - there's one child here, he's taken to school by a car, and brought back. I - in a pram, a boy about six. Cor, fancy my mother wheeling us in a pr
a
m. Never had a pram for a start. We used to have a soap box or a bag sugar box, buy for about threepence that and put a couple of wheels on it. We was - we had a Rolls Royce didn't we for threepence. Yes, yes, we had a little - yeh, that was our - our mot
or car. Go all the way to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 Leadenhall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 market, bring home - a bag of - fish heads or giblets - for the - weekend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So women would carry babies about then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, they carried 'em, yes. Well they did, they carried it - always had a baby on in -
 in a shawl. Carried the babies. On their arm or over their shoulder like that. Couldn't - no pram, they was rich people that had a little pram. If they're comfortable they got a pram. You see, in - that's how it went like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think most of the ch
ildren at your school came from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no, no, they - they were more - different - breed weren't they. You see that time, years ago - a teacher, his parents were - what they call the middle class you see. Middle cl
ass - children of middle class people. They weren't - children of - poor people. Now any child can go to - be a teacher. And - don't matter what class he's in. You see - they never had the opportunities that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there quite a lot of middle class children over at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh they were there, yes, they was - I'm telling, there was a lot of - lot of - in the areas was all business people, their children, police - police children, children of policemen. See, that was more or less a - a bit
 of a select school when I was a boy, Dempsey Street. You see. It wasn't a - poor school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
If there were any poor children would the teachers treat them any differently than these other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, they wouldn't treat them but they - they - be 
kind to you, but they wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Not the other way round?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no, no. They wasn't - anything against you for that. Well they couldn't help it could they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were there any gangs or groups in the school amongst the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, there 
would be, there would be - they - they'd be - boys that line up and want to quarrel with the Jewish children in another school see, the Christians against the jews, they was - Ashfield Street school - there, they call it - it's Ashfield Street now, it was
 
a different school, I'll think of it in a minute. They - they used to say, lets come and have a war with the - jews, see, that's what they said - years ago. They'd be either in Stepney Green - well of course they weren't all like that, it was only the - w
hat I call the - the lower type of boys as I call 'em, the board boys. And that was only done from ignorance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they go off and do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
They'd throw stones at one another and all like that and - belts and - hit one another if they could. Som
etimes you was walking along, you'd get a - a - someone - run up the side and give you a clout - and then run away see. And be three or four or them together you see. Give you a clout. I remember - me and a brother of mine, we was pushing a - a little mot
or what we'd made with four - pram wheels - and was - sugar box, and one boy said - where's {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Garden Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
? And my brother turned round and looked across, over there, he said. And this boy hit him straight in the eye. And he had a lovely black eye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why did he do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
'Cos he was a Christian and the other - he was a Jewish boy see. I suppose someone had hit him and - he hit them. Poor old Sid was holding the string driving the - little - what we called the motors that time you see, four wheel
ed carts, running our motor along, he got a lovely black eye. 'Course then after that - it was red rag to a bull, he - every Jewish boy he see he wanted to give them one, and he did. There was no stopping him, he was - he was a - he was a year older than 
m
e. He was a little tough fellow. He was a - he finished up - a full Corporal in the Royal Fusiliers, Sid. And he finished up - he done seven years, he joined the Army for - what was it they used to join - oh, six months on the specials - they used to call
 it, six months, and then they used to do about three years on and off - five years on the reserve, used to get a - couple of coppers a week that time. Didn't get much
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Were any of your brothers as resourceful as you were about making money when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, yes. Oh yes. I had a - a younger brother, he - he was a - sold rabbits, wild rabbits. Greengrocery. He started off with greengrocery. Oh he was a - business - idea. I - I remember him - we was going hop picking, and - he caught 
a little rabbit. You know, they're not very - a baby rabbit. He skinned it, and he washed it, and he boiled it in a beer can what you bought at that time a pot of ale, fourpence it used to be, a quart, quart beer cans they were, and - the publicans used t
o have their name - marked on the side of these tin cans. And - he boiled that with some vegetables, and he made himself a little - stew. You know how old he was? About -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was it more difficult for girls to get these odd jobs while they were at school 
to earn money, were your sisters ever able to do anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - girls - girls didn't have many opportunities to - get jobs, they got jobs as - perhaps mind a baby for somebody, or something like that. Or - girls were looked after different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You mean your mother wouldn't let your sisters go off like you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, they - but I tell you what the girls did in the East End - a lot of girls'd be - the Jewish people'd get 'em to go in - tidy up their homes for 'em, you know what I mean, help 'em 
that way, in the house. For a few coppers a week. They didn't get much of it. 'Course every - everybody got a - and then it wasn't easy to get a job then. Less the shopkeeper knew you. See, when I was a boy, shopkeeper would say - help 'em with a milkroun
d - a - dairyman, something like that. Or a catsmeat man, he'd ask you to go - help him, go round delivering the cats meat. 'Cos everybody had cats that time, now you - nobody's got cats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But girls wouldn't do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, not the - no, very - very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would your sisters be allowed to go out round the City and stay out late?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no, never. No. Oh no, never. If we took them up see - say the Leadenhall Market in the summertime - 'cos the shops used to be open late that time -
 we'd take 'em home before daylight - or - darkness. We wouldn't take 'em in wintertime, 'course there was some variations but - was - they wouldn't be allowed out, my sisters. 'Course you see, years ago - people had more - feeling towards a child, they w
ouldn't allow no one to take advantage of a child. They'd soon stop 'em, like I - I would meself you see - now. Yes - children were respected more I think then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think girls were protected by their families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, oh you dare no
t interfere with a girl years ago, you'd have all the family after you. And they'd give you what for. You wouldn't want to do it again, you see, the - it was - it was the natural upbringing of you. You know I saw a boy doing something once to a girl - and
 
I was a walking along, and somebody reported me - like to me that this boy was - a little devil. And - they said, well when your sister goes back to work, you look out your door and watch what happens. Well - he - I mean, he lives say - next door this boy
,
 that's right. And - he had three sisters and two brothers. And my sister went back to work say about quarter to two, in the dinner hour, he stood at the door, and he had a stick in his hand like that. Now as my sister went by he walked behind her, and ju
st raised her skirt with the stick. And of course - that encouraged me to treat him. And I raised my foot into the seat of his pants. And I can assure he never done anything like that again. I lifted him right off the ground.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Brothers would be quite protective towards sisters would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, well I lifted him off the ground, and then I knocked at his door and I told his parents. I said, if ever your son - stands at that door when my sister goes back from work - I'll put a hammer on his head.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was your sister conscious that this had happened or didn't she know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. She didn't say nothing, she was a church girl see. She - was a girl opposite what told me. See, she - she wasn't a brave girl see, she - she went always to church every 
- more or less every night she was there. And - anyhow - he always remember me, that - that boy. He became a barber - he was a barber the last time I saw him. Oh yes, I - I gave him the - curing - treat for that, I just lifted his - seat of his trousers, 
h
e must have been about fourteen then. I didn't stand for that. Of course, they knew what I'd do if they - I cut up rough, but - that's what I cured him - of doing to that - girl. And it see not only cured him for my sister, it cured for anybody's. Because
 he'd learned his lesson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Would you say any children were left out of things in the playground, do you remember any children who just stood about, were left out for any reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh not necessary, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You were all pretty friendly towards each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, you knew - you knew one another. You see, you was all - you see if you - mostly - some people are what they call meek, some children, and some are rough. See, we was brought up tough. To rough it you see, I mean, we never knew what hardsh
ip was in that way. We went without food we never complained. But some children - I went to school with boys as I'm telling you, their fathers was police inspectors, the head man of this district, Inspector Wensley. I went to school with his two sons. Wel
l
 one was a lot younger but the older one, Fred - he got killed in the '14 warm most - all - all - all my schoolmates were - were more or less - cut down in the '14 war. Everywhere you remember was - say where's so and so. He's gone off. That was what happ
e
ned. In the '14 war cleared away everybody. Little children - you know, kids that went away. Honest - never done harm to anybody. They were mown down in the '14 war. That wasn't a war, that was a - a - a murder. You take for instance - all those places li
ke the Dardanelles and the Somme - on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somme{\*\xmlclose}
 they was absolutely slaughtered. Well, there was five of us brothers we was all soldiers - during the '14 war. And - some mothers had worse than that. I knew families - all gone you know, all disappeared.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
How would families around here react to their sons going to war, did people regard them as heroes at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - oh well, they - they - their - everybody - it was natural wasn't it? If the man wasn't in the war he - they used to shout after h
im. Yellow belly and all that see. White feather, that was the - fashion then, put a white feather in their coat. I remember a boy - he was wounded in the war, and he had a - a blue uniform and he had it at home, took it off and stood on the street corner
,
 and a woman put a white feather on him. And that boy was wounded in the war. But what I was coming to is this. That woman's husband got killed. After, that boy was proper wounded, and he stood there with ordinary clothes on. But that woman - she - she pu
t that white feather him and says to him - some - low disparaging remark you see, about not being a soldier. Her own husband got killed. I thought to myself, well that's retaliated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 As the war dragged on and on and more and more men were disappearing a
nd never coming back from the front, do you think people's morale began to sink a little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Oh yes, everybody lost somebody more or less. Cor I know some whole families was wiped out wasn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever go on to any other school after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. That - that school - I left that school - when I was - four - fourteen as you say, and when I was about fifteen to sixteen I learnt to be a - I - I got a - I was working in the City }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 selling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  odds and ends and - then I got recomme
nded to go up to that place in Clerkenwell, and - in - learn to be a shoemaker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 About fifteen. Just - fifteen to sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you have stayed at school any longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no. You was anxious to go out in the world earn some didn't you.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever do any part time education afterwards?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Any evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Looking back do you think you've got any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You think you benefitted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. Yes, I learnt in school what I had to learn, and then - you learn yourself then. It comes automatically everything to me. You see, I learnt my trade, and I worked with a lot of the foreign element Jews, and - I learn
t more or less to speak a bit of Yiddish - from it, 'course they never spoke English to you, if they wanted anything they required they called out in Yiddish to you. So - I used to say, what does that mean, what does that mean? And - ninety percent of the
 words I asked for - I never forgot. They told me - bread was broitz, and - that's like - when I was a - working as a kind as a - in a Welsh place, the Welsh dairy, they used to speak Welsh to you and say with the Welsh words.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That milk round you were on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that Welsh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, the Welshman was the milk round, yes. They'd speak Welsh words to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that your very first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes. As a - a - a - yes. Helping in the milk - dairy, yes. Used to get up very early then, four o'clock. Four o'clock in the mornings to wash the cans and that. Get ready for the first round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What would you earn for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Couple of bob a week, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Ten, twelve, that was - fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Could you tell us about the newspapers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How old would you be when you started that? Would you still be at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, oh yes. Sell the - sell the newspapers after you left school, and went up in the City - that was a sideline.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go straight from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well up - up the City. 'Cos if you had as a start a number - a quire of papers you see, they was ha'penny each papers, three - three a - three a pe
nny you paid. Not - not - nine - I think it was ninepence a quire and it was nine three's is twenty-seven, twenty-seven copies in the quire, and you - you paid - ninepence see for that and you got back - them - them more ha'pennies you see, you - every th
ree you sold you had a ha'penny profit. And if someone give you a penny for a paper it was - which - happened you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Which paper would you sell?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Star - Evening News, that was the - most sold that time, it was the Evening News and the Star. They
 were ha'penny papers. The Standard, they were penny papers like. Evening Standard or the - the - the Daily Mirror was a ha'penny paper and all when I was a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Why was the Standard a penny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well posh - posh - posh paper. That was the posh paper, the Standard. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would the Star and Evening News come from the same newspaper office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no. Two different offices up -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So what would you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Go for either one to the other, which you wanted to sell. The Star or the Even
ing News see. This - this - they were ha'penny papers. Oh yes, used to get ha'penny profit on every three you sold. See, 'cos that - you was the run boys, run through picking up customers, but these people had their regular stands, they - stopped on 'em y
ou see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you used to call out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 The headlines, that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, we did, yeh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you usually get rid of most of your papers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, we didn't buy - overloaded with lots, unless - and then - then these ne
wspaper men on these stands - after sold their - main lot they'd say - stand here and sell these for us. You say - near Fenchurch Street the man had a big stand there - on the corner, he'd say - stand here and sell them - he'd give you the profits every t
h
ree you sold you had a ha'penny profit see. On his stand. Well we didn't mind that, that would start us off. There was lots of stands in the City. After their main trade had gone, so they was satisfied. Or perhaps it might be a dirty wet day, they'd say, 
here you are, stand there and - and get wet for a ha'penny for a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you go on doing that for a little while after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Before you did your music thing in the churches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh that was - that was when I started - that was when I first proper job, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But you never did papers full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, done it when we wanted to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would it never have been worth your while to do it as a full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 To sell papers, like morning papers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh if I'd had stood - stuck by it - did a - have got this. Plenty of opportunities in the City to - sell - things. The chief thing is was having to stock money to buy the stock with. See? If you went - say you wanted buy something in Houndsditch, i
f you had a few shillings, what they call stock money, you was lords. See, instead of buying a small quantity and then run back and - and increasing each time - which we have done - that was how it is. The more money you had to buy the stock with, if you 
could buy a gross of picture postcards, for instance, instead of buying - two or three dozen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And they'd take some of the newspapers back you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, they'd took one back, when you bought fresh - supplies, one in every three you were allow
ed to change. What they call returns see. Bumps. Then if we picked up any spare papers and they was clean and tidy, we put them in as well see and got them exchanged.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you do this with another boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, we mostly worked on our own paper boys
 did. Each boy had - run himself - if I run up to Fleet Street - for a quire of papers, the quicker I got - sold 'em out the quicker I earnt that there - fourpence ha'penny didn't I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How did you get to Fleet Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Walk. Walk right up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How long would that take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - get on the back of a cart or a bus or anything for anywhere - that time you wasn't afraid to get on the back of a van, or a bus or jump off, because the traffic was only horse traffic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So that's how you'd often get up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, get up there on the back of a - another vehicle, if you fancied to. And those paper vans used to run along as well, carts, they used to travel pretty quickly. And get on behind a cab, the back of a old four wheel cab. Get on 
the back anywhere. Threw his - his whip over at you, and - stung your ears.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Then you'd get off again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Mm. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When you started a full time job, your job with the organist, did you continue to live at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Until you went into the Army you were still living at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you now contributing more to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, that wa
s different you see, when - when - when I - when I learnt my trade - she went - when I - came out of the services I - I passed in the services as a - Army shoemaker. And I was - given a discharge as a satisfactory shoemaker. You see - and I was used to Ar
m
y boots you see, they were heavy boots that time, and - I become what they call a bit of a expert - in repairing 'em. 'Cos they got - used to have them big scotch tips on the heels, like they do on the horses. And - it was practice for me you see. But whe
n I come home out form the services - I started more or less working for myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When you first started when you left school, even your first job, were you able to give your mother more when you went as a full time job with the organist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, 
yes, well - yes, yes, she - she had - she seen - when I got the pay from the organist of a night, I used to get I think two shillings a day that time - about five nights a week. Well I had ten shillings stock money didn't I? See, well - I could use that a
nd earn a few more shillings after I done with the organist, on Saturday and Sunday, all like that, we wasn't fussy any days we went to work. It was all to earn money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did you elder brothers treat you any differently once you were in a full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Because you'd always contributed anyway hadn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. I had a - household pets in the garden you know like the - pigeons was our favourite. Pigeons was nearly
 everybodys favourite. And chickens, anything like that, rabbits, wild - not wild rabbits, tame rabbits. And we - we used - that - had some lovely pets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did you stop going to church or Sunday school once you were fourteen and left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, 
naturally - that - that - that - I - after I left school they didn't get much church out of me, I - retired from that. You see, the boys - most boys - joined the - what do you call it, the Boys Brigade, then from there they went into the Scouts, and then 
- they went other - activities. 'Course later life came along - bioscope came along, and pictures, that interest the boys on a Saturday and Sunday more than anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go to the pictures on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, Sunday and the Saturday, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That wasn't frowned upon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, no, no. You - there was - hundreds of little places where you could go for a penny or ha'penny, see - pictures.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you interested in politics once you were about eighteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. Never. Never interested me, politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever vote before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The - I'd vote, but I - were never interest - I never interested myself in politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You never joined a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Or helped out at elections?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did you do anything different with your spare time, on Sundays you said you had pets and things, what about evenings once you were at work, cinemas things like that I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, sometimes you would go. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 Up}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  a show. You see, 'cos the - thea
tres when I was a young man was - wasn't very dear. You could go in for threepence - the music hall here, local music hall, it was only threepence to go in. In the gallery. And was fourpence in the pit, and some places was tuppence. In the - in the - in t
he - music halls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever go into central {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose} while you were a young man, did you ever go in to any theatres in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Central London{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No. Not much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did people on the whole who lived in this area, they didn't go up to the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West End{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No
, they went up the West - up the - West, yes, they went up the West End music halls - Up to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13831914\charrsid66970 Alhambra}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  or up there - up in - that's - that was a - outing wasn't it, to go up there, they - told people, oh I've been in Lyons's Corner House up - Hyde Park there. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Trafalgar Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and all that area. See. Hyde Park was their favourite - right to a place called the Corner House they called it, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Lyons{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s Corner House.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that regarded as quite a long way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well it wasn't a long way but it was - it was o
nly two or three coppers to ride up there. The people didn't like wasting a lot of money years ago. 'Course - you see, you could ride - about a mile and a half for a penny, easy. On the buses years ago when I was a boy. Mile and a half to - I've been - tw
o mile. Two mile for a penny. Up from Aldgate to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Burdett Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, two mile. A penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you ever go out into the country once you were a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you go out for days into the country at all or to the seaside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh you would 
- yeh, go out - Croydon way, Epsom or any way like that, if you had a few coppers extra you wanted to spend. Used to go over Blackheath there - Bank Holidays and that, different areas had you - different ideas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there anything special at Blackheath on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No, it was - just a - a country park more or less, know what I mean. You went there, it was a change from being round where it was all houses. You see, that bit of grass what's growing out the back there, we never knew that did we.
 We never knew about grass. If I want - I had - birds, say I had a linnet - or a bird or any bird I wanted to get a - bit of - groundsell or - dandelion for, I'd have to go all the way to Victoria Park to get it. You wouldn't see no growing here, no one w
o
uldn't allow a weed to grow in their - front door like you see now, you go along - the front street now you see - all these growing in your local park and - all along the edges. You didn't see that when I was a boy. A gardener wouldn't have it. And he wou
ldn't allow it to grow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So caged birds were popular were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, oh the cage - everybody had caged birds. Linnets and - chaffinches. Well you could buy one for - a - for - threepence or fourpence, in Club Row or in Mile End Road of a Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 These are really wild birds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, they were real - wild birds and you tamed 'em yourself - you tamed - keep 'em yourself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Didn't you think that was rather cruel, you didn't feel that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well I - I had a chaffinch for years, he - he - 
I don't think he was - he was - the only cruelty was he was caged up. He must have been healthy else he wouldn't have sung like he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do chaffinches sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, chaffinches got a lovely song. I thought anyhow. A chaffinch - they finish up wi
th a song - on the letter. Chuck me out the window, like that. They go - ch -ch-ch-ch-ch - chuck me out the window, but linnets got a nice sweet song as well. And then we used - then I crossed - I - I - bred canaries, and I crossed them with the linnet, l
innet mules.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Can you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, linnet - we - I knew all the crosses, we had - goldfinch mules, greenfinch mules. Linnet mules, bullfinch mules. The bullfinch mules didn't sing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What are these crossed with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 A canary. Get a canary an
d - you could buy a canary then for about sixpence, seven - eightpence down Club Row. Shilling - always get - what they call - a little - I had a little green hen and - she - prolific, she laid any - any eggs what you put - mated with her. Once you get 'e
m to mate you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I thought it was quite hard to get caged birds to mate, is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. Oh no. We - yes, we used to buy - little cages and put 'em in, and when - the hens - called they - they mated. And if they had eggs and they fertilised the egg,
 once the - some mules can't - won't cross. But the - they used to lay - lay some - pretty - mules those goldfinches. 'Course the greenfinches are similar to the canary, they're all - one colour. But the linnets and the - they lay a sparrow coloured egg. 
The linnets see, they - like they got a - sparrow colour haven't they. But they've got a lovely song. I - my - I had a aunt of mine had a linnet over twenty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When did they start going out, birds like chaffinches and linnets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - about th
e - after the '14 war - after the '14 war - law come in, stopped it. After the '14 war they passed these here - wild bird protection act. So everybody - stopped it. They used to - you could catch 'em easy as anything, like I told you - that time we used t
o
 catch the - pheasants with the horsehair and the maize. We used to catch the - you know - a chaffinch say for instance, say wanted to catch chaffinches. Get a chaffinch, cover the cage up with a - with a - handerkerchief see, he's in the darkness and mor
e
 the darkness the more they sang. And then get out in the - in a field where the chaffinches were or near a wood - and we used to have little twigs stuck into bird lime. It's like a glue. Then you put 'em beside of a dummy bird. You had a dummy chaffinch 
a
nd you stand him up there, and of course their natural instinct is, this is my property, and you've got to be cleared off. So when one chaffinch sings - the other wants to come down to it. And he come down to where this stuffed one was to have a fight wit
h
 him, and he'd get caught. See they used to get the stuffed one, and stick it there. And they'd have one hid in a - handkerchief so they couldn't see it. And they - he'd sing away he would, a - a singing chaffinch. And we'd have these little porcupine qui
l
ls that's what they were, about like little knitting needles, and you stick the tip in the - in these little slots all round this here - bird and the others come and got caught, of course once they got their feet on it they couldn't get off. You just pick
ed 'em up put 'em in the cage and wiped their feet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 From that moment they were caged birds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. But that's how most of them got caught. With the quills.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You said you had pigeons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were they racing pigeons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, well some of 'em. Some were fancy pigeons, some were racing pigeons.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You just let them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Let 'em out and they come back to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you go to let them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh you - you - well - if you let 'em out where you live they fly round 
the area. But if you wanted to take 'em somewhere - take 'em a few mile away and release 'em and they come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They always come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Mostly they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You were saying they used to show films and things at the pubs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Pubs. There was a - here in Stepney Green here was a pub called the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 Mulberry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
 Tree. And then they - they - up in the clubroom of the pub see they opened it as a little picture place. Pay a penny to go in - that time. And then - then - then further down here in Stepney Way 
here, was the Green Dragon, a - another little - was an old music hall what they had in them pubs, you know, they used to have benefits for - keep the clubroom see, like it's a little music hall - of Saturday night mostly it was. And that. Make these leag
u
es as they call them. Yeh, but the pictures they showed in them was little - 'cos they had a big clubroom you see and - they fixed up their bioscope there and - 'til the - what they call - I reckon - that time - the - when the - the depression came along.
 
When the pictures started them bioscope that was when - these here little - picture palaces opened everywhere, some were a ha' - as much as a ha'penny in Commercial Road here was one, they called it - Silverland, you could go in for a ha'penny children se
e, or anybody. And then they - they - you see the performance then they had a - then they'd have a fresh - send them out then there - there'd be fresh people come in. And that went on all - oh - a long long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of clubs were these, what would they hold in the club room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Above the pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh in the pub was - they - they'd have their own club, they'd have a - perhaps a mon - a money club you know, have - pay in - Monday night - say Christmas club, they'd hold them clubs. 
They used to hold all - all sorts of - and then they used to have dart clubs and all - all - everything went in you see. In some places they had a - bagatelle clubs, where the men played bagatelle. And others played darts. 'Course darts was a - a thing wh
a
t came on. See, I remember a pub here in - Redmonds Road when the darts - there'd be an advertisement in the Sporting Life - similar to this. At a well known East End pub there will be a dart match on so and so night, you see, well that was a little pub j
u
st here, bottom of Jamaica Street, bottom - there. And - there used to be money matches you see, they used to play for money, different - a dart match see. And there was all these here boys, they'd back on - on the diff - different players you see. Some o
f 'em was crack players you see. And - they'd put their - that little advert in the - paper about - regarding that, and you see the - cabs come, four wheelers that time. See I'm going back a bit. And - that's what used to happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 People used to come in from outside the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, outside when they get the wire, there's a dart match coming off over at - down the Anchor - Anchor and Oak the name of the pub was. And they used to play in there. Oh it was a - a lot of that gambling went on that time, o
n different people. And some of the - boys was experts you know, dart throwers. Yeh, but the pictures what they showed was real - and really a lot of places took advantage of that. It was a get - you know, get money - in. 'Cos after all, when you reckon i
t
 out - that time a glass of beer was only a penny. See, if you had a penny - you could - or - you had threepence you could go and have bread and cheese and - and beer for - and then a ha' - perhaps a hapenny 'cos bread and cheese was only threeha'pence, i
t was a penny the cheese and ha'penny the bread they charged mostly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 If you went to the cinema who would you go with? When you were boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well with a - a friend - a friend. Oh a friend or - friend you know, you got a lot of boys, the local boys always. We used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did you make different friends once you'd gone to work than when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, you did get involved with different people don't you, different - some boys is - come from a different - household to what you are. 
They're better off than what you are, when you're young. See, but - when I was - a boy you see - there was lots of - what I call - nice families you know, the children was - dressed different to what I was see, 'cos I was from - poor people. See. We never
 
knew about collars and ties when I was a child. Just a - a shirt you see. You could buy a collar - you could buy a ha'penny collar made of paper. Ha'penny paper collar. And then there was - little white collar - people used to buy 'em, and they was only a
 
ha'penny, and you put 'em on, they lasted the day, you know, what I mean, 'course if you was careful they lasted longer. And then they had a - then they had another collar there, we used to - poor people - well most people had it, they were made of cellul
o
id. You only had to have a little bit of - wet cloth and you wiped 'em, but the - they had a habit of going yellowish round the - neck see, but they was - they lasted a long time, them white - collars, 'cos they was cheaper than buying the ha'penny paper 
collars see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would you dress up to go out in the evening, once you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 scarves}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  was the fashion that time, silk scarves you see. You had a silk scarf - or - or a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 woollen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  scarf that time. See, that was the average - head - neck dre
ss of the - people. 'Course when they put a - a collar on, I had a brother next to me, he always had a - wore a collar, he used to - go to work with a collar and tie. He - he was a carman. And he - and - they all knew him, see, he had a collar and tie on.
 
'Cos the average - was - they made a - average driver on the road always had a silk scarf round his neck - tied in a square bow see they used to - make it like a lit - you make - simple way of making it, you make a bow, and they threadled it round their b
races to keep it - centre. Yeh, that was the average neck dress. Unless they had a gurnsey on you know, or a jersey. See they didn't want that on then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about Sundays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Sundays was the - no different, no difference, there - there wasn't no di
fference. See -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
When did people start do you think to wear collars and ties as a normal form of dress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - as - as - they get - got on in - financially. You see. The average - shirts never had collars attached to 'em. Then they brought in the
 attached collars - shirts, well then they - were - different. You see - the average working man's shirt used to charge from - half a crown to three and six they'd last you - two or three years easy, them shirts would. And they was washed you see, then - 
t
hen they only had - no collar on 'em, just the - shirt for a stud, you put a collar on 'em there was a stud hole at the back, put the back stud in. That was for stiff collars that time, well then when the soft collars came into vogue, you - people used to
 
use them. Put them on. Oh yes, it was - they were - different prices though wasn't it, ay. Three and - three and - three and six - a good - good class mans shirt it was, last you easy two or three years. Half a crown some - a - a cap you could get from si
xpence ha'penny. A man's cap - a shilling, if you paid a shilling you had a posh cap. That - would cost you about thirty bob today, them caps. They're not made like they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about women's clothing, did they make them different, you say a man who
 was better off wore a collar and tie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well the women, they had a nice hat, they wore a hat didn't they. Yeh. 'Course thousands of women wore caps - mens caps. Like you see the men wearing here today, you see, the women used to wear them. Mens caps, 
the poor people. They had a cap on their head. Or - a - a - anybody had a hat with feather and that in they used to put feathers in. Used to be a lot of - people - what they call - feather curlers, they used to - curl those - feathers you see, and they st
u
ck 'em in the hat. Well they took 'em out of one hat and stick 'em in the other wouldn't they. Stick 'em up the side of a straw hat for instance. Straw hats was a - a posh man - East Ender. If he had a straw hat, oh he - he's well off. Bowler hat - straw 
h
ats and bowler hats see. The butchers used to all wear straw hats mostly. If you saw a - went to a butchers shop you'd generally see him with a straw hat on. Well like a lot of tradesmen - wore 'em, with a collar and tie you see, but - not - not so partic
ular today are they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of hat would a tradesman wear when he was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, if he was a - a tradesman he'd be a respected person wouldn't he. He'd be - have a little - a - few steps above the other others you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you allowed to
 bring your friends home to meet your parents? Did they encourage you to do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they never said - they never argued with us. Because our friend - my friends as I was a young man - see I was interested in animals, like pigeons. Any animal, don
't matter what it was, and the - and your friends was the same, you mixed with one another. The - everywhere you went was pigeon fanciers round this district, hundreds and hundreds. I - had a pair of gold - don't see many of 'em now - these was - a - a va
r
iety of pigeon called a dipper, they look - fly for hours and hours without coming down, you know, once you release 'em, you feed 'em, and they fly - oh - a long - hours, very long hours, and - I had a pair of these lovely bronze coloured - they're bronze
 
they were, and you look at 'em it looks like they're bronze. These - North of England Tiplers, and I couldn't breed with 'em, they didn't breed, you know what I mean, they - they laid the eggs but - they were unfertile always. They must have been in bred 
-
 pair. Well anyhow, a man wanted to buy 'em of of me. And - he was a baker. And he lived in this very street, Exmouth Street it was called then. Just across Stepney Way was a pub there, there was a well known pub it - they used to play - it was a skittle 
a
lley, they used to play skittles out in the back, and - I - heard this man wanted these two Tiplers so I took 'em to him. So - I said, I hear you want to buy my - two Tiplers. He said, yes, he says - I'll buy 'em. Well I says, how much are you willing to 
g
ive me for 'em? He said - one and six. Straight out. That's ninepence each see. So - ninepence each. I showed 'em to him, I said, look would you give ninepence each for them would you? So he says, yes. So I undone this here little basket, and I let 'em fl
y
. I said, now look, you catch 'em you can have 'em for nothing. Yeh, I said, you catch 'em you'll have 'em for nothing. They - you know when they come down, perhaps about eight or nine hours afterwards. 'Course they don't go to nowhere else, only where th
ey live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So most of your friends were pigeon fanciers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, that time, yes, you mixed - same as if you're - you're a boxer, you mix with boxers you see. And - you got all friends - wherever you go they know - you know one another. And y
ou've got hundreds of friends you see. It's the same thing with that. See. The same - well mostly in tradesmen, every tradesman knows his own - you meet one another in the merchants, like I was a shoemaker, I used to be in the grinding shops up Whitechape
l
, there was a - a - as far as I'm - remember, everywhere you went people sold in the East End, all round the East End was - scores and scores of leather merchants. There's not one there now. Not one. In Whitechapel alone - in Whitechapel Road, just there 
b
y Whitechapel station - was two - two - opposite Whitechapel station was one, it's a dairy now, next to the post office, that dairy was the leather merchants, Andrews, and then - further up was another - big firm. Clog makers and - boot manufacturers they
 were. And leather merchants. Along Whitechapel Road - in the back turnings was numerous leather merchants you knew. Oh - established businesses, now it's all gone. No more. Don't know - what's happened to our grade, it's gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Where would you go to meet girl friends at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - if you - went to - you saw - passed one another up the main road or if you went to the pictures - or to the Paragon in Mile End or - Foresters in Cambridge Road, that was the local theatres. And - and then - then
 you meet a girl - mostly at entertainment, the only entertainment girls got was in pubs wasn't it, or men. Men - it was the natural thing to go to pubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would girls go by themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh no, no, no, they - wouldn't go - girls wouldn't go in pubs
 on their own. Unless they was low class. See, that type, the - the - be in - in the different - places, well - you could see them a mile off, them, by the way they - painted up their faces and - decorated theirself mostly those women. They - they wanted 
to be gaudy you see and dressed according.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about dance halls, were there dance halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh - oh yes, there was plenty of dance halls here in the East End. Numerous dance halls. There - of course that was the meeting place for boys and girls as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Girls could go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, girls, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 By themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, girls could go there and - wait for - partner, it was here in - just here - faced the bottom of this street, Jamaica Street, was two dance halls. Brandons and - an
d a hall - right next to the school was another one. You see a - dozens and dozens - of taxis and cabs out there - to take people home you see, but - there's none of that hardly now dance halls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How much did it cost to get into a dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 About sixpence. If it was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That would be quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, sixpence - paid that - of course posh places they charge - might charge a shilling. Then - there was numerous halls everywhere you went in the East End - was dance halls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You had to dress up to go to a dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they did - wouldn't let a - a ruffians in, you know what I mean. But - they - as - ruffians don't - they don't worry about dress today, ruffians, you can't tell a - a - a - a decent person from a - another one,
 by dress, to look at people with dress - you see some of these - hippies whats a running about today. Some of 'em are very clever - people, and yet they'll let theirself go what I call - frwosy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would there be groups of boys at that time who'd go around in gangs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes, yes, elements - ay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Annoying people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, that was all - that'll all - never stop that. Boys'll always be - like the football boys. See all them boys that go to football matches today - they go there - and they - 
supporters as they call their self, and they become active, and then they start - getting - spiteful to one another. The same thing - that's been all over the world that. Followers you see. It don't matter your sport is you'll always find the fanatics fol
lowing see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of sport would they follow in those days, gangs of boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, when I was a boy - you went to boxing halls mostly. We did, that was our main - sport. Go and see a - a football matches as used - like they have even today. Use
d to have boxing matches and football matches, then - then you met your match if you went there. If you wanted to be tough there'd be tough boys there wouldn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You'd get into fights with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yeh, you could - and - you'd have to get ou
t of it, but - that - that business has been going on now ever since - Eve and Adam. You see, there's always been - active sort of people. See, in - in - used to go to the theatre or the music hall, if it didn't - a - agree with the public, so they blew '
e
m out raspberries, you know what I mean. I've seen - well known people when I was young get - the bird as they called it. Yes, we had a - we had a - somebody, one of the boys, brought a big box of these raspberrie kinds that had gone sweaty. They're - the
y
're like a little - jelly and they got - coconut cut up, put on in that - they called them raspberry kinds, well these went sweaty, and - they - took a box up into the Paragon and - they threw 'em all over the stage and onto the band, they were - the band
 
was playing, these things, and once they hit anything they stuck like a - and mess. That - that's true that is. All over the place they threw that - seven pound box - of - of - these - a boy got 'em form a sweetstuff shop. He got - whoever it was got glad
 to get rid of 'em see, and he - he brought 'em up there. We'll have a - a lark tonight. And threw - they - they all had handfuls you know and - threw 'em from the gallery, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would this gangs of boys be quite frightened of the police?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well yo
u were frightened of the police, because that time - when I was a boy you see - if you was to - be - spiteful or - cut up rough, they used to draw their stick and - club you. They wasn't afraid to club you then. They did that. They knocked - knocked - hel
l out of a - these tough boys, with the stick because they were afraid of - that's what made 'em all afraid, they got a crack on the head. Oh that was - nasty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you ever see any policeman actua}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 lly do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yeh, oh yes. I saw here - a - a 
man - every time he saw a policeman and it was like a red - rag to a bull, he would want to go and insult him. Well, he - went up to this young policeman and - he was going to have a fight with him, see. And before you could look round the policeman got h
i
m on the floor. Bang, bang, bang. He was a - champion boxer of police. And - this fellow, he - he - oh I never forget his face, was cut from here - here right down here. But he clobbered him. He cured him of being a tough boy against policemen. That was t
h
em terrors. Oh they had to look after theirself the police did years ago, 'cos they - they were knock - kicked and knocked about - by the drunkards you see. And some of them chaps was real tough boys, them policemen. Not like they are today, they're not t
o
ugh, they're only little frail boys, these was - some of them - weighed seventeen and eighteen stone and - and - was - athletes as well as being policemen. Oh I've seen some wonderful athletes here in the East End here. With - the boys. Used to - boxing b
o
ys and that I used to go with. In fact, that - that club up there - well that night school was the only club around here - with - where they had a - athletic club. Was a - and then the police had a - their own athletic club, and then they used to come to 
- up there to the LCC and like - and do training up there, see. And when you belonged to that - them athletic clubs - you - there was naturally a lot at that time it was the only place a gymnasium what you could use.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your parents always want to kno
w where you were when you were a young man, when you were about sixteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. No, never. There was only interested in - my mum, as long as you bought her wages in. That was the only interest I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did you have to tell her where you were going at nights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, never. No. Not - not as a rule.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh, they were different, they - girls was indoors wasn't they. They don't go out, if they - went to church - them girls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But they couldn't go out by themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
No. But then - far as I remember, them girls - they all were dressmakers, like - three of 'em, and - they all had their jobs during the week to help mum when they grew up. One done the washing, regular. One done the front room and the - and upstairs and t
he bedrooms, another one done the stairs, and Lord knows what, they all had their regular jobs and they kept that on 'til they got married theirselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did you ever take your sisters out, would you take them out to the pictures or the theatre or music hall or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well - if they'd have wanted to go I - I suppose we would have taken 'em. See we I we had a - a - two variety places here, one was the - Mile End Empire, opposite Stepney Green. And then there was the Forresters Music Hall in Cambr
idge Road. They used to have a lot of dramas there, and that was a cheaper place, it was tuppence, up in the - Paragon was only threepence. Then - then when - of course the bioscope came along, the pictures came along, everywhere was picture palaces. You 
could go where you liked see, see what picture was showing. Charlie Chaplin or who - when he first started you see. When I was young, he was a - only a young man as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were people quite excited by films when they first came out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yes. Yes, y
es. Yes, I saw a film in Whitechapel Road - then - only paid a penny to go in there - and - opposite Whitechapel church and as this bio - like the train came in, so all the people got up and ran out, they thought it was coming on top of 'em. See the train
 
come along, ch-ch-ch-ch-ch - like, see and that was - they thought - thought the train was coming into this here - fairly - a big size - room where you was all sat in side by side. Yeh, all the people got up and run out they thought the train was coming i
n the room to 'em. Yeh, never seen such a thing before like that. Oh yes, they was - good old times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Do you think looking back honestly you would say they were good old days? Rather than bad old days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, people were happy, as far as I was conc
erned, people were happy wasn't they? They wasn't - never had that fear of war on them. You see. The 1914 war came along - that caused a lot of - hardship. Tom, Dick and Harry got slaughtered - down down for nothing which shouldn't have never happened.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 But before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well before that people were generally hard up, you see, the - there was no - two ways about it. It's a different thing, you see - when I was young - a man - a man had decent job, he wouldn't let his wife go to work. Now they got a
 decent job or not they go to work. See when a woman got man - a man got married he kept his wife.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
But she had more children then probably, she couldn't have worked even if she'd wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, no, that's true. But they - that - that may be tru
e, but some did a little bit of - what I call work. But - the average - person today - all go out to work. Not that - so - my mother never went to work after her say her - first couple of children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did she work before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes. My - 
I - my - and I never let my wife go to work. All the time - as soon as I got married to her - and it - of course I was her second husband. But - I never let her go to work. Oh no, I - I always thought I was the breadwinner and I - entitled to keep her. An
d I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Most men really looked upon themselves as the breadwinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, yeh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They didn't want their wives to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
I - I - I meant - to bring some - I found a rent book somewhere that's about - a flat we had in - bottom of the Jamaica
 Street - Dinstan Houses - my mother-in-law lived in Cressey Houses, and I lived in Dunstan. We paid a lot of money, about eight shillings a week - for that flat, I think that's about - four pound odd now, ten, four pound ten a week. Yes, you see, well - 
it was different. I - I always considered when - when I got married I wouldn't let my wife go to work and - I kept her, I said, you've got enough work to do - without going to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did your father feel like that as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He never - he never said
 nothing did he. But he never give up hardly any money did he. What could he give up if he earnt say - twenty-five shillings a week they give up a pound he thought he was giving up as - fortune. You see. Whereas where I - went to work you see - I earnt a 
few bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Did your life become easier in your whole family once the various brothers started working and bringing money into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well, you - you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were things changed very much?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They all went away at separate times you see. They 
didn't stop together, it was only me and my next brother - there was three of us left, Joe, the eldest one, Joe, he - he got married. He got eight children I think he had. And he got married. And of course as I say -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did he do, what sort of job did he have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He - he worked - he had a - he was in a greengrocery business, and he started selling rabbits, and he sold rabbits for years, and then the '14 war came along and then that windled away. Then he went to work - I think he finished up on the
 Borough Council working. He was a - a - more or less a gambler, he done all his money in in - betting. Yeh, they - there's lots of people even today a doing the same. They go in the betting shops you see - it - they're encouraged to bet today. When I was
 
a - young man - or even up 'til - this - say a few years ago, you were - you had to be afraid to put a bet on because you didn't know if the policeman's going to pinch your - for - lock you up for - and charge you. You was caught with a bet on you you got
 found about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Can I ask you about what other members of your family did, it's very interesting to follow what happened to families. Your oldest brother was in the greengrocery, what about the next one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 My - my next - my next brother, he - he - h
e was in - he - he's in Wales now, he's alive, he - drove Haig about, Douglas Haig. He was a - he was a - Staff Sergeant, 'course when he joined the Army you see, in the 1914 war there wasn't hardly any cars about. And he - there was a - a motor driver - 
a
 - a Rolls driver who could drive a - powerful car, like him, he was - he was apprenticed as Straker and Squires, the - big people. And he was a proper mechanic. Besides being a motor driver he knew why a - a car - worked, you understand. That was the - b
enefit of a - them people then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 That was quite rare in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, well - he was in the Army, in two days he was in France. Then as I say, he became Haig's - Staff Sergeant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Did he go on doing this with cars when he came out of the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Then when he came back he went back to - to Wales, his governor was a Colonel in the Army, apart from being a colliery owner, see he was a colliery owner and he - he - he - had a little - cottage there, being a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 chauffeur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  to him, and instead of him 
going back to him you see he started a - car business on his own. Repairs and all all that, a garage, him and he took a partner and they worked there at Porthcawl for years 'til he retired.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about the next one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And, the next one - was Ted, 
he was on the railway, he was a - up at Manchester, he - he was sent to Manchester industrial school for playing truant here in - in the East End a that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of thing did he do on the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 He was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 supervisor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 . He was a what - he w
as - he was also one of these - you know, mouthpieces for the union up there. He used to travel backwards and forwards from Manchester to Euston, see, and - I know - 'course every time I've been with - with him at - to see him off - all the drivers and al
l the - staff of the railways all - you know, saluted him as a - you know, the - they knew him, see. He was a union representative for 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about your next brother who came after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Sid. Then Sid came, he - he - of course he - he serves -
 he was a carman and he - finished up - working in the docks, when the depression came you know. When they started to get rid of horses you know - he went to work in the docks. He was a - oh he was a character as well. Everybody knew him in the East End. 
See, he was a - he was a - a strong union man for the dock people. Like the dock workers. 'Course he - he come out with - without - now they come out they get hand outs of thousands of pounds now. They got nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When he retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh, they got 
- just a couple of shillings a week I think they got. These people get hand outs and pensions you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Were you next after him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yes, yes, I'm the last - youngest brother I was of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 So there's five boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Them five, yeh, well 
there was a - two or three had passed away. You see, I remember - I was the youngest son, see and - in the fourteen war the whole five of us was in the service. We joined up, well - Sid, that one next to me, that one I just mentioned, he was a - he done s
e
ven years in the Army, like a - he was what they call - oh, he - three years he done. What did I say, oh no, he was a special reservist, he was - he done his training, and then he came home, he was on - on a - it was a - a system they had that time, you c
o
uld join - do - so many - months in the Army, and then you go on what they call special reserve. And he was - doing his last - he was doing his last training when the '14 war broke out, 'course he didn't come back did he, they kept him. Yeh, and he was a 
special reservist. He was a corporal in the - Royal Fusiliers. Full corporal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And you said your sisters were all dressmakers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes. They - they - them sisters - there's only one left of them, there's two gone - and there's one left - she lives ov
er at Morden in Surrey. They were all dressmakers. Of course that was the East End trade that time. Bootmaking and dressmaking and uphol - and all them trades was here in the East End you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about who your sisters married, what sort of occupations did they have?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
One sister, he's a lorry driver who she married, the youngest one was a lorry driver. And - one - one - he worked for - Kierley and Tonges, he was a - war reserve policeman during the war. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What's Kierley and Tonges?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They're - wholesale grocers. They are the international tea stores. They -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did he do there for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
He was a warehouseman in the warehouse see. 'Cos they had vast warehouses here at Whitechapel, back of Whitechapel station, as you get in
 the train at Whitechapel you can see it. That - it's all been pulled down now though. Of course when I was there during the war, that was the area I was in - as air raid warden. My area there. Whitechapel - from one - one to four posts I belonged to. Oh 
-
 four post was Petticoat Lane, all that area, this side, down Commercial Street and then - Hanbury Street and - Whitechapel Road right to the corner of Cambridge Road there was the - old area, you see, and - and I knew more or less - everybody on that are
a
. Because you - you learnt to go round every day, you know people by sight and you knew by their number. You could tell - you - funny things what you learnt - during the war, to keep your eyes open, to be observant and - little things like - you knew wher
e
 a fire hydrant was in the dark, say a - a strange fireman come along, he'd want to know wouldn't he. And you - you could tell him. Her you are, there it is. You knew where every - pillarbox was, every alarm, everything. You knew everything like that, you
 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What did your third sister's husband do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 She didn't - the third sister didn't marry. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about your children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 They - one child had and died, the other one never had any children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What sort of occupations did your own children do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Who? Oh - the boy, he - he was a - he went in the Army. And then he - he - he then went in the police, then he become a taxi driver. And - the girl, she - she married a chap but - never had any children, but the boy's got - four children, an
d ten great-grandchildren we got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 When you were a boy, what sort of furniture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Never had a lot did they. Never had a lot. Now if a person - we never had - I can never remember - only seeing a - a bed in the room and - couple of chairs - and that
's all. Table. And - no - no elaborate furniture. You see - today a person's got - a fridge. A wireless. A television. They'd got electric light. They've got - heaters to heat the fire instead of having coal and coke like we had. If we never had coal and 
c
oke we went and found old leather and - old boots to burn for firing, see that was our - fuel, didn't cost nothing. Firewood you had - collected it. It's easier to get firewood today than it was when I was a boy, because nobody wants the firewood today, s
o
 there's no demand for it, so you have plenty. You go up the main road you see the boxes laying there from the fruit - along Whitechapel road there, well when I was young you'd have to pay a few coppers for each box. Well now you get 'em given to you. Unl
ess we went to the market like Leadenhall market and - took 'em away from the shopkeepers there, they was only glad to - clear 'em out for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about carpets and curtains, what sort of things would people have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh carpets - today they're - t
hey're - everybody's got carpets, there - that time they never had it, they had oilcloth didn't they. They'd have a bit of carpet it was true. They'd buy it - secondhand as a rule. But - mats - they'd have a mat at the door or - inside, a couple of mats -
 in the passage, some people, some never - never had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would furniture be bought secondhand quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, you could buy furniture secondhand always. And then - new - I remember - them Windsor chairs they called them, you know, them strong c
hairs, last you a lifetime. I've got chairs - in my house - they must be getting on for a hundred years old. But you can stand on 'em and work on 'em and do anything you like on 'em. But it - what I'm coming to is this, they didn't cost about four and six
 each that time. Less than that. You could buy a - four - Windsor chairs - I think they used to work out about two and ninepence or three and six each the most. And you painted 'em up how you like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would these be bought from a carpenter?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 No, fro
m these here - furniture shops they have 'em in the window they would. Yeh, they was very - chairs was very cheap at that - Windsor chairs. And that's the finest chair ever a household can have. I - I'll explain why. If you go on a chair like that, if you
 
want to stand on it you're liable to break your leg, or your back. But you could get on them old Windsor chairs, and you still can - stand on a Windsor chair - and you're as solid and - and - on a - on a ladder. I - I've got a - one - that all the childre
n
 that I've - when they've got married I've ask - told 'em, no standing on cane bottom chairs - or them sort of chairs, I've give 'em all a chair, I have. Painted 'em up silver and white and all Lord knows what. That's - if you want to - fit a - light up t
h
ere, stand on the chair, if you haven't got steps. But don't go on them other chairs. I've got little chairs sawn down from Windsor chairs - short ones about that - a foot - high. Now you get on that, now, even now - I get on there, I know when I'm on it 
it's solid, it's not going to shift, and it's not going to let me down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was most furniture good quality or could you get very cheap badly made stuff?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, there was good quality furniture. But it - things is different prices today
, the - prices are outstanding today aren't they. When you take a chair like that for instance, look - they want about six - six pound, five or six pound for a chair like that. Well - when you reckon like that - you could get four for less than a pound co
u
ldn't you. Windsor chairs that would outlast - thousand of them. You - you - there's no - and some of them - them old fashioned - workers that made - chairs, they was - proper mechanics. But what did they earn, they only earned about thirty bob a week if 
t
hey earnt that did they. See. They were proper - they're cabinet makers. Good - good old - cabinets they were. Used to see 'em with their - making these stools and in the fields with the old - knives what they used, crude looking tools, but they were expe
r
ts with it. I knew a man, an old man, he made brewers dray wheels. Only the wheels. All the brewers drays were a big firm here in the East End - and they were named Bonlacks, and they used to give him this hub, the block, this here - the hub to start with
,
 and these here pieces of spokes, wood for the spokes. And the ferrals. And he used to cut them out, them wheels, fit them in the hubs, then he'd put the ferrals on, and they were sent away to the - blacksmith, they put 'em on a big steel plate like on th
e
 ground it is, and they put the tyre on - hot the tyre - hot the tyre then they put it on the wood and they burn it on. That's how they used to do it. Now them wheels last a hundred years or more, easy. And that old man, he - he - most of them old heavy d
r
ays what - don't see 'em now - them old heavy wheels, he made 'em. And he was a foreigner. He was a proper old - country - from the - country you know, in - Russia where he come from. Him - he made those wheels. For Mann and Crosswoods, was the local brew
e
rs where he mostly made the old - wheels for. He made a - he'd start off making - cutting the whole in the box, you know this - and cut his spokes out, say he had - I forget now how many spokes went round, and he'd fit in them that there, on like a - then
 they'd put the ferrals on, then they used to be sent away to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 tired}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
. Now that - that man - that - that man worked day and night for that - for years, all on his own. There was no one could - they reckoned, could compete with him. He was an expert at that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose Mann and Crosslands employed a lot of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh yeh, they did, yeh they did, still do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Dud they then as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, yes, they still did. You see, then they - they had to have a - a man like that making these wheels because they had - such a lot of vehicles being used.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 I suppose they had people to make barrels as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they make - they - they - they're not made now, they don't have them. They've got metal barrels now haven't they. Oh yes, this - labour 
is changing. You see - all those horsekeepers what they had - during the war when I was a warden - a bomb dropped here, Cambridge Road here, near Whitechapel Station, killed a lot of their horses and smashed all the stables up, and - I saw a lot of them h
o
rses, I helped to tie up a few of 'em - that was out in the street, you know, run helter skelter - when that bomb dropped in Cambridge Road on them stables. Yeh, well knew that - you see they had - they had farriers working there regular, blacksmiths as y
ou call them, blacksmiths, they had harness makers - employed - everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 These were all skilled men weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes. You - you - they didn't have amateurs to look after 'em. They - if you went to get a job that time you had to show - that you knew what you was doing before they employed you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Would they employ a lot of unskilled men as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, yes, they'd get - they used to get jobs. See, well - in most of the jobs years ago as far as I remember, a lot of it was recommendat
ion. Say I worked there at the brewery, I'd say to the foreman, I've got a friend of mine who could do with a - job. Well fetch him along they'd say see. And if you got - if he works like you do or if you're - like - then we'll be satisfied. See, as long 
a
s a man pulled his weight he was a - kept, you see - years ago - most manual workers, when they got a job, were given a - job on what they - they was physically able to do, you know what I mean, if it was - it was mostly - slapping - pulling yourself - bo
d
y about, and if you wasn't fit for that you couldn't get employment. You see it's no good - asking a weak man to carry a sack of coals is it. You see, and that was very hard job. A sack of coals was two hundredweight. Well when you got a sack of coal on y
o
ur back you've got to walk say fifty yards with it, upstairs and all that business which we had to, is - a - a - a weak man couldn't take that job on so you had no competition from him did you. See, so - them - fit men - like even in the docks - if a man 
couldn't - pull his weight, and they had to work hard that time, now it's all done with the container, they - put the hooks on it and away it - is - hardly - a lot of the jobs is not done -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Men must have been quite worn out if they did this heavy physical work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, yes, they were, yes, they were - yeh, yeh. And I've seen my dad like even - I used to get up five in the morning - on average see. Monday to Saturday, that's six days isn't it. Twelve hours a day was his day's work, before you could h
ave - earn a penny overtime. You had to do twelve hours work before you come on the - on the overtime basis. Six o'clock you start in the morning, six o'clock you started on overtime. But some people didn't get overtime, they had to - it all went in with 
t
heir day's work. I - I was - I was doing work with my dad in - I'd been - doing journey work three times a - a week, that's every other day a journey. That would bring you home say one and two in the morning. Never got no overtime for that. You just took 
i
t and that a matter of - course. See, 'til the unions start coming along, just - previous to war the unions started - coming along, they had a - a union here in the East End, was called the London Carman's Trade Union. And then that went to the National U
n
ion of Vehicle Workers. It's like it is now the General - General Transport Workers now. Well I - I remember some of them early - starters that run that union - just - ordinary men with a little - gift of the gab you see, but it - it - it's - everywhere y
o
u went after a certain time - everywhere you went you had to be a union man, otherwise you wouldn't be employed. See, and the dockers who worked hand in glove with the - the - transport workers, so they respected one another you see. And that's how it - i
t went on, got on - strong footing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Even individual Carmen, one or two who worked for a small firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, if you - say you was on a small firm and you wasn't in a union - they want to be nasty any time they wouldn't - let you be in - served in the docks or anything like that. See. That could cause a strike that would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How did employers react?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well they'd - tell 'em, you'll have to join the union, see, after a time, see, at first they - took no notice but - after a time I was working whe
re men - didn't want to join the union. Well no notice was taken of 'em. But if the dockers say no union men won't be served, if you ain't got a ticket - you can't come here. Well won't have no blacklegs coming in here you see, no scabs they used to call 
'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was your father a union man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, he - well he had to be didn't he. He was compelled - and they was all compelled to be. You had to be. I - I become a - a chairman of the union - as a young man, and - then - secretary - I worked with, he was a - a car man as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 This was with the Carman's Union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yes, the Car men. Yeah. And I - I was a - used to have a meeting every week in a local pub see, where our branch was, and - and - when anything went wrong - you knew who Tom, Dick and Ha
rry was see, in the firm. See I was a chairman and the secretary, I had - between us we knew everybody that worked at the firm, say there was three or four hundred people working there that time, we knew 'em all. They - they - some come up the branch and 
some didn't. But you never - they never - took much notice as long as they got - they paid their fees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
On the whole were people interested in union activities like meetings, union meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well - some were and some weren't. It was a - to me when
 they first started it was a general booze up. It was always in a pub where they held the branch you see. And they were in the pub. - they'd have a - a room in a pub for their meeting place, and there'd be a meeting see. There was any complaints, see - yo
u could - put 'em before the secretary or - so and so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was there a minimum wage established by this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, it was - a coming along - I'd say - just about the '14 war came along and knocked everything a bit - sky high. But of course after the
 war - in the - the firms started reading out who they wanted to weed out - you see - everything - become level again. And then 'course - just after the '14 war - motor started coming in hand. See - you could count motors - that - a big firm a I worked fo
r
 they had a Foden lorry - with solid tyres, steam lorry, they were the first big heavy motors - and - then they had a - a little motor come along. About a ton van. But now - everywhere you look is motors. That big firm I worked for I say they had two - tw
o
 - two motors, the Foden and that little - little run about van. And - now it's all motors. And everything'll come to a stoppage soon you'll see. With the motors. Well it's coming to a stoppage now I think. Every now and then there's a bridge breaks down,
 you read in the paper, there's thousands of motors stranded, blocked up. They can't get out and they can't get in. It's - a funny thing this motor - business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 You say the roads weren't so congested even with hundreds of horses around?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Oh no, you could go - you didn't know such a thing as congestion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Weren't the streets rather dirty though?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes. Well they were swept regular though weren't they. Oh yes, the streets were swept. The Borough Councils had workmen, and the workmen that ti
me - was honest to do workmen. They were - then they swept a street. Now you walk along a street today, I - I've seen in my simple way - weeds growing which a Borough Council man wouldn't allow - he'd pull his fingers and pull that weed out, but not today
,
 they leave 'em. They don't know they're there, they - they don't even see 'em. Even when I come by my little garden there, on the front of our window, I see any - dandelion or - anything growing - that's starting with the grass now, fresh grass, I pull i
t straight out. Them - little - daisies and one thing and another, but - if everybody had that same idea, these weeds wouldn't be about, thistles and that all over the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Was that a poorly paid job, a road sweeper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Well he wasn't - he was a B
orough worker he was a respected - person, he - well the roadsweepers used that time work in gangs, they'd be about - four or five men with a gang, go up one street and down another, but they were swept. They were - but you go now look - this morning the 
m
an came here, he works - he's a porter, his wages is say about - I say about thirty pound a week, easy. And he just - five minutes after he's gone the paper and that is all what he's put out in the main road. Instead of picking it up and putting it in the
 dustbin, he's put it out into the main road and it's blow back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 What about refuse collection, how often when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Well, they used to come - they used to come twice a week when I was a boy, the dustmen did, with the old horses an
d carts. But - now they - well they come twice a week now but - they used to at that time with the horse and carts come, and then they used to - when they was - there was two dustmen see, two carts, one they filled up one and while he was away they was fi
l
ling the other one up. See, and then when he come back he drove away and he brought the empty one back. They was like - have them dust vans now. Single horses they was mostly. In - they had 'em all over the place here in the City. It - it - each district 
had its own dustmen you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 How about mail, how many deliveries a day would there be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh they used to be late deliveries with the mail, it was all day long. Early in the morning and late at night, they used to be delivering letters in the dark. 
Yeh, of a night time have the postman come round. In the dark, they don't do that now. You see - everybody's - become what I call gangsters so - they don't go out with the mail late at night. Yeh, the postman - used to have - what do you call it - oil lam
p
s round their waist. When I - when I - yeh, they never had - elec - that electric batteries. Just ordinary oil lamp - like the policeman did. A policeman had oil lamp and all. Used to - turn it off from the top, there was a - a domed top and he used to tu
r
n it off, that was ordinary oil. See then, the night. duty policemen had a different coat on - to the day duty. That there was their night duty coat over the oil. To protect it. They used to use them old coats for that purpose. Yes, that was only ordinary
 oil they used, oil lamps. Of course when the electric - batteries came along they was - well advanced.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 And a postman did the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
The postman as well. They had the oil - lamps. Oh I've seen it all change. See, want - want threepenno'rth of gib
lets or fish, and then they - they give you all the pieces of fish - for a couple of coppers that time, to feed all the family. I've seen - one firm used to sell only - English meat. No frozen meat. They were shipping butchers. And we used to buy a rump b
o
ne off 'em after they'd cut the steaks off and for their hotels and restaurants. And they used to charge you threepence. It was a - like a three cornered bone, like a - what they call the whole leg - hopping feet, and there'd be enough meat and suet fat o
n there to make a beef steak pudding for the whole family for threepence, English meat. Would be all right today wouldn't it. Feed a family of about eight - for threepence. And then - then - when that bone was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10766789\charrsid66970 chopped}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970  up and boiled - they had soup or and - whole basin of soup out of it mum'd make 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Do you think your mother was a good manager?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Oh yes, well she - she was learnt that wasn't she. It come - it comes to you see. Circumstances make you expert - at things, you see, it was the same as m
e. I learnt to - fiddle as I call it, and - go along life like that. You see, and then I - when I was - when I got on I had a lot of friends - I used to - boys - worked in Billingsgate Market, had a few boxer friends see and - used to go there and they us
e
d to bring home that time - samples from them you see, what they give me. And then if I took any - repairs for 'em - I'd go down there and take 'em their foot wear and - they'd - send me back a - box of kippers or something like that to take home, or a bo
x
 of roe. Yes. Don't get those things now. Come in handy they would. Yeh, very often I had - I still - if I wanted to - still go there I could still go and find - friends there. Oh yes, I was a respected boy. Yeh, they got a - one - friend of mine, he's a 
-
 he's managing the car park there now, he's - a - he was a good boxer, George. George Reeves, he - he fought most of the best middle weights and welterweights here and - and I used to spare with him a lot see, and - we were great friends. Yeh, well - what
 
they call a wheel within a wheel, you help one another. I - I done a trick there one holiday Monday, I went there - in the war. And - I think I took 'em a couple of pair of shoes there - or boots what I'd mended for 'em, and there was a - my friend - he w
o
rked for a firm, only had one box of fish come up. And - I said to him, is that all that's come up today Ted? He says, yes. Well in this box of fish was two big cod and in the middle was a small cod. I suppose the - the small one weighed about - six to ei
g
ht pound day. But the two big ones filled this here long box up. So an old Jewish man came up, and he says to me - do you think they'll sell that - that fish? I said, you won't buy that. He says, why not? I says, you wouldn't pay five pound for that box o
f
 fish would you? Why not, he says. So he says, I - I says, I'll speak to the - friend of mine for you. So I went and told this Teddy. His name was - Allen. I said, Ted, there's an old boy there, he - he's willing to give a fiver for them couple of fish. D
o
n't want the little one. He's - that's for me. So - he says, right, good. See - so he paid this money for them two fish, and he paid - the porterage, they had to pay a - shilling or so porterage. And - he had two big long bags, like mat baskets as they ca
l
l 'em, you've seen the little mat baskets what they make plaited, and he had two long ones, he had one cod in each, and he - he had a taxi waiting out the back to take 'em away. And I spoke to him. I said - how do you make that pay? 'Course I - you know -
 
tapping him. So he said, well - he said, I've got a club. He said, I fry that fish, he says, in big slices of cod, and I cut 'em up and I charge 'em half a crown a piece. See? From the small slices he'd get half a crown, the big slices he'd get a dollar s
e
e. Cut - it'd be cut in half. Fried cod in this club he was a serve in that club. Of course that time it was good money. So I thought to myself, high, he - he's earning a few pound out of that then. Yeh, they was nice big long cod you know. And he was tha
t time charging half a crown a small piece of fish. 'Course now they charge five bob - for a piece like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 It was a lot of money then wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 
Yeh, it was a lot of money then. And - and that's why I told - Teddy, I said, Ted, he's told me h
e gets - half a crown a piece in the club, he was in the gambling club see, of a night time they'd want a bit of fried fish, half a crown or - and they got - they had no limit to their money those gamblers and that's how it goes. Well anyhow I had my cod 
f
or nothing, they were satisfied, they could have got fiver for the fish, the two porters. I think the guv - they had to give the guv'nor something like - thirty-five bob for that. They give the guv'nor thirty-five bob for that fish, with the shilling port
e
rage. So they had the rest of the fiver between 'em. And I had a fish for nothing, that cod, lovely big cod I - about six to eight pound easy it was. I know it was - you know, a - nice one. Enough food, all of us over the weekend you know. Oh yes. Yes, I 
said, you won't give five pound for that fish and he - he says, I - I will. 'Course he - there was no one else had fish, it was on a - like a holiday Monday - in the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7229527 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Food was short in the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16733626 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2968889\charrsid66970 Yeh. Oh yes, things was different then.
\par }}